\b PROLOG: A YEAR BEFORE\par
\b0\f1\tab\par
\tab\f0 THE MAN from Earth came to a decision. It had been slow in coming and developing, but it was here.\par
\tab It had been weeks since he had felt the comforting deck of his ship and the cool, dark blanket of space about it. Originally, he had intended a quick report to the local office of the Interstellar Spatio-analytic Bureau and a quicker retreat to space. Instead, he had been held here.\par
\tab It was almost like a prison.\par
\tab He drained his tea and looked at the man across the table. He said, \ldblquote I\rquote m not staying any longer.\rdblquote\par
\tab\par
\tab The other man came to a decision. It had been slow in coming and developing, but it was here. He would need time, much more time. The response to the first letters had been nil. They might have fallen into a star for all they had accomplished.\par
\tab That had been no more than he had expected, or, rather, no less. But it was only the first move.\par
\tab It was certain that, while future moves developed, he could not allow the man from Earth to squirm out of reach. He fingered the smooth black rod in his pocket.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote You don\rquote t appreciate the delicacy of the problem.\rdblquote\par
\tab\par
\tab The Earthman said, \ldblquote What\rquote s delicate about the destruction of a planet? I want you to broadcast the details to all of Sark; to everyone on the planet.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote We can\rquote t do that. You know it would mean panic.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You said at first you would do it.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote ve thought it over and it just isn\rquote t practical.\rdblquote\par
\tab The Earthman turned to a second grievance. \ldblquote The representative of the I.S.B. hasn\rquote t arrived.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I know it. They are busy organizing proper procedures for this crisis. Another day or two.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Another day or two! It\rquote s always another day or two! Are they so busy they can\rquote t spare me a moment? They haven\rquote t even seen my calculations.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I have offered to bring your calculations to them. You don\rquote t want me to.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And I still don\rquote t. They can come to me or I can go to them.\rdblquote  He added violently, \ldblquote I don\rquote t think you believe me. You don\rquote t believe Florina will be destroyed.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I believe you.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You don\rquote t. I know you don\rquote t. I see you don\rquote t. You\rquote re humoring me. You can\rquote t understand my data. You\rquote re not a Spatio-analyst. I don\rquote t even think you\rquote re who you say you are. Who are you?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You\rquote re getting excited.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, I am. Is that surprising? Or are you just thinking, Poor devil, Space has him. You think I\rquote m crazy.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Nonsense.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Sure you do. That\rquote s why I want to see the I.S.B. They\rquote ll know if I\rquote m crazy or not. They\rquote ll know.\rdblquote\par
\tab The other man remembered his decision. He said, \ldblquote Now you\rquote re not feeling well. I\rquote m going to help you.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No, you\rquote re not,\rdblquote  shouted the Earthman hysterically, \ldblquote because I\rquote m going to walk out. If you want to stop me, kill me, except that you won\rquote t dare. The blood of a whole world of people will be on your hands if you do.\rdblquote\par
\tab The other man began shouting, too, to make himself heard. \ldblquote I won\rquote t kill you. Listen to me, I won\rquote t kill you. There\rquote s no need to kill you.\rdblquote\par
\tab The Earthman said, \ldblquote You\rquote ll tie me up. You\rquote ll keep me here. Is that what you\rquote re thinking? And what will you do when the I.S.B. starts looking for me? I\rquote m supposed to send in regular reports, you know.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The Bureau knows you\rquote re safely with me.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Do they? I wonder if they know I\rquote ve reached the planet at all? I wonder if they received my original message?\rdblquote  The Earthman was giddy. His limbs felt stiff.\par
\tab The other man stood up. It was obvious to him that his decision had come none too soon. He walked slowly about the long table, toward the Earthman.\par
\tab He said soothingly, \ldblquote It will be for your own good.\rdblquote  He took the black rod from his pocket.\par
\tab The Earthman croaked, \ldblquote That\rquote s a psychic probe.\rdblquote  His words were slurred, and when he tried to rise, his arms and legs barely quivered.\par
\tab He said, between teeth that were clenching in rigor, \ldblquote Drugged!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Drugged!\rdblquote  agreed the other man. \ldblquote Now look, I won\rquote t hurt you. It\rquote s difficult for you to understand the true delicacy of the matter while you\rquote re so excited and anxious about it. I\rquote ll just remove the anxiety. Only the anxiety.\rdblquote\par
\tab The Earthman could no longer talk. He could only sit there. He could only think numbly, Great Space, I\rquote ve been drugged. He wanted to shout and scream and run, but he couldn\rquote t.\par
\tab The other had reached the Earthman now. He stood there, looking down at him. The Earthman looked up. His eyeballs could still move.\par
\tab The psychic probe was a self-contained unit. Its wires needed only to be fixed to the appropriate places on the skull. The Earthman watched in panic until his eye muscles froze. He did not feel the fine sting as the sharp, thin leads probed through skin and flesh to make contact with the sutures of his skull bones.\par
\tab He yelled and yelled in the silence of his mind. He cried, No, you don\rquote t understand. It\rquote s a planet full of people. Don\rquote t you see that you can\rquote t take chances with hundreds of millions of living people?\par
\tab The other man\rquote s words were dim and receding, heard from the other end of a long, windy tunnel. \ldblquote It won\rquote t hurt you. In another hour you\rquote ll feel well, really well. You\rquote ll be laughing at all this with me.\rdblquote\par
\tab The Earthman felt the thin vibration against his skull and then that faded too.\par
\tab Darkness thickened and collapsed about him. Some of it never lifted again. It took a year for even parts of it to lift.\par
\par
