\b THREE: The Librarian\par
\b0\f1\tab\par
\tab\par
\tab\f0 THEY LEFT the diamagnetic scooter in a scooter-cubby outside the City limits. Scooters were rare in the City and Terens had no wish to attract unnecessary attention. He thought for a savage moment of those of the Upper City with their diamagnetic ground-cars and anti-gray gyros. But that was the Upper City. It was different.\par
\tab Rik waited for Terens to lock the cubby and fingerprint-seal it. He was dressed in a new one-piece suit and felt a little uncomfortable. Somewhat reluctantly he followed the Townman under the first of the tall bridgelike structures that supported the Upper City.\par
\tab On Florina, all other cities had names, but this one was simply the \ldblquote City.\rdblquote  The workers and peasants who lived in it and around it were considered lucky by the rest of the planet. In the City there were better doctors and hospitals, more factories and more liquor stores, even a few dribbles of very mild luxury. The inhabitants themselves were somewhat less enthusiastic. They lived in the shadow of the Upper City.\par
\tab The Upper City was exactly what the name implied, for the City was double, divided rigidly by a horizontal layer of fifty square miles of cementalloy resting upon some twenty thousand steel-girdered pillars. Below in the shadow were the \ldblquote natives.\rdblquote  Above, in the sun, were the Squires. It was difficult to believe in the Upper City that the planet of its location was Florina. The population was almost exclusively Sarkite in nature, together with a sprinkling of patrollers. They were the upper class in all literalness.\par
\tab Terens knew his way. He walked quickly, avoiding the stares of passers-by, who surveyed his Townman clothing with a mixture of envy and resentment. Rik\rquote s shorter legs made his gait less dignified as he tried to keep up. He did not remember very much from his only other visit to the City. It seemed so different now. Then it had been cloudy. Now the sun was out, pouring through the spaced openings in the cementalloy above to form strips of light that made the intervening space all the darker. They plunged through the bright strips in a rhythmic, almost hypnotic fashion.\par
\tab Oldsters sat on wheeled chairs in the strips, absorbing the warmth and moving as the strip moved. Sometimes they fell asleep and would remain behind in the shade, nodding in their chairs until the squeaking of the wheels when they shifted position woke them. Occasionally mothers nearly blocked the strips with their carriageci offspring.\par
\tab Terens said, \ldblquote Now, Rik, stand up straight. We\rquote re going up.\rdblquote  \par
\tab He was standing before a structure that filled the space between four square-placed pillars, and from ground to Upper City.\par
\tab Rik said, \ldblquote I\rquote m scared.\rdblquote\par
\tab Rik could guess what the structure was. It was an elevator that lifted to the upper level.\par
\tab These were necessary, of course. Production was below, but consumption was above. Basic chemicals and raw food staples were shipped into Lower City, but finished plastic ware and fine meals were matters for Upper City. Excess population spawned below; maids, gardeners, chauffeurs, construction laborers were used above.\par
\tab Terens ignored Rik\rquote s expression of fright. He was amazed that his own heart beat so violently. Not fright, of course. Rather a fierce satisfaction that he was going up. He would step all over that sacred cementalloy, stamp on it, scuff his dirt upon it. He could do that as a Townman. Of course he was still only a Florinian native to the Squires, but he was a Townman and he could step on the cementalloy whenever he pleased.\par
\tab Galaxy, he hated them!\par
\tab He stopped himself, drew a firm breath and signaled for the elevator. There was no use thinking hate. He had been on Sark for many years; on Sark itself, the center and breeding place of the Squires. He had learned to bear in silence. He ought not forget what he had learned now. Of all times, not now.\par
\tab He heard the whir of the elevator settling at the lower level, and the entire wall facing him dropped into its slot.\par
\tab The native who operated the elevator looked disgusted. \ldblquote Just two of you.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Just two,\rdblquote  said Terens, stepping in. Rik followed.\par
\tab The operator made no move to restore the fallen wall to its original position. He said, \ldblquote Seems to me you guys could wait for the two o\rquote clock load and move with it. I ain\rquote t supposed to run this thing up and down for no two guys.\rdblquote  He spat carefully, making sure that the sputum hit lower-level concrete and not the floor of his elevator.\par
\tab He went on, \ldblquote Where\rquote s your employment tickets?\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens said, \ldblquote I\rquote m a Townman. Can\rquote t you see it by my clothes?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Clothes don\rquote t mean nothing. Listen, you think I\rquote m risking my job because you maybe picked up some uniform somewheres? Where\rquote s your card?\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens, without another word, presented the standard document-folder all natives had to carry at all times: registration number, employment certificate, tax receipts. It was open to the crimson of his Townman\rquote s license. The operator scanned it briefly.\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, maybe you picked that up, too, but that\rquote s not my business. You got it and I pass you, though Townman\rquote s just a fancy name for a native to my way of figgering. What about the other guy?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote He\rquote s in my charge,\rdblquote  said Terens. \ldblquote He can come with me, or shall we call a patroller and check into the rules?\rdblquote\par
\tab It was the last thing Terens wanted but he suggested it with suitable arrogance.\par
\tab\ldblquote Awrright! Y\rquote don\rquote t have to get sore.\rdblquote  The elevator wall moved up, and with a lurch the elevator climbed. The operator mumbled direfully under his breath.\par
\tab Terens smiled tightly. It was almost inevitable. Those who worked directly for the Squires were only too glad to identify themselves with the rulers and make up for their real inferiority by a tighter adherence to the rules of segregation, a harsh and haughty attitude toward their fellows. They were the \ldblquote uppermen\rdblquote  for whom the other Florinians reserved their particular hate, unalloyed by the carefully taught awe they felt for the Squires.\par
\tab The vertical distance traveled was thirty feet, but the door opened again to a new world. Like the native cities of Sark, Upper City was laid out with a particular eye to color. Individual structures, whether dwelling places or public buildings, were inset in an intricate multicolored mosaic which, close at hand, was a meaningless jumble, but at a distance of a hundred yards took on a soft clustering of hues that melted and changed with the angle of view.\par
\tab\ldblquote Come on, Rik,\rdblquote  said Terens.\par
\tab Rik was staring wide-eyed. Nothing alive and growing! Just stone and color in huge masses. He had never known houses could be so huge. Something stirred momentarily in his mind. For a second the hugeness was not so strange. . . And then the memory closed down again.\par
\tab A ground-car flashed by.\par
\tab\ldblquote Are those Squires?\rdblquote  Rik whispered.\par
\tab There had been time for only a glance. Hair close-cropped, wide, flaring sleeves of glossy, solid colors ranging from blue to violet, knickers of a velvety appearance and long, sheer hose that gleamed as if it were woven of thin copper wire. They wasted no glance at Rik and Terens.\par
\tab\ldblquote Young ones,\rdblquote  said Terens. He had not seen them at such close quarters since he left Sark. On Sark they were bad enough but at least they had been in place. Angels did not fit here, thirty feet over Hell. Again he squirmed to suppress a useless tremble of hatred.\par
\tab A two-man flatcar hissed up behind them. It was a new model that had built-in air controls. At the moment it was skimming smoothly two inches above surface, its gleaming flat bottom curled upward at all edges to cut air resistance. Still, the slicing of air against its lower surface sufficed to produce the characteristic hiss which meant \ldblquote patrollers.\rdblquote\par
\tab They were large, as all patrollers were; broad-faced, flatcheeked, long, straight black hair, light brown in complexion. To the natives, all patrollers looked alike. The glossy black of their uniforms, enhanced as they were by the startling silver of strategically placed buckles and ornamental buttons, depressed the importance of the face and encouraged the impression of likeness still more.\par
\tab One patroller was at the controls. The other leaped out lightly over the shallow rim of the car.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote Folder!\rdblquote  stared mechanically and momentarily at it and flipped it back at Terens. \ldblquote Your business here.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I intend consulting the library, Officer. It is my privilege.\rdblquote  The patroller turned to Rik. \ldblquote What about you?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I--\rdblquote  began Rik.\par
\tab\ldblquote He is my assistant,\rdblquote  interposed Terens.\par
\tab\ldblquote He has no Townman privileges,\rdblquote  said the patroller.\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote ll be responsible for him.\rdblquote\par
\tab The patroller shrugged. \ldblquote It\rquote s your lookout. Townmen have privileges, but they\rquote re not Squires. Remember that, boy.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, Officer. By the way, could you direct me to the library?\rdblquote  \par
\tab The patroller directed him, using the thin, deadly barrel of a needle-gun to indicate direction. From their present angle, the library was a blotch of brilliant vermilion deepening into crimson toward the upper stories. As they approached, the crimson crept downward.\par
\tab Rik said with sudden vehemence, \ldblquote I think it\rquote s ugly.\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens gave him a quick, surprised glance. He had been accustomed to all this on Sark, but he, too, found the garishness of Upper City somewhat vulgar. But then, Upper City was more Sark than Sark itself. On Sark, not all men were aristocrats. There were even poor Sarkites, some scarcely better off than the average Florinian. Here only the top of the pyramid existed, and the library showed that.\par
\tab It was larger than all but a few on Sark itself, far larger than Upper City required, which showed the advantage of cheap labor. Terens paused on the curved ramp that led to the main entrance. The color scheme on the ramp gave the illusion of steps, somewhat disconcerting to Rik, who stumbled, but giving the library the proper air of archaism that traditionally accompanied academic structures.\par
\tab The main hall was large, cold, and all but empty. The librarian behind the single desk it contained looked like a small, somewhat wrinkled pea in a bloated pod. She looked up and half rose.\par
\tab Terens said quickly, \ldblquote I\rquote m a Townman. Special privileges. I am responsible for this native.\rdblquote  He had his papers ready and marched them before him.\par
\tab The librarian seated herself and looked stern. She plucked a metal sliver from a slot and thrust it at Terens. The Townman placed his right thumb firmly upon it. The librarian took the sliver and put it in another slot where a dim violet light shone briefly.\par
\tab She said, \ldblquote Room 242.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Thank you.\rdblquote\par
\tab\par
\tab The cubicles on the second floor had that icy lack of personality that any link in an endless chain would have. Some were filled, their glassite doors frosted and opaque. Most were not.\par
\tab\ldblquote Two forty-two,\rdblquote  said Rik. His voice was squeaky.\par
\tab\ldblquote What\rquote s the matter, Rik?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I don\rquote t know. I feel very excited.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Ever been in a library before?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I don\rquote t know.\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens put his thumb on the round aluminum disk which, five minutes before, had been sensitized to his thumbprint. The clear glass door swung open and, as they stepped within, it closed silently and, as though a blind had been drawn, became opaque.\par
\tab The room was six feet in each direction, without window or adornment. It was lit by the diffuse ceiling glow and ventilated by a forced-air draft. The only contents were a desk that stretched from wall to wall and an upholstered backless bench between it and the door. On the desk were three \ldblquote readers.\rdblquote  Their frosted-glass fronts slanted backward at an angle of thirty degrees. Before each were the various control-dials.\par
\tab\ldblquote Do you know what this is?\rdblquote  Terens sat down and placed his soft, plump hand upon one of the readers.\par
\tab Rik sat down too.\par
\tab\ldblquote Books?\rdblquote  he asked eagerly.\par
\tab\ldblquote Well.\rdblquote  Terens seemed uncertain. \ldblquote This is a library, so your guess doesn\rquote t mean much. Do you know how to work the reader?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No. I don\rquote t think so, Townman.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You\rquote re sure? Think about it a little.\rdblquote\par
\tab Rik tried valiantly. \ldblquote I\rquote m sorry, Townman.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Then I\rquote ll show you. Look! First, you see, there\rquote s this knob, labeled \lquote Catalog\rquote  with the alphabet printed about it. Since we want the encyclopedia first, we\rquote ll turn the knob to E and press downward.\rdblquote\par
\tab He did so and several things happened at once. The frosted glass flared into life and printing appeared upon it. It stood out black on yellow as the ceiling light dimmed. Three smooth panels moved out like so many tongues, one before each reader, and each was centered by a tight light-beam.\par
\tab Terens snapped a toggle switch and the panels moved back into their recesses.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote We won\rquote t be taking notes.\rdblquote\par
\tab Then he went on, \ldblquote Now we can go down the list of E\rquote s by turning this knob.\rdblquote\par
\tab The long line of alphabetized materials, titles, authors, catalog numbers flipped upward, then stopped at the packed column listing the numerous volumes of the encyclopedia.\par
\tab Rik said suddenly, \ldblquote You press the numbers and letters after the book you want on these little buttons and it shows on the screen.\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens turned on him. \ldblquote How do you know? Do you remember that?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Maybe I do. I\rquote m not sure. It just seems the right thing.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, call it an intelligent guess.\rdblquote\par
\tab He punched a letter-number combination. The light on the glass faded, then brightened again. It said: \ldblquote Encyclopedia of Sark, Volume 54, Sol-Spec.\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens said, \ldblquote Now look, Rik, I don\rquote t want to put any ideas in your head, so I won\rquote t tell you what\rquote s in my mind. I just want you to look through this volume and stop at anything that seems familiar. Do you understand?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Good. Now take your time.\rdblquote\par
\tab The minutes passed. Suddenly Rik gasped and sent the dials spinning backward.\par
\tab When he stopped, Terens read the heading and looked pleased. \ldblquote You remember now? This isn\rquote t a guess? You remember?\rdblquote\par
\tab Rik nodded vigorously. \ldblquote It came to me, Townman. Very suddenly.\rdblquote\par
\tab It was the article on Spatio-analysis.\par
\tab\ldblquote I know what it says,\rdblquote  Rik said. \ldblquote You\rquote ll see, you\rquote ll see.\rdblquote  He was having difficulty breathing normally and Terens, for his part, was almost equally excited.\par
\tab\ldblquote See,\rdblquote  said Rik, \ldblquote they always have this part.\rdblquote\par
\tab He read aloud haltingly, but in a manner far more proficient than could be accounted for by the sketchy lessons in reading he had received from Valona. The article said:\par
\tab\ldblquote It is not surprising that the Spatio-analyst is by temperament an introverted and, often enough, maladjusted individual. To devote the greater part of one\rquote s adult life to the lonely recording of the terrible emptiness between the stars is more than can be asked of someone entirely normal. It is perhaps with some realization of this that the Spatio-analytic Institute has adopted as its official slogan the somewhat wry statement, \ldblquote We Analyze Nothing.\rdblquote\ldblquote\par
\tab Rik finished with what was almost a shriek.\par
\tab Terens said, \ldblquote Do you understand what you\rquote ve read?\rdblquote\par
\tab The smaller man looked up with blazing eyes. \ldblquote It said, \lquote We Analyze Nothing.\rquote  That\rquote s what I remembered. I was one of them.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You were a Spatio-analyst?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  cried Rik. Then, in a lower voice, \ldblquote My head hurts.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Because you\rquote re remembering?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I suppose so.\rdblquote  He looked up, forehead furrowed. \ldblquote I\rquote ve got to remember more. There\rquote s danger. Tremendous danger! I don\rquote t know what to do.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The library\rquote s at our disposal, Rik.\rdblquote  Terens was watching carefully, weighing his words. \ldblquote Use the catalog yourself and look up some texts on Spatio-analysis. See where that leads you.\rdblquote\par
\tab Rik flung himself upon the reader. He was shaking visibly. Terens moved aside to give him room.\par
\tab\ldblquote How about Wrijt\rquote s \i Treatise of Spatio-analytic Instrumentation?\i0\rdblquote  asked Rik. \ldblquote Doesn\rquote t that sound right?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It\rquote s all up to you, Rik.\rdblquote\par
\tab Rik punched the catalog number and the screen burned brightly and steadily. It said, \ldblquote Please Consult Librarian for Book in Question.\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens reached out a quick hand and neutralized the screen. \ldblquote Better try another book, Rik.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But . . .\rdblquote  Rik hesitated, then followed orders. Another search through the catalog and then he chose Enning\rquote s \i Composition of Space\i0 .\par
\tab The screen filled itself once more with a request to consult the librarian. Terens said, \ldblquote Damn!\rdblquote  and deadened the screen again.\par
\tab Rik said, \ldblquote What\rquote s the matter?\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens said, \ldblquote Nothing. Nothing. Now don\rquote t get panicky, Rik. I just don\rquote t quite see--\rdblquote\par
\tab There was a little speaker behind the grillwork on the side of the reading mechanism. The librarian\rquote s thin, dry voice emerged therefrom and froze them both.\par
\tab\ldblquote Room 242! Is there anyone in Room 242?\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens answered harshly, \ldblquote What do you want?\rdblquote\par
\tab The voice said, \ldblquote What book is it you want?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote None at all. Thank you. We are only testing the reader.\rdblquote\par
\tab There was a pause as though some invisible consultation was proceeding. Then the voice said with an even sharper edge to it, \ldblquote The record indicates a reading request for Wrijt\rquote s \i Treatise of Spatio-analytical Instrumentation\i0 , and Enning\rquote s \i Composition of Space\i0 . Is that correct?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote We were punching catalog numbers at random,\rdblquote  said Terens. \par
\tab\ldblquote May I ask your reason for desiring those books?\rdblquote  The voice was inexorable.\par
\tab\ldblquote I tell you we don\rquote t want them. . . . Now stop it.\rdblquote  The last was an angry aside to Rik, who had begun whimpering.\par
\tab A pause again. Then the voice said, \ldblquote If you will come down to the desk you may have access to the books. They are on a reserved listing and you will have to fill out a form.\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens held out a hand to Rik. \ldblquote Let\rquote s go.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Maybe we\rquote ve broken a rule,\rdblquote  quavered Rik.\par
\tab\ldblquote Nonsense, Rik. We\rquote re leaving.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote We won\rquote t fill out the form?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No, we\rquote ll get the books some other time.\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens was hurrying, forcing Rik along with him. He strode down the main lobby. The librarian looked up.\par
\tab\ldblquote Here now,\rdblquote  she cried, rising and circling the desk. \ldblquote One moment. One moment!\rdblquote\par
\tab They weren\rquote t stopping for her.\par
\tab That is, until a patroller stepped in front of them. \ldblquote You\rquote re in an awful hurry, laddies.\rdblquote\par
\tab The librarian, somewhat breathless, caught up to them. \ldblquote You\rquote re 242, aren\rquote t you?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Look here,\rdblquote  said Terens firmly, \ldblquote why are we being stopped?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Didn\rquote t you inquire after certain books? We\rquote d like to get them for you.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It\rquote s too late. Another time. Don\rquote t you understand that I don\rquote t want the books? I\rquote ll be back tomorrow.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The library,\rdblquote  said the woman primly, \ldblquote at all times endeavors to give satisfaction. The books will be made available to you in one moment.\rdblquote  Two spots of red burned high upon her cheekbones. She turned away, hurrying through a small door that opened at her approach.\par
\tab Terens said, \ldblquote Officer, if you don\rquote t mind--\rdblquote\par
\tab But the patroller held out his moderately long, weighted neuronic whip. It could serve as an excellent club, or as a longer-range weapon of paralyzing potentialities. He said, \ldblquote Now, laddy, why don\rquote t you sit down quietly and wait for the lady to come back? It would be the polite thing to do.\rdblquote\par
\tab The patroller was no longer young, no longer slim. He looked close to retirement age and he was probably serving out his time in quiet vegetation as library guard, but he was armed and the joviality on his swarthy face had an insincere look about it.\par
\tab Terens\rquote  forehead was wet and he could feel the perspiration collecting at the base of his spine. Somehow he had underestimated the situation. He had been sure of his own analysis of the matter, of everything. Yet here he was. He shouldn\rquote t have been so reckless. It was his damned desire to invade Upper City, to stalk through the library corridors as though he were a Sarkite. . .\par
\tab For a desperate moment he wanted to assault the patroller and then, unexpectedly, he didn\rquote t have to.\par
\tab It was just a flash of movement at first. The patroller started to turn a little too late. The slower reactions of age betrayed him. The neuronic whip was wrenched from his grasp and before he could do more than emit the beginning of a hoarse cry it was laid along his temple. He collapsed.\par
\tab Rik shrieked with delight, and Terens cried, \ldblquote Valona! By all the devils of Sark, \i Valona!\i0 "\par
\tab\par
