\b FOUR: The Rebel\par
\b0\f1\tab\par
\tab\par
\tab\f0 TERENS RECOVERED almost at once. He said, \ldblquote Out. Quickly!\rdblquote  and began walking.\par
\tab For a moment he had the impulse to drag the patroller\rquote s unconscious body into the shadows behind the pillars that lined the main hall, but there was obviously no time.\par
\tab They emerged onto the ramp, with the afternoon sun making the world bright and warm about them. The colors of Upper City had shifted to an orange motif.\par
\tab Valona said anxiously, \ldblquote Come on!\rdblquote  but Terens caught her elbow.\par
\tab He was smiling, but his voice was hard and low. He said, \ldblquote Don\rquote t run. Walk naturally and follow me. Hold on to Rik. Don\rquote t let him run.\rdblquote\par
\tab A few steps. They seemed to be moving through glue. Were there sounds behind them from the library? Imagination? Terens did not dare look.\par
\tab\ldblquote In here,\rdblquote  he said. The sign above the driveway he indicated flickered a bit in the light of afternoon. It didn\rquote t compete very well with Florina\rquote s sun. It said: Ambulance Entrance.\par
\tab Up the drive, through a side entrance, and between incredibly white walls. They were blobs of foreign material against the aseptic glassiness of the corridor.\par
\tab A woman in uniform was looking at them from a distance. She hesitated, frowned, began to approach. Terens did not wait for her. He turned sharply, followed a branch of the corridor, then another one. They passed others in uniform and Terens could imagine the uncertainty they aroused. It was quite unprecedented to have natives wandering about unguarded in the upper levels of a hospital. What did one do?\par
\tab Eventually, of course, they would be stopped.\par
\tab So Terens felt his heartbeat step up when he saw the unobtrusive door that said: To Native Levels. The elevator was at their level. He herded Rik and Valona within and the soft lurch as the elevator dropped was the most delightful sensation of the day.\par
\tab There were three kinds of buildings in the City. Most were Lower Buildings, built entirely on the lower level. Workers\rquote  houses, ranging up to three stories in height. Factories, bakeries, disposal plants. Others were Upper Buildings: Sarkite homes, theaters, the library, sports arenas. But some few were Doubles, with levels and entrances both below and above; the patroller stations, for instance, and the hospitals.\par
\tab One could therefore use a hospital to go from Upper City to Lower City and avoid in that manner the use of the large freight elevators with their slow movements and overattentive operators. For a native to do so was thoroughly illegal, of course, but the added crime was a pinprick to those already guilty of assaulting patrollers.\par
\tab They stepped out upon the lower level. The stark aseptic walls were there still, but they had a faintly haggard appearance as though they were less often scrubbed. The upholstered benches that lined the corridors on the upper level were gone. Most of all there was the uneasy babble of a waiting room filled with wary men and frightened women. A single attendant was attempting to make sense out of the mess, and succeeding poorly.\par
\tab She was snapping at a stubbled oldster who pleated and unpleated the wrinkled knee of his raveling trousers and who answered all questions in an apologetic monotone.\par
\tab\ldblquote Exactly what is your complaint? . . . How long have you had these pains? . . . Ever been to the hospital before? . . Now look, you people can\rquote t expect to bother us over every little thing. You sit down and the doctor will look at you and give you more medicine.\rdblquote\par
\tab She cried shrilly, \ldblquote Next!\rdblquote  then muttered something to herself as she looked at the large timepiece on the wall.\par
\tab Terens, Valona and Rik were edging cautiously through the crowd. Valona, as though the presence of fellow Florinians had freed her tongue of paralysis, was whispering intensely.\par
\tab\ldblquote I had to come, Townman. I was so worried about Rik. I thought you wouldn\rquote t bring him back and--\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote How did you get to Upper City, anyway?\rdblquote  demanded Terens over his shoulder, as he shoved unresisting natives to either side.\par
\tab\ldblquote I followed you and saw you go up the freight elevator. When it came down I said I was with you and he took me up.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Just like that.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I shook him a little.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Imps of Sark,\rdblquote  groaned Terens.\par
\tab\ldblquote I had to,\rdblquote  explained Valona miserably. \ldblquote Then I saw the patrollers pointing out a building to you. I waited till they were gone and went there too. Only I didn\rquote t dare go inside. I didn\rquote t know what to do so I sort of hid until I saw you coming out with the patroller stopping--\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You people there!\rdblquote  It was the sharp, impatient voice of the receptionist. She was standing now, and the hard rapping of her metal stylus on the cementalloy desk top dominated the gathering and reduced them to a hard-breathing silence.\par
\tab\ldblquote Those people trying to leave. Come here. You cannot leave without being examined. There\rquote ll be no evading work-days with pretended sick calls. Come back here!\rdblquote\par
\tab But the three were out in the half shadow of Lower City. There were the smells and noise of what the Sarkites called the Native Quarter about them and the upper level was once more only a roof above them. But however relieved Valona and 13.1k might feel at being away from the oppressive richness of Sarkite surroundings, Terens felt no lifting of anxiety. They had gone too far and henceforth there might be no safety anywhere.\par
\tab The thought was still passing through his turbulent mind when Rik called, \ldblquote Look!\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens felt salt in his throat.\par
\tab It was perhaps the most frightening sight the natives of the Lower City could see. It was like a giant bird floating down through one of the openings in the Upper City. It shut off the sun and deepened the ominous gloom of that portion of the City. But it wasn\rquote t a bird. It was one of the armed ground-cars of the patrollers.\par
\tab Natives yelled and began running. They might have no specific reason to fear, but they scattered anyway. One man, nearly in the path of the car, stepped aside reluctantly. He had been hurrying on his way, intent on some business of his own, when the shadow caught him. He looked about him, a rock of calm in the wildness. He was of medium height, but almost grotesquely broad across the shoulders. One of his shirt sleeves was slit down its length, revealing an arm like another man\rquote s thigh.\par
\tab Terens was hesitating, and Rik and Valona could do nothing without him. The Townman\rquote s inner uncertainty had mounted to a fever. If they ran, where could they go? If they remained where they were, what would they do? There was a chance that the patrollers were after others altogether, but with a patroller unconscious on the library floor through their act, the chances of that were negligible.\par
\tab The broad man was approaching at a heavy half trot. For a moment he paused in passing them, as though with uncertainty. He said in a conversational voice, \ldblquote Khorov\rquote s bakery is second left, beyond the laundry.\rdblquote\par
\tab He veered back.\par
\tab Terens said, \ldblquote Come on.\rdblquote\par
\tab He was sweating freely as he ran. Through the uproar, he heard the barking orders that came naturally to patroller throats. He threw one look over his shoulder. A half dozen of them were piling out of the ground-car, fanning out. They would have no trouble, he knew. In his damned Townman\rquote s uniform, he was as conspicuous as one of the pillars supporting the Upper City.\par
\tab Two of the patrollers were running in the right direction. He didn\rquote t know whether or not they had seen him, but that didn\rquote t matter. Both collided with the broad man who had just spoken to Terens. All three were close enough for Terens to hear the broad man\rquote s hoarse bellow and the patrollers\rquote  sharp cursing. Terens herded Valona and Rik around the corner.\par
\tab Khorov\rquote s bakery was named as such by an almost defaced \ldblquote worm\rdblquote  of crawling illuminated plastic, broken in half a dozen places, and was made unmistakable by the wonderful odor that filtered through its open door. There was nothing to do but enter, and they did.\par
\tab An old man looked out from the inner room within which they could see the flour-obscured gleam of the radar furnaces. He had no chance to ask their business.\par
\tab Terens began, \ldblquote A broad man--\rdblquote  He was holding his arms apart in illustration, and the cries of \ldblquote Patrollers! Patrollers!\rdblquote  began to be heard outside.\par
\tab The old man said hoarsely, \ldblquote This way! Quickly!\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens held back. \ldblquote In there?\rdblquote\par
\tab The old man said, \ldblquote This one is a dummy.\rdblquote\par
\tab First Rik, then Valona, then Terens crawled through the furnace door. There was a faint click and the back wall of the furnace moved slightly and hung freely from the hinges above. They pushed through it and into a small room, dimly lit, beyond.\par
\tab\par
\tab They waited. Ventilation was bad, and the smell of baking increased hunger without satisfying it. Valona kept smiling at Rik, patting his hand mechanically from time to time. Rik stared back at her blankly. Once in a while he put a hand to his flushed face.\par
\tab Valona began, \ldblquote Townman--\rdblquote\par
\tab He snapped back in a tight whisper, \ldblquote Not now, Lona. Please!\rdblquote\par
\tab He passed the back of his hand across his forehead, then stared at the dampness of Ms knuckles.\par
\tab There was a click, magnified by the close confinement of their hiding place. Terens stiffened. Without quite realizing it, he raised clenched fists.\par
\tab It was the broad man, poking his immense shoulders through the opening. They scarcely fit.\par
\tab He looked at Terens and was amused. \ldblquote Come on, man. We\rquote re not going to be fighting.\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens looked at his fists, and let them drop.\par
\tab The broad man was in markedly poorer condition now than when they had first seen him. His shirt was all but removed from his back and a fresh weal, turning red and purple, marked one cheekbone. His eyes were little and the eyelids crowded them above and below.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote They\rquote ve stopped looking. If you\rquote re hungry, the fare here isn\rquote t fancy, but there\rquote s enough of it. What do you say?\rdblquote\par
\par
\tab It was night in the City. There were lights in the Upper City that lit the sky for miles, but in the Lower City the darkness was clammy. The shades were drawn tightly across the front of the bakery to hide the illegal, past-curfew lights away from it.\par
\tab Rik felt better with warm food inside him. His headache began to recede. He fixed his eyes on the broad man\rquote s cheek.\par
\tab Timidly he asked, \ldblquote Did they hurt you, mister?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote A little,\rdblquote  said the broad one. \ldblquote It doesn\rquote t matter. It happens every day in my business.\rdblquote  He laughed, showing large teeth. \ldblquote They had to admit I hadn\rquote t done anything but I was in their way while they were chasing someone else. The easiest way of getting a native out of the way--\rdblquote  His hand rose and fell, holding an invisible weapon, butt-first.\par
\tab Rik flinched away and Valona reached out an anxious, protective arm.\par
\tab The broad man leaned back, sucking at his teeth to get out particles of food. He said, \ldblquote I\rquote m Matt Khorov, but they just call me the Baker. Who are you people?\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens shrugged. \ldblquote Well. . .\rdblquote\par
\tab The Baker said, \ldblquote I see your point. What I don\rquote t know won\rquote t hurt anyone. Maybe. Maybe. At that, though, you might trust me. I saved you from the patrollers, didn\rquote t I?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes. Thank you.\rdblquote  Terens couldn\rquote t squeeze cordiality into his voice. He said, \ldblquote How did you know they were after us? There were quite a few people running.\rdblquote\par
\tab The other smiled. \ldblquote None of them had the faces you three were wearing. Yours could have been ground up and used for chalk.\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens tried to smile in return. He didn\rquote t succeed well. \ldblquote I'm not sure I know why you risked your life. Thank you, anyway. It isn\rquote t much, just saying \lquote Thank you,\rquote  but there\rquote s nothing else I can do right now.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You don\rquote t have to do anything.\rdblquote  The Baker\rquote s vast shoulders leaned back against the wall. \ldblquote I do this as often as I can. It\rquote s nothing personal. If the patrollers are after someone I do my best for him. I hate the patrollers.\rdblquote\par
\tab Valona gasped. \ldblquote Don\rquote t you get into trouble?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Sure. Look at this.\rdblquote  He put a finger gently on his bruised cheek. \ldblquote But you don\rquote t think I ought to let it stop me, I hope. That\rquote s why I built the dummy oven. So the patrollers wouldn\rquote t catch me and make things too hard for me.\rdblquote\par
\tab Valona\rquote s eyes were wide with mingled fright and fascination.\par
\tab The Baker said, \ldblquote Why not? You know how many Squires there are on Florina? Ten thousand. You know how many patrollers? Maybe twenty thousand. And there are five hundred million of us natives. If we all lined up against them . . .\rdblquote  He snapped his fingers.\par
\tab Terens said, \ldblquote We\rquote d be lining up against needle-guns and blaster-cannon, Baker.\rdblquote\par
\tab The Baker retorted, \ldblquote Yeah. We\rquote d have to get some of our own. You Townmen have been living too close to the Squires. You\rquote re scared of them.\rdblquote\par
\tab Valona\rquote s world was being turned upside down today. This man fought with patrollers and spoke with careless self-confidence to the Townman. When Rik plucked at her sleeve she disengaged his fingers gently and told him to sleep. She scarcely looked at him. She wanted to hear what this man said.\par
\tab The broad man was saying, \ldblquote Even with needle-guns and blast-cannon, the only way the Squires hold Florina is with the help of a hundred thousand Townmen.\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens looked offended, but the Baker went on, \ldblquote For instance, look at you. Very nice clothes. Neat. Pretty. You\rquote ve got a nice little shack, I\rquote ll bet, with book-films, a private hopper and no curfew. You can even go to Upper City if you want to. The Squires wouldn\rquote t do that for you for nothing.\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens felt in no position to lose his temper. He said, \ldblquote All right. What do you want the Townmen to do? Pick fights with the patrollers? What good would it do? I admit I keep my town quiet and up to quota, but I keep them out of trouble. I try to help them, as much as the law will allow. Isn\rquote t that something? Someday--\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Aah, someday. Who can wait for someday? When you and I are dead, what difference will it make who runs Florina? To us, I mean.\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens said, \ldblquote In the first place, I hate the Squires more than you do. Still--\rdblquote  He stopped, reddening.\par
\tab The Baker laughed. \ldblquote Go ahead. Say it again. I won\rquote t turn you in for hating the Squires. What did you do to get the patrollers after you?\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens was silent.\par
\tab The Baker said, \ldblquote I can make a guess. When the patrollers fell over me they were plenty sore. Sore in person, I mean, and not just because some Squire told them to be sore. I know them and I can tell. So I figure that there\rquote s only one thing that could have happened. You must\rquote ve knocked down a patroller. Or killed him, maybe.\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens was still silent.\par
\tab The Baker lost none of his agreeable tone. \ldblquote It\rquote s all right to keep quiet but there\rquote s such a thing as being too cautious, Townman. You\rquote re going to need help. They know who you are.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No, they don\rquote t,\rdblquote  said Terens hastily.\par
\tab\ldblquote They must have looked at your cards in the Upper City.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Who said I was in the Upper City?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote A guess. I\rquote ll bet you were.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote They looked at my card, but not long enough to read my name.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Long enough to know you\rquote re a Townman. All they have to do is find a Townman missing from his town or one who can\rquote t account for his movements today. The wires all over Florina are probably scorching right now. I think you\rquote re in trouble.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Maybe.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You know there\rquote s no maybe. Want help?\rdblquote\par
\tab They were talking in whispers. Rik had curled up in the corner and gone to sleep. Valona\rquote s eyes were moving from speaker to speaker.\par
\tab Terens shook his head. \ldblquote No, thanks. I--I\rquote ll get out of this.\rdblquote\par
\tab The Baker\rquote s ready laughter came. \ldblquote It will be interesting to see how. Don\rquote t look down on me because I haven\rquote t got an education. I\rquote ve got other things. Look, you spend the night thinking about it. Maybe you\rquote ll decide you can use help.\rdblquote\par
\par
\tab Valona\rquote s eyes were open in the darkness. Her bed was only a blanket thrown on the floor, but it was nearly as good as the beds she was used to. Rik slept deeply on another blanket in an opposite corner. He always slept deeply on days of excitement after his headaches passed.\par
\tab The Townman had refused a bed and the Baker had laughed (he laughed at everything, it seemed), turned out the light and told him he was welcome to sit up in the darkness.\par
\tab Valona\rquote s eyes remained open. Sleep was far away. Would she ever sleep again? She had knocked down a patroller!\par
\tab Unaccountably, she was thinking of her father and mother.\par
\tab They were very misty in her mind. She had almost made herself forget them in the years that had stretched between them and herself. But now she remembered the sound of whispered conversations during the night, when they thought her asleep. She remembered people who came in the dark.\par
\tab The patrollers had awakened her one night and asked her questions she could not understand but tried to answer. She never saw her parents again after that. They had gone away, she was told, and the next day they had put her to work when other children her age still had two years of play time. People looked after her as she passed and other children weren\rquote t allowed to play with her, even when work time was over. She learned to keep to herself. She learned not to speak. So they called her \ldblquote Big Lona\rdblquote  and laughed at her and said she was a half-wit.\par
\tab Why did the conversation tonight remind her of her parents?\par
\tab\ldblquote Valona.\rdblquote\par
\tab The voice was so close that its light breath stirred her hair and so low she scarcely heard it. She tensed, partly in fear, partly in embarrassment. There was only a sheet over her bare body.\par
\tab It was the Townman. He said, \ldblquote Don\rquote t say anything. Just listen. I am leaving. The door isn\rquote t locked. I\rquote ll be back, though. Do you hear me? Do you understand?\rdblquote\par
\tab She reached in the darkness, caught his hand, pressed it with her fingers. He was satisfied.\par
\tab\ldblquote And watch Rik. Don\rquote t let him out of your sight. And Valona.\rdblquote  There was a long pause. Then he went on, \ldblquote Don\rquote t trust this Baker too much. I don\rquote t know about him. Do you understand?\rdblquote\par
\tab There was a faint noise of motion, an even fainter distant creak, and he was gone. She raised herself to one elbow and, except for Rik\rquote s breathing and her own, there was only silence.\par
\tab She put her eyelids together in the darkness, squeezing them, trying to think. Why did the Townman, who knew everything, say this about the Baker, who hated patrollers and had saved them? Why?\par
\tab She could think of only one thing. He had been there. Just when things looked as black as they could be, the Baker had come and had acted quickly. It was almost as though it had been arranged or as if the Baker had been waiting for it all to happen. \par
\tab She shook her head. It seemed strange. If it weren\rquote t for what the Townman had said, she would never think this.\par
\tab The silence was broken into quivering pieces by a loud and unconcerned remark. \ldblquote Hello? Still here?\rdblquote\par
\tab She froze as a beam of light caught her full. Slowly she relaxed and bunched the sheet about her neck. The beam fell away.\par
\tab She did not have to wonder about the identity of the new speaker. His squat broad form bulked in the half-light that leaked backward from the flash.\par
\tab The Baker said, \ldblquote You know, I thought you\rquote d go with him.\rdblquote\par
\tab Valona said weakly, \ldblquote Who, sir?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The Townman. You know he left, girl. Don\rquote t waste time pretending.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote He\rquote ll be back, sir.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Did he say he would be back? If he did, he\rquote s wrong~ The patrollers will get him. He\rquote s not a very smart man, the Townman, or he\rquote d know when a door is left open for a purpose. Are you planning to leave too?\rdblquote\par
\tab Valona said, \ldblquote I\rquote ll wait for the Townman.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Suit yourself. It will be a long wait. Go when you please.\rdblquote  \par
\tab His light-beam suddenly left her altogether and traveled along the floor, picking out Rik\rquote s pale, thin face. Rik\rquote s eyelids crushed together automatically, at the impact of the light, but he slept on.\par
\tab The Baker\rquote s voice grew thoughtful. \ldblquote But I\rquote d just as soon you left that one behind. You understand that, I suppose. If you decide to leave, the door is open, but it isn\rquote t open for \i him\i0 .\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote He\rquote s just a poor, sick fellow--\rdblquote  Valona began in a high, frightened voice.\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes? Well, I collect poor sick fellows and that one stays here. Remember!\rdblquote\par
\tab The light-beam did not move from Rik\rquote s sleeping face.\par
