\tab\f0 RIK saw the Baker killed. He saw him crumple without a sound, his chest driven in and charred into smoking ruins under the silent push of the blaster. It was a sight that drowned out for him most of what had preceded and almost all that had followed.\par
\tab There was the dim memory of the patroller\rquote s first approach, of the quiet but terribly intent manner in which he had drawn his weapon. The Baker had looked up and shaped his lips for one last word that he had no time to utter. Then the deed was done, there was the rushing of blood in Rik\rquote s ears and the wild screaming scramble of the mob swirling in all directions, like a river in flood.\par
\tab For a moment it negated the improvement Rik\rquote s mind had made in those last few hours of sleep. The patroller had plunged toward him, throwing himself forward upon yelling men and women as though they were a viscous sea of mud he would have to slog through. Rik and Lona turned with the current and were carried away. There were eddies and subcurrents, turning and quivering as the flying patrollers\rquote  cars began to hover overhead. Valona urged Rik forward, ever outward to the outskirts of the City. For a while he was the frightened child of yesterday, not the almost adult of that morning.\par
\tab He had awakened that morning in the grayness of a dawn he could not see in the windowless room he slept in. For long minutes he lay there, inspecting his mind. Something had healed during the night; something had knit together and become whole. It had been getting ready to happen ever since the moment, two days before, when he had begun to \ldblquote remember.\rdblquote  The process had been proceeding all through yesterday. The trip to the Upper City and the library, the attack upon the patroller and the flight that followed, the encounter with Baker--it had all acted upon him like a ferment. The shriveled fibers of his mind, so long dormant, had been seized and stretched, forced into an aching activity, and now, after a sleep, there was a feeble pulsing about them.\par
\tab He thought of space and the stars, of long, long, lonely stretches, and great silences.\par
\tab Finally he turned his head to one side and said, \ldblquote Lona.\rdblquote\par
\tab She snapped awake, lifting herself to an elbow, peering in his direction.\par
\tab\ldblquote Rik?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Here I am, Lona.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Are you all right?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Sure.\rdblquote  He couldn\rquote t hold down his excitement. \ldblquote I feel fine, Lona. Listen! I remember more. I was in a ship and I know exactly--\rdblquote\par
\tab But she wasn\rquote t listening to him. She slipped into her dress and with her back to him smoothed the seam shut down the front and then fumbled nervously with her belt.\par
\tab She tiptoed toward him. \ldblquote I didn\rquote t mean to sleep, Rik. I tried to stay awake.\rdblquote\par
\tab Rik felt the infection of her nervousness. He said, \ldblquote Is something wrong?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Sh, don\rquote t speak so loudly. It\rquote s all right.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Where\rquote s the Townman?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote He\rquote s not here. He--he had to leave. Why don\rquote t you go back to sleep, Rik?\rdblquote\par
\tab He pushed her consoling arm aside. \ldblquote I\rquote m all right. I don\rquote t want to sleep. I wanted to tell the Townman about my ship.\rdblquote\par
\tab But the Townman wasn\rquote t there and Valona would not listen. Rik subsided and for the first time felt actively annoyed with Valona. She treated him as though he were a child and he was beginning to feel like a man.\par
\tab A light entered the room and the broad figure of the Baker entered with it. Rik blinked at him and was, for a moment, daunted. He did not entirely object when Valona\rquote s comforting arm stole about his shoulder.\par
\tab The Baker\rquote s thick lips stretched in a smile. \ldblquote You\rquote re early awake.\rdblquote\par
\tab Neither answered..\par
\tab The Baker said, \ldblquote It\rquote s just as well. You\rquote ll be moving today.\rdblquote\par
\tab Valona\rquote s mouth, was dry. She said, \ldblquote You\rquote ll not be giving us to the patrollers?\rdblquote\par
\tab She remembered the way he had looked at Rik after the Townman had left. He was still looking at Rik; only at Rik.\par
\tab\ldblquote Not to the patrollers,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote The proper people have been informed and you\rquote ll be safe enough.\rdblquote\par
\tab He left, and when he returned shortly thereafter he brought food, clothes and two basins of water. The clothes were new and looked completely strange.\par
\tab He watched them as they ate, saying, \ldblquote I\rquote m going to give you new names and new histories. You\rquote re to listen, and I don\rquote t want you to forget. You\rquote re not Florinians, do you understand? You\rquote re brother and sister from the planet Wotex. You\rquote ve been visiting Florina--\rdblquote\par
\tab He went on, supplying details, asking questions, listening to their answers.\par
\tab Rik was pleased to be able to demonstrate the workings of his memory, his easy ability to learn, but Valona\rquote s eyes were dark with worry.\par
\tab The Baker was not blind to that. He said to the girl, \ldblquote If you give me the least trouble I\rquote ll send him on alone and leave you behind.\rdblquote\par
\tab Valona\rquote s strong hands clenched spasmodically. \ldblquote I will give you no trouble.\rdblquote\par
\tab It was well into the morning when the Baker rose to his feet and said, \ldblquote Let\rquote s go!\rdblquote\par
\tab His last action was to place little black sheets of limp leatherette in their breast pockets.\par
\tab Once outside, Rik looked with astonishment at what he could see of himself. He did not know clothing could be so complicated. The Baker had helped him get it on, but who would help him take it off? Valona didn\rquote t look like a farm girl at all. Even her legs were covered with thin material, and her shoes were raised at the heels so that she had to balance carefully when she walked.\par
\tab Passers-by gathered, staring and gawking, calling to one another. Mostly they were children, marketing women, and skulking, ragged idlers. The Baker seemed oblivious to them. He carried a thick stick which found itself occasionally, as though by accident, between the legs of any who pressed too closely.\par
\tab And then, when they were still only a hundred yards from the bakery and had made but one turning, the outer reaches of the surrounding crowd swirled excitedly and Rik made out the black and silver of a patroller.\par
\tab That was when it happened. The weapon, the blast, and again a wild flight. Was there ever a time when fear had not been with him, when the shadow of the patroller had not been behind him?\par
\par
\tab They found themselves in the squalor of one of the outlying districts of the City. Valona was panting harshly; her new dress bore the wet stains of perspiration.\par
\tab Rik gasped, \ldblquote I can\rquote t run any more.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote We\rquote ve got to.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Not like this. Listen.\rdblquote  He pulled back firmly against the pressure of the girl\rquote s grip. \ldblquote Listen to me.\rdblquote\par
\tab The fright and panic were leaving him.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote Why don\rquote t we go on and do what the Baker wanted us to do?\rdblquote\par
\tab She said, \ldblquote How do you know what he wanted us to do?\rdblquote  She was anxious. She wanted to keep moving.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote We were to pretend we were from another world and he gave us these.\rdblquote  Rik was excited. He pulled the little rectangle out of his pocket, staring at both sides and trying to open it as though it were a booklet.\par
\tab He couldn\rquote t. It was a single sheet. He felt about the edges and as his fingers closed at one corner he heard, or rather felt, something give, and the side toward him turned a startling milky white. The close wording on the new surface was difficult to understand though he began carefully making out the syllables.\par
\tab Finally he said, \ldblquote It\rquote s a passport.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What\rquote s that?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Something to get us away.\rdblquote  He was sure of it. It had popped into his head. A single word, \ldblquote passport,\rdblquote  like that. \ldblquote Don\rquote t you see? He was going to have us leave Florina. On a ship. Let\rquote s go through with that.\rdblquote\par
\tab She said, \ldblquote No. They stopped him. They killed him. We couldn\rquote t, Rik, we couldn\rquote t.\rdblquote\par
\tab He was urgent about it. He was nearly babbling. \ldblquote But it would be the best thing to do. They wouldn\rquote t be expecting us to do that. And we wouldn\rquote t go on the ship he wanted us to go on. They\rquote d be watching that. We\rquote d go on another ship. Any other ship.\rdblquote\par
\tab A ship. Any ship. The words rang in his ears. Whether his idea was a good one or not, he didn\rquote t care. He wanted to be on a ship. He wanted to be in space.\par
\tab\ldblquote\i Please\i0 , Lona!\rdblquote\par
\tab She said, \ldblquote All right. If you really think so. I know where the spaceport is. When I was a little girl we used to go there on idle-days sometimes and watch from far away to see the ships shoot upward.\rdblquote\par
\tab They were on their way again, and only a slight uneasiness scratched vainly at the gateway of Rik\rquote s consciousness. Some memory not of the far past but of the very near past; something he should remember and could not; could just barely not. Something.\par
\tab He drowned it in the thought of the ship that waited for them. \par
\tab The Florinian at the entry gate was having his fill of excitement that day, but it was excitement at long distance. There had been the wild stories of the previous evening, telling of patrollers attacked and of daring escapes. By this morning the stories had expanded and there were whispers of patrollers killed.\par
\tab He dared not leave his post, but he craned his neck and watched the air-cars pass, and the grim-faced patrollers leave, as the spaceport contingent was cut and cut till it was almost nothing.\par
\tab They were filling the City with patrollers, he thought, and was at once frightened and drunkenly uplifted. Why should it make him happy to think of patrollers being killed? They never bothered him. At least not much. He had a good job. It wasn\rquote t as though he were a stupid peasant.\par
\tab But he was happy.\par
\tab He scarcely had time for the couple before him, uncomfortable and perspiring in the outlandish clothing that marked them at once as foreigners. The woman was holding a passport through the slot.\par
\tab A glance at her, a glance at the passport, a glance at the list of reservations. He pressed the appropriate button and two translucent ribbons of film sprang out at them.\par
\tab\ldblquote Go on,\rdblquote  he said impatiently. \ldblquote Get them on your wrists and move on.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Which ship is ours?\rdblquote  asked the woman in a polite whisper.\par
\tab That pleased him. Foreigners were infrequent at the Florinian spaceport. In recent years they had grown more and more infrequent. But when they did come they were neither patrollers nor Squires. They didn\rquote t seem to realize you were only a Florinian yourself and they spoke to you politely.\par
\tab It made him feel two inches taller. He said, \ldblquote You\rquote ll find it in Berth 17, madam. I wish you a pleasant trip to Wotex.\rdblquote  He said it in the grand manner.\par
\tab He then returned to his task of putting in surreptitious calls to friends in the City for more information and of trying, even more unobtrusively, to tap private power-beam conversations in Upper City.\par
\tab It was hours before he found out that he had made a horrible mistake.\par
\par
\tab Rik said, \ldblquote Lona!\rdblquote\par
\tab He tugged at her elbow, pointed quickly and whispered, \ldblquote That one!\rdblquote\par
\tab Valona looked at the indicated ship doubtfully. It was much smaller than the ship in Berth 17, for which their tickets held good. It looked more burnished. Four air locks yawned open and the main port gaped, with a ramp leading from it like an outstretched tongue reaching to ground level.\par
\tab Rik said, \ldblquote They\rquote re airing it. They usually air passenger ships before flight to get rid of the accumulated odor of canned oxygen, used and reused.\rdblquote\par
\tab Valona stared at him. \ldblquote How do you know?\rdblquote\par
\tab Rik felt a sprig of vanity grow within himself. \ldblquote I just know. You see, there wouldn\rquote t be anyone in it now. It isn\rquote t comfortable, with the draft on.\rdblquote\par
\tab He looked about uneasily. \ldblquote I don\rquote t know why there aren\rquote t more people about, though. Was it like this when you used to watch it?\rdblquote\par
\tab Valona thought not, but she could scarcely remember. Childhood memories were far away.\par
\par
\tab There was not a patroller in sight as they walked up the ramp on quivering legs. What figures they could see were civilian employees, intent on their own jobs, and small in the distance.\par
\tab Moving air cut through them as they stepped into the hold and Valona\rquote s dress bellied so that she had to bring her hands down to keep the hemline within bounds.\par
\tab\ldblquote Is it always like this?\rdblquote  she asked. She had never been on a spaceship before; never dreamed of being on one. Her lips stuck together and her heart pounded.\par
\tab Rik said, \ldblquote No. Just during aeration.\rdblquote\par
\tab He walked joyfully over the hard metallite passageways, inspecting the empty rooms eagerly.\par
\tab\ldblquote Here,\rdblquote  he said. It was the galley.\par
\tab He spoke rapidly. \ldblquote It isn\rquote t food so much. We can get along without food for quite a while. It\rquote s water.\rdblquote\par
\tab He rummaged through the neat and compact nestings of utensils and came up with a large, capped container. He looked about for the water tap, muttered a breathless hope that they had not neglected to fill the water tanks, then grinned his relief when the soft sound of pumps came, and the steady gush of liquid.\par
\tab\ldblquote Now just take some of the cans. Not too many. We don\rquote t want them to take notice.\rdblquote\par
\tab Rik tried desperately to think of ways of countering discovery. Again he groped for something he could not quite remember. Occasionally he still ran into those gaps in his thought and, cowardlike, he avoided them, denied their existence.\par
\tab He found a small room devoted to fire-fighting equipment, emergency medical and surgical supplies, and welding equipment.\par
\tab He said with a certain lack of confidence, \ldblquote They won\rquote t be in here, except in emergencies. Are you afraid, Lona?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I won\rquote t be afraid with you, Rik,\rdblquote  she said humbly. Two days before, no, twelve hours before, it had been the other way around. But on board ship, by some transmutation of personality she did not question, it was Rik who was the adult, she who was the child.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote We won\rquote t be able to use lights because they would notice the power drain, and to use the toilets, we\rquote ll have to wait for rest periods and try to get out past any of the night crew.\rdblquote\par
\tab The draft cut off suddenly. Its cold touch on their faces was no longer there and the soft, steady humming sound, that had distantly accompanied it, stopped and left a large silence to fill its place.\par
\tab Rik said, \ldblquote They\rquote ll be boarding soon, and then we\rquote ll be out in space.\rdblquote\par
\tab Valona had never seen such joy in Rik\rquote s face. He was a lover going to meet his love.\par
\par
\tab If Rik had felt a man on awaking that dawn, he was a giant now, his arms stretching the length of the Galaxy. The stars were his marbles, and the nebulae were cobwebs to brush away.\par
\tab He was on a ship! Memories rushed back continuously in a long flood and others left to make room. He was forgetting the kyrt fields and the mill and Valona crooning to him in the dark. They were only momentary breaks in a pattern that was now returning with its raveled ends slowly knitting.\par
\tab It was the ship!\par
\tab If they had put him on a ship long ago, he wouldn\rquote t have had to wait so long for his burnt-out brain cells to heal themselves.\par
\tab He spoke softly to Valona in the darkness. \ldblquote Now don\rquote t worry. You\rquote ll feel a vibration and hear a noise but that will be just the motors. There\rquote ll be a heavy weight on you. That\rquote s acceleration.\rdblquote\par
\tab There was no common Florinian word for the concept and he used another word for it, one that came easily to mind. Valona did not understand.\par
\tab She said, \ldblquote Will it hurt?\rdblquote\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote It will be very uncomfortable, because we don\rquote t have anti-acceleration gear to take up the pressure, but it won\rquote t last. Just stand against this wall, and when you feel yourself being pushed against it, relax. See, it\rquote s beginning.\rdblquote\par
\tab He had picked the right wall, and as the thrumming of the thrusting hyperatomics swelled, the apparent gravity shifted, and what had been a vertical wall seemed to grow more and more diagonal.\par
\tab Valona whimpered once, then lapsed into a hard-breathing silence. Their throats rasped as their chest walls, unprotected by straps and hydraulic absorbers, labored to free their lungs sufficiently for just a little air intake.\par
\tab Rik managed to pant out words, any words that might let Valona know he was there and ease the terrible fear of the unknown that he knew must be filling her. It was only a ship, only a wonderful ship; but she had never been on a ship before.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote There\rquote s the jump, of course, when we go through hyperspace and cut across most of the distance between the stars all at once. That won\rquote t bother you at all. You won\rquote t even know it happened. It\rquote s nothing compared to this. Just a little twitch in your insides and it\rquote s over.\rdblquote  He got the words out syllable by grunted syllable. It took a long time.\par
\tab Slowly, the weight on their chests lifted and the invisible chain holding them to the wall stretched and dropped off. They fell, panting, to the floor.\par
\tab Finally Valona said, \ldblquote Are you hurt, Rik?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I, hurt?\rdblquote  He managed a laugh. He had not caught his breath yet, but he laughed at the thought that he could be hurt on a ship.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote I lived on a ship for years once. I didn\rquote t land on a planet for months at a time.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Why?\rdblquote  she asked. She had crawled closer and put a hand to his cheek, making sure he was there.\par
\tab He put his arm about her shoulder, and she rested within it quietly, accepting the reversal.\par
\tab\ldblquote Why?\rdblquote  she asked.\par
\tab Rik could not remember why. He had done it; he had hated to land on a planet. For some reason it had been necessary to stay in space, but he could not remember why. Again he dodged the gap.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote I had a job.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  she said. \ldblquote You analyzed Nothing.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote That\rquote s right.\rdblquote  He was pleased. \ldblquote That\rquote s exactly what I did. Do you know what that means?\rdblquote\par
\tab "No."\par
\tab He didn\rquote t expect her to understand, but he had to talk. He had to revel in memory, to delight drunkenly in the fact that he could call up past facts at the flick of a mental finger.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote You see, all the material in the universe is made up of a hundred different kinds of substances. We call those substances elements. Iron and copper are elements.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I thought they were metals.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote So they are, and elements too. Also oxygen, and nitrogen, carbon and palladium. Most important of all, hydrogen and helium. They\rquote re the simplest and most common.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I never heard of those,\rdblquote  Valona said wistfully.\par
\tab\ldblquote Ninety-five per cent of the universe is hydrogen and most of the rest is helium. Even space.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I was once told,\rdblquote  said Valona, \ldblquote that space was a vacuum. They said that meant there was nothing there. Was that wrong?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Not quite. There\rquote s \i almost\i0  nothing there. But you see, I was a Spatio-analyst, which meant that I went about through space collecting the extremely small amounts of elements there and analyzing them. That is, I decided how much was hydrogen, how much helium and how much other elements.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Why?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, that\rquote s complicated. You see, the arrangement of elements isn\rquote t the same everywhere in space. In some regions there is a little more helium than normal; in other places, more sodium than normal; and so on. These regions of special analytic makeup wind through space like currents. That\rquote s what they call them. They\rquote re the currents of space. It\rquote s important to know how these currents are arranged because that might explain how the universe was created and how it developed.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote How would it explain that?\rdblquote\par
\tab Rik hesitated. \ldblquote Nobody knows exactly.\rdblquote\par
\tab He hurried on, embarrassed that this immense store of knowledge in which his mind was thankfully wallowing could come so easily to an end marked \ldblquote unknown\rdblquote  under the questioning of . . . of . . . It suddenly occurred to him that Valona, after all, was nothing but a Florinian peasant girl.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote Then, again, we find out the density, you know, the thickness, of this space gas in all regions of the Galaxy. It\rquote s different in different places and we have to know exactly what it is in order to allow ships to calculate exactly how to jump through hyperspace. It\rquote s like. . .\rdblquote  His voice died away.\par
\tab Valona stiffened and waited uneasily for him to continue, but only silence followed. Her voice sounded hoarsely in the complete darkness.\par
\tab\ldblquote Rik? What\rquote s wrong, Rik?\rdblquote\par
\tab Still silence. Her hands groped to his shoulders, shaking him. \ldblquote Rik! Rik!\rdblquote\par
\tab And it was the voice of the old Rik, somehow, that answered. It was weak, frightened, its joy and confidence vanished.\par
\tab\ldblquote Lona. We did something wrong.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What\rquote s the matter? We did what wrong?\rdblquote\par
\tab The memory of the scene in which the patroller had shot down the Baker was in his mind, etched hard and clear, as though called back by his exact memory of so many other things.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote We shouldn\rquote t have run away. We shouldn\rquote t be here on this ship.\rdblquote\par
\tab He was shivering uncontrollably, and Valona tried futilely to wipe the moisture from his forehead with her hand.\par
\tab\ldblquote Why?\rdblquote  she demanded. \ldblquote Why?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Because we should have known that if the Baker were willing to take us out in daylight he expected no trouble from patrollers. Do you remember the patroller? The one who shot the Baker?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Do you remember his face?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I didn\rquote t dare look.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I did, and there was something queer, but I didn\rquote t think. I didn\rquote t think. Lona, that \i wasn\rquote t\i0  a patroller. It was the Townman, Lona. It was the Townman dressed like a patroller.\rdblquote\par
