\tab Myrlyn Terens, had he released his taut nerves the slightest, might easily, and even thankfully, have gone into hysteria. He had been a trifle too late in returning to the bakery. They had already left it and it was only by good fortune that he Met them in the street. His next action had been dictated; it was in no way a matter of free choice; and the Baker lay quite horribly dead before him.\par
\tab Afterward, with the crowd swirling, Rik and Valona melting into the crowd, and the air-cars of the patrollers, the \i real\i0  patrollers, beginning to put in their vulture appearance, what could he do?\par
\tab His first impulse to race after Rik he quickly fought down. It would do no good. He would never find them, and there was too great a chance that the patrollers would not miss him. He scurried in another direction, toward the bakery.\par
\tab His only chance lay in the patroller organization itself. There had been generations of a quiet life. At least there had been no Florinian revolts to speak of in two centuries. The institution of the Townman (he grinned savagely at the thought) had worked wonders and the patrollers had only perfunctory police duties since. They lacked the fine-pointed teamwork that would have developed under more strenuous conditions.\par
\tab It had been possible for him to walk into a patroller station at dawn, where his description must have already been sent, though obviously it had not been much regarded. The lone patroller on duty was a mixture of indifference and sulkiness. Terens had been asked to state his business, but his business included a plastic two-by-four he had wrenched from the side of a crazy hovel at the outskirts of town.\par
\tab He had brought it down upon the patroller\rquote s skull, changed clothing and weapons. The list of his crimes was already so formidable that it did not bother him in the least to discover that the patroller had been killed, not stunned.\par
\tab Yet he was still at large and the rusty machinery of patroller justice had so far creaked after him in vain.\par
\tab He was at the bakery. The Baker\rquote s elderly helper, standing in the doorway in a vain attempt to peer knowledge of the disturbance into himself, squeaked thinly at the sight of the dread black and silver of patrollerhood and oozed back into his shop.\par
\tab The Townman lunged after him, crumpling the man\rquote s loose, floury collar into his pudgy fist and twisting. \ldblquote Where was the Baker going?\rdblquote\par
\tab The old man\rquote s lips yawned open, but no sound came.\par
\tab The Townman said, \ldblquote I killed a man two minutes ago. I don\rquote t care if I kill another.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Please. Please. I do not know, sir.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You will die for not knowing.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But he did not tell me. He made some sort of reservations.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You have overheard so much, have you? What else did you overhear?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote He mentioned Wotex once. I think the reservations were on a spaceship.\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens thrust him away.\par
\tab He would have to wait. He would have to let the worst of the excitement outside die. He would have to risk the arrival of real patrollers at the bakery.\par
\tab But not for long. Not for long. He could guess what his erstwhile companions would do. Rik was unpredictable, of course, but Valona was an intelligent girl. From the way they ran, they must have taken him for a patroller indeed and Valona was sure to decide that their only safety lay in continuing the flight that the Baker had begun for them.\par
\tab The Baker had made reservations for them. A spaceship would be waiting. They would be there.\par
\tab And he would have to be there first.\par
\tab There was this about the desperation of the situation. Nothing more mattered. If he lost Rik, if he lost that potential weapon against the tyrants of Sark, his life was a small additional loss.\par
\tab So when he left, it was without a qualm, though it was broad daylight, though the patrollers must know by now it was a man in patroller uniform they sought, and though two air-cars were in easy sight.\par
\tab\par
\tab Terens knew the spaceport that would be involved. There was only one of its type on the planet. There were a dozen tiny ones in Upper City for the private use of space-yachts and there were hundreds all over the planet for the exclusive use of the ungainly freighters that carried gigantic bolts of kyrt cloth to Sark, and machinery and simple consumer goods back. But among all those there was only one spaceport for the use of ordinary travelers, for the poorer Sarkites, Florinian civil servants and the few foreigners who managed to obtain permission to visit Florina.\par
\tab The Florinian at the port\rquote s entry gate observed Terens\rquote  approach with every symptom of lively interest. The vacuum that surrounded him had grown insupportable.\par
\tab\ldblquote Greetings, sir,\rdblquote  he said. There was a slyly eager tone in his voice. After all, patrollers were being killed. \ldblquote Considerable excitement in the City, isn\rquote t there?\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens did not rise to the bait. He had drawn the arced visor of his hat low and buttoned the uppermost button of the tunic.\par
\tab Gruffly he snapped, \ldblquote Did two persons, a man and a woman, enter the port recently en route to Wotex?\rdblquote\par
\tab The gatekeeper looked startled. For a moment he gulped and then, in a considerably subdued tone, said, \ldblquote Yes, Officer. About half an hour ago. Maybe less.\rdblquote  He reddened suddenly. \ldblquote Is there any connection between them and--Officer, they had reservations which were entirely in order. I wouldn\rquote t let foreigners through without proper authority.\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens ignored that. Proper authority! The Baker had managed to establish that in the course of a night. Galaxy, he wondered, how deeply into the Sarkite administration did the Trantorian espionage organization go?\par
\tab\ldblquote What names did they give?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Gareth and Hansa Barne.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Has their ship left? Quickly!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No-no, sir.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What berth?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Seventeen.\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens forced himself to refrain from running, but his walk was little short of that. Had there been a real patroller in sight that rapid, undignified half run of his would have been his last trip in freedom.\par
\tab A spaceman in officer\rquote s uniform stood at the ship\rquote s main air lock.\par
\tab Terens panted a little. He said, \ldblquote Have Gareth and Hansa Barne boarded ship?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No, they haven\rquote t,\rdblquote  said the spaceman phlegmatically. He was a Sarkite and a patroller was only another man in uniform to him. \ldblquote Do you have a message for them?\rdblquote\par
\tab With cracking patience Terens said, \ldblquote They \i haven\rquote t\i0  boarded!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote That\rquote s what I\rquote ve said. And we\rquote re not waiting for them. We leave on schedule, with or without them.\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens turned away.\par
\tab He was at the gatekeeper\rquote s booth again. \ldblquote Have they left?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Left? Who, sir?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The Barnes. The ones for Wotex. They\rquote re not on board ship. Did they leave?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No, sir. Not to my knowledge.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What about the other gates?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote They\rquote re not exits, sir. This is the only exit.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Check them, you miserable idiot.\rdblquote\par
\tab The gatekeeper lifted the communi-tube in a state of panic. No patroller had ever spoken to him so in anger and he dreaded the results. In two minutes he put it down.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote No one has left, sir.\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens stared at him. Under his black hat his sandy hair was damping against his skull and down each cheek there was the gleaming mark of perspiration.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote Has any ship left the port since they entered?\rdblquote\par
\tab The gatekeeper consulted the schedule. \ldblquote One,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote the liner \i Endeavor\i0 .\rdblquote\par
\tab Volubly he went on, eager to gain favor with the angry patroller by volunteering information. \ldblquote The \i Endeavor\i0  is making a special trip to Sark to carry the Lady Samia of Fife back from Florina.\rdblquote\par
\tab He did not bother to describe exactly by what refined manner of eavesdropping he had managed to acquaint himself with the \ldblquote confidential report.\rdblquote\par
\tab But to Terens now, nothing mattered.\par
\tab He backed slowly away. Eliminate the impossible and whatever remained, however improbable, was the truth. Rik and Valona had entered the spaceport. They had not been captured or the gatekeeper would certainly have known about it. They were not simply wandering about the port, or they would by now have been captured. They were not on the ship for which they had tickets. They had not left the field. The only object that had left the field was the \i Endeavor\i0 . Therefore, on it, possibly as captives, possibly as stowaways, were Rik and Valona.\par
\tab And the two were equivalent. If they were stowaways they would soon be captives. Only a Florinian peasant girl and a mindwrecked creature would fail to realize that one could not stow away on a modern spaceship.\par
\tab And of all spaceships to choose, they chose that which carried the daughter of the Squire of Fife.\par
