\b ELEVEN: The Captain\par
\b0\f1\tab\par
\tab\par
\tab\f0 IT was the first time, really, that Captain Racety had found himself unable to impose his will upon a passenger. Had that passenger been one of the Great Squires themselves, he might still have counted on co-operation. A Great Squire might be all-powerful on his own continent, but on a ship he would recognize that there could be only one master, the Captain.\par
\tab A woman was different. Any woman. And a woman who was daughter of a Great Squire was completely impossible.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote My Lady, how can I allow you to interview them in private?\rdblquote\par
\tab Samia of Fife, her dark eyes snapping, said, \ldblquote Why not? Are they armed, Captain?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Of course not. That\rquote s not the point.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Anyone can see they\rquote re only a pair of very frightened creatures. They\rquote re half scared to death.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Frightened people can be very dangerous, my Lady. They can\rquote t he counted on to act sensibly.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Then why do you keep them frightened?\rdblquote  She had the tiniest stammer when she was angry. \ldblquote You\rquote ve got three tremendous sailors standing over them with blasters, poor things. Captain, I\rquote ll not forget this.\rdblquote\par
\tab No, she wouldn\rquote t, the Captain thought. He could feel himself beginning to give way.\par
\tab\ldblquote If Your Ladyship pleases, will you tell me exactly what it is that you want?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It\rquote s simple. I\rquote ve told you. I want to speak to them. If they\rquote re Florinians, as you say they are, I can get tremendously valuable information from them for my book. I can\rquote t do that, though, if they\rquote re too frightened to speak. If I could be with them alone it would be fine. Alone, Captain! Can you understand a simple word? \i Alone!\i0\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And what would I say to your father, my Lady, if he discovers that I allowed you to remain unguarded in the presence of two desperate criminals?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Desperate criminals! Oh, Great Space! Two poor fools that tried to escape their planet and had no more sense than to board a ship going to Sark! Besides, how would my father know?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote If they hurt you he would know.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Why should they hurt me?\rdblquote  Her small fist lifted and vibrated, while she put every atom of force she could find into her voice. \ldblquote I \i demand\i0  it, Captain.\rdblquote\par
\tab Captain Racety said, \ldblquote How about this then, my Lady? I will be present. I shall not be three sailors with blasters. I shall be one man with no blaster in view. Otherwise\rdblquote --and in his turn he put all his resolution into his voice--\rdblquote I must refuse your demand.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Very well, then.\rdblquote  She was breathless. \ldblquote Very well. But if I can\rquote t get them to speak because of you I will personally see to it that you captain no more ships.\rdblquote\par
\par
\tab Valona put her hand hastily over Rik\rquote s eyes as Samia entered the brig.\par
\tab\ldblquote What\rquote s the matter, girl?\rdblquote  asked Samia sharply, before she could remember that she was going to speak to them comfortingly.\par
\tab Valona spoke with difficulty. She said, \ldblquote He is not bright, Lady. He wouldn\rquote t know you were a Lady. He might have looked at you. I mean without intending any harm, Lady.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, goodness,\rdblquote  said Samia. \ldblquote Let him look.\rdblquote  She went on, \ldblquote Must they stay here, Captain?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Would you prefer a stateroom, my Lady?\rdblquote\par
\tab Samia said, \ldblquote Surely you could manage a cell not quite so grim.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It is grim to you, my Lady. To them, I am sure this is luxury. There is running water here. Ask them if there was any in their hut on Florina.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, tell those men to leave.\rdblquote\par
\tab The Captain motioned to them. They turned, stepping out nimbly.\par
\tab The Captain set down the light aluminum folding chair he had brought with him. Samia took it.\par
\tab He said brusquely to Rik and Valona, \ldblquote Stand up.\rdblquote\par
\tab Samia broke in instantly. \ldblquote No! Let them sit. You\rquote re not to interfere, Captain.\rdblquote\par
\tab She turned to them. \ldblquote So you are a Florinian, girl.\rdblquote\par
\tab Valona shook her head. \ldblquote We\rquote re from Wotex.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You needn\rquote t be frightened. It doesn\rquote t matter that you\rquote re from Florina. No one will hurt you.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote We\rquote re from Wotex.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But don\rquote t you see that you\rquote ve practically admitted you\rquote re from Florina, girl? Why did you cover the boy\rquote s eyes?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote He\rquote s not allowed to look at a Lady.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Even if he\rquote s from Wotex?\rdblquote\par
\tab Valona was silent.\par
\tab Samia let her think about it. She tried to smile in a friendly way. Then she said, \ldblquote Only Florinians aren\rquote t allowed to look at Ladies. So you see you\rquote ve admitted that you\rquote re a Florinian.\rdblquote\par
\tab Valona burst out, \ldblquote\i He\rquote s\i0  not.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Are \i you?\i0\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, I am. But he\rquote s not. Don\rquote t do anything to him. He \i really\i0  isn\rquote t a Florinian. He was just found one day. I don\rquote t know where he comes from, but it\rquote s not Florina.\rdblquote  Suddenly she was almost voluble.\par
\tab Samia looked at her with some surprise. \ldblquote Well, I\rquote ll speak to him. What\rquote s your name, boy?\rdblquote\par
\tab Rik was staring. Was that how women Squires looked? So small, and friendly-looking. And she smelled so nice. He was very glad she had let him look at her.\par
\tab Samia said again, \ldblquote What\rquote s your name, boy?\rdblquote\par
\tab Rik came to life but stumbled badly in the attempt to shape a monosyllable.\par
\tab\ldblquote Rik,\rdblquote  he said. Then he thought, Why, that\rquote s not my name. He said, \ldblquote I think it\rquote s Rik.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Don\rquote t you know?\rdblquote\par
\tab Valona, looking woebegone, tried to speak, but Samia held up a sharply restraining hand.\par
\tab Rik shook his head. \ldblquote I don\rquote t know.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Are you a Florinian?\rdblquote\par
\tab Rik was positive here. \ldblquote No. I was on a ship. I came here from somewhere else.\rdblquote  He could not bear to look away from Samia but he seemed to see the ship co-existing with her. A small and very friendly and homelike ship.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote It was on a ship that I came to Florina and before that I lived on a planet.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What planet?\rdblquote\par
\tab It was as though the thought were forcing its way painfully through mental channels too small for it. Then Rik remembered and was delighted at the sound his voice made, a sound so long forgotten.\par
\tab\ldblquote Earth! I come from Earth!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Earth?\rdblquote\par
\tab Rik nodded.\par
\tab Samia turned to the Captain. \ldblquote Where is this planet Earth?\rdblquote\par
\tab Captain Racety smiled briefly. \ldblquote I never heard of it. Don\rquote t take the boy seriously, my Lady. A native lies the way he breathes. It comes naturally to him. He says whatever comes first into his mind.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote He doesn\rquote t \i talk\i0  like a native.\rdblquote  She turned to Rik again. \ldblquote Where is Earth, Rik?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I--\rdblquote  He put a shaking hand to his forehead. Then he said, \ldblquote It\rquote s in the Sirius Sector.\rdblquote  The intonation of the statement made it half a question.\par
\tab Samia said to the Captain, \ldblquote There is a Sirius Sector, isn\rquote t there?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, there is. I\rquote m amazed he has that right. Still, that doesn\rquote t make Earth any more real.\rdblquote\par
\tab Rik said vehemently, \ldblquote But it is. I remember, I tell you. It\rquote s been so long since I remembered. I can\rquote t be wrong now. I can\rquote t.\rdblquote\par
\tab He turned, gripping Valona\rquote s elbows and clawing at her sleeve. \ldblquote Lona, tell them I come from Earth. I do. I do.\rdblquote\par
\tab Valona\rquote s eyes were wide with anxiety. \ldblquote We found him one day, Lady, and he had no mind at all. He couldn\rquote t dress himself or talk or walk. He was nothing. Ever since then he\rquote s been remembering little by little. So far everything he\rquote s remembered has been so.\rdblquote  She cast a quick, fearful glance at the bored face of the Captain. \ldblquote He may really have come from Earth, Squire. No contradiction intended.\rdblquote\par
\tab The last was a long-established conventional phrase that went with any statement that seemed in contradiction to a previous statement by a superior.\par
\tab Captain Racety grunted. \ldblquote He may have come from the center of Sark for all that story proves, my Lady.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Maybe, but there\rquote s something queer about all this,\rdblquote  insisted Samia, making up her mind flatly, woman-wise, on the side of romance. \ldblquote I\rquote m sure of it. . . . What made him so helpless when you found him, girl? Had he been hurt?\rdblquote\par
\tab Valona said nothing at first. Her eyes darted helplessly back and forth. First to Rik, whose fingers clutched at his hair, then to the Captain, who was smiling without humor, finally to Samia, who waited.\par
\tab\ldblquote Answer me, girl,\rdblquote  said Samia.\par
\tab It was a hard decision for Valona to make, but no conceivable lie could substitute for the truth in this place and at this time. She said, \ldblquote A doctor once looked at him. He said m-my Rik was psycho-probed.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Psycho-probed!\rdblquote  Samia felt a slight wash of repulsion well over her. She pushed her chair away. It squeaked against the metal floor. \ldblquote You mean he was psychotic?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I don\rquote t know what that means, Lady,\rdblquote  said Valona humbly. \par
\tab\ldblquote Not in the sense you\rquote re thinking of, my Lady,\rdblquote  said the Captain almost simultaneously. \ldblquote Natives aren\rquote t psychotic. Their needs and desires are too simple. I\rquote ve never heard of a psychotic native in my life.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But then--\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It\rquote s simple, my Lady. If we accept this fantastic story the girl tells, we can only conclude that the boy had been a criminal, which is a way of being psychotic, I suppose. If so, he must have been treated by one of those quacks who practice among the natives, been nearly killed and was then dumped in a deserted section to avoid detection and prosecution.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But it would have to be someone with a psycho-probe,\rdblquote  protested Samia. \ldblquote Surely you wouldn\rquote t expect natives to be able to use them.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Perhaps not. But then you wouldn\rquote t expect an authorized medical man to use one so inexpertly. The fact that we arrive at a contradiction proves the story to be a lie throughout. If you will accept my suggestion, my Lady, you will leave these creatures to our handling. You see that it\rquote s useless to expect anything out of them.\rdblquote\par
\tab Samia hesitated. \ldblquote Perhaps you\rquote re right.\rdblquote\par
\tab She rose and looked uncertainly at Rik. The Captain stepped behind her, lifted the little chair and folded it with a snap.\par
\tab Rik jumped to his feet. \ldblquote Wait!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote If you please, my Lady,\rdblquote  said the Captain, holding the door open for her. \ldblquote My men will quiet him.\rdblquote\par
\tab Samia stopped at the threshold. \ldblquote They won\rquote t hurt him?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I doubt if he\rquote ll make us go to extremes. He will be easy handling.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Lady! Lady!\rdblquote  Rik called. \ldblquote I can prove it. I\rquote m from Earth.\rdblquote\par
\tab Samia stood irresolute for a moment. \ldblquote Let\rquote s hear what he has to say.\rdblquote\par
\tab The Captain said coldly, \ldblquote As you wish, my Lady.\rdblquote\par
\tab She returned, but not very far. She remained a step from the door.\par
\tab Rik was flushed. With the effort of remembering, his lips drew back into the caricature of a smile. He said, \ldblquote I remember Earth. It was radioactive. I remember the Forbidden Areas and the blue horizon at night. The soil glowed and nothing would grow in it. There were just a few spots men could live on. That\rquote s why I was a Spatio-analyst. That\rquote s why I didn\rquote t mind staying in space. My world was a dead world.\rdblquote\par
\tab Samia shrugged. \ldblquote Come along, Captain. He\rquote s simply raving.\rdblquote  \par
\tab But this time it was Captain Racety who stood there, open-mouthed. He muttered, \ldblquote A radioactive world!\rdblquote\par
\tab She said, \ldblquote You mean there \i is\i0  such a thing?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes.\rdblquote  He turned wondering eyes on her. \ldblquote Now where could he have picked \i that\i0  up?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote How could a world be radioactive and inhabited?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But there \i is\i0  one. And it \i is\i0  in the Sirius Sector. I don\rquote t remember its name. It might even be Earth.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It \i is\i0  Earth,\rdblquote  said Rik, proudly and with confidence. \ldblquote It is the oldest planet of the Galaxy. It is the planet on which the whole human race originated.\rdblquote\par
\tab The Captain said softly, \ldblquote That\rquote s so!\rdblquote\par
\tab Samia said, mind whirling, \ldblquote You mean the human race originated on this Earth?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No, no,\rdblquote  said the Captain abstractedly. \ldblquote That\rquote s superstition. It\rquote s just that that\rquote s how I came to hear about the radioactive planet. It claims to be Man\rquote s home planet.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I didn\rquote t know we were supposed to have a home planet.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I suppose we started somewhere, my Lady, but I doubt that anyone can possibly know on what planet it happened.\rdblquote\par
\tab With sudden decision he walked toward Rik. \ldblquote What else do you remember?\rdblquote\par
\tab He almost added \ldblquote boy,\rdblquote  but held it back.\par
\tab\ldblquote The ship mostly,\rdblquote  said Rik, \ldblquote and Spatio-analysis.\rdblquote\par
\tab Samia joined the Captain. They stood there, directly before Rik, and Samia felt the excitement returning. \ldblquote Then it\rquote s all true? But then how did he come to be psycho-probed?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Psycho-probed!\rdblquote  said Captain Racety thoughtfully. \ldblquote Suppose we ask him. Here, you, native or outworlder or whatever you are. How did you come to be psycho-probed?\rdblquote\par
\tab Rik looked doubtful. \ldblquote You all say that. Even Lona. But I don\rquote t know what the word means.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote When did you stop remembering, then?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote m not sure.\rdblquote  He began again, desperately. \ldblquote I was on a ship.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote We know that. Go on.\rdblquote\par
\tab Samia said, \ldblquote It\rquote s no use barking, Captain. You\rquote ll drive out what few wits are left him.\rdblquote\par
\tab Rik was entirely absorbed in wrenching at the dimness within his mind. The effort left no room for any emotion. It was to his own astonishment that he said, \ldblquote I\rquote m not afraid of him, Lady. I\rquote m trying to remember. There was danger. I\rquote m sure of that. Great danger to Florina, but I can\rquote t remember the details about it.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Danger to the whole planet?\rdblquote  Samia cast a swift glance at the Captain.\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes. It was in the currents.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What currents?\rdblquote  asked the Captain.\par
\tab\ldblquote The currents of space.\rdblquote\par
\tab The Captain spread his hands and let them drop. \ldblquote This is madness.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No, no. Let him go on.\rdblquote  The tide of belief had shifted to Samia again. Her lips were parted, her dark eyes gleamed and little dimples between cheek and chin made their appearance as she smiled. \ldblquote What are the currents of space?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The different elements,\rdblquote  said Rik vaguely. He had explained that before. He didn\rquote t want to go through that again.\par
\tab He went on rapidly, nearly incoherently, speaking as the thoughts came to him, driven by them. \ldblquote I sent a message to the local office on Sark. I remember that very clearly. I had to be careful. It was a danger that went beyond Florina. Yes. Beyond Florina. It was as wide as the Milky Way. It had to be handled carefully.\rdblquote\par
\tab He seemed to have lost all real contact with those who listened to him, to be living in a world of the past before which a curtain was tearing away in places. Valona placed a soothing hand upon his shoulder and said, \ldblquote Don\rquote t!\rdblquote  but he was unresponsive even to that.\par
\tab\ldblquote Somehow,\rdblquote  he went on breathlessly, \ldblquote my message was intercepted by some official on Sark. It was a mistake. I don\rquote t know how it happened.\rdblquote\par
\tab He frowned. \ldblquote I\rquote m sure I sent it to the local office on the Bureau\rquote s own wave length. Do you suppose the sub-ether could have been tapped?\rdblquote  He did not even wonder that the word \ldblquote sub-ether\rdblquote  came so easily to him.\par
\tab He might have been waiting for an answer, but his eyes were still unseeing. \ldblquote Anyway, when I landed on Sark they were waiting for me.\rdblquote\par
\tab Again a pause, this time long and meditative. The Captain did nothing to break it; he seemed to be meditating himself.\par
\tab Samia, however, said, \ldblquote Who was waiting for you? Who?\rdblquote\par
\tab Rik said, \ldblquote I--I don\rquote t know. I can\rquote t remember. It wasn\rquote t the office. It was someone of Sark. I remember speaking to him. He knew about the danger. He spoke of it. I\rquote m sure he spoke of it. We sat at a table together. I remember the table. He sat opposite me. It\rquote s as clear as space. We spoke for quite a while. It seems to me I wasn\rquote t anxious to give details. I\rquote m sure of that. I would have had to speak to the office first. And then he. . .\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes?\rdblquote  prompted Samia.\par
\tab\ldblquote He did something. He-- No, nothing more will come. \i Nothing will come!\i0\rdblquote\par
\tab He screamed the words and then there was silence, a silence that was anticlimactically broken by the prosaic buzz of the Captain\rquote s wrist communo.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote What is it?\rdblquote\par
\tab The answering voice was reedy and precisely respectful. \ldblquote A message to the Captain from Sark. It is requested that he accept it personally.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Very well. I will be at the sub-etherics presently.\rdblquote\par
\tab He turned to Samia. \ldblquote My Lady, may I suggest that it is, in any case, dinnertime.\rdblquote\par
\tab He saw that the girl was about to protest her lack of appetite, to urge him to leave and not to bother about her. He continued, more diplomatically, \ldblquote It is also time to feed these creatures. They are probably tired and hungry.\rdblquote\par
\tab Samia could say nothing against that. \ldblquote I must see them again, Captain.\rdblquote\par
\tab The Captain bowed silently. It might have been acquiescence. It might not.\par
\tab Samia of Fife was thrilled. Her studies of Florina satisfied a certain aspiration to intellect within her, but the Mysterious Case of the Psycho-probed Earthman (she thought of the matter in capitals) appealed to something much more primitive and much more demanding. It roused the sheer animal curiosity in her.\par
\tab It was a mystery!\par
\tab There were three points that fascinated her. Among these was not the perhaps reasonable question (under the circumstances) of whether the man\rquote s story was a delusion or a deliberate lie, rather than the truth. To believe it anything other than truth would spoil the mystery and Samia could not allow that.\par
\tab The three points were therefore these. (1) What was the danger that threatened Florina, or, rather, the entire Galaxy? (2) Who was the person who had psycho-probed the Earthman? (3) Why had the person used the psycho-probe?\par
\tab She was determined to sift the matter to her own thorough satisfaction. No one is so modest as not to believe himself a competent amateur sleuth, and Samia was far from modest.\par
\tab As soon after dinner as she could politely manage, she hurried down to the brig.\par
\tab She said to the guard, \ldblquote Open the door!\rdblquote\par
\tab The sailor remained perfectly erect, staring blankly and respectfully ahead. He said, \ldblquote If Your Ladyship pleases, the door is not to be opened.\rdblquote\par
\tab Samia gasped. \ldblquote How dare you say so? If you do not open the door instantly, the Captain shall be informed.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote If Your Ladyship pleases, the door is not to be opened. That is by the strict order of the Captain.\rdblquote\par
\tab She stormed up the levels once more, bursting into the Captain\rquote s stateroom like a tornado compressed into sixty inches.\par
\tab\ldblquote Captain!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote My Lady?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Have you ordered the Earthman and the native woman to be kept from me?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I believe, my Lady, it was agreed that you were to interview them only in my presence.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Before dinner, yes. But you saw they were harmless?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I saw that they \i seemed\i0  harmless.\rdblquote\par
\tab Samia simmered. \ldblquote In that case I order you to come with me now.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I cannot, my Lady. The situation has changed.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote In what way?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote They must be questioned by the proper authorities on Sark and until then I think they should be left alone.\rdblquote\par
\tab Samia\rquote s lower jaw dropped, but she rescued it from its undignified position almost immediately. \ldblquote Surely you are not going to deliver them to the Bureau of Florinian Affairs.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well,\rdblquote  temporized the Captain, \ldblquote that was certainly the original intention. They have left their village without permission. In fact they have left their planet without permission. In addition, they have taken secret passage on a Sarkite vessel.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The last was a mistake.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Was it?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote In any case, you knew all their crimes before our last interview.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But it was only at the interview that I heard what the so-called Earthman had to say.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote So-called. You said yourself that the planet Earth existed.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I said it might exist. But, my Lady, may I be so bold as to ask what you would like to see done with these people?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I think the Earthman\rquote s story should be investigated. He speaks of a danger to Florina and of someone on Sark who has deliberately attempted to keep knowledge of that danger from the proper authorities. I think it is even a case for my father. In fact I would take him to my father, when the proper time came.\rdblquote\par
\tab The Captain said, \ldblquote The cleverness of it all!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Are you being sarcastic, Captain?\rdblquote\par
\tab The Captain flushed. \ldblquote Your pardon, my Lady. I was referring to our prisoners. May I be allowed to speak at some length?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I don\rquote t know what you mean by \lquote some length,\rdblquote  she retorted angrily, \ldblquote but I suppose you may begin.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Thank you. In the first place, my Lady, I hope you will not minimize the importance of the disturbances on Florina.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What disturbances?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You cannot have forgotten the incident in the library.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote A patroller killed! Really, Captain!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And a second patroller killed this morning, my Lady, and a native as well. It is not very usual for natives to kill patrollers and here is one who has done it twice, and yet remains uncaught. Is he a lone hand? Is it an accident? Or is it all part of a carefully laid scheme?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Apparently you believe the last.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, I do. The murdering native had two accomplices. Their description is rather like that of our two stowaways.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You never said so!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I did not wish to alarm Your Ladyship. You\rquote ll remember, however, that I told you repeatedly that they could be dangerous.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Very well. What follows from all this?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What if the murders on Florina were simply side shows intended to distract the attention of the patroller squadrons while these two sneaked aboard our ship?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote That sounds so silly.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Does it? Why are they running away from Florina? We haven\rquote t asked them. Let us suppose they are running away from the patrollers since that is certainly the most reasonable assumption. Would they be running to Sark of all places? And on a ship that carries Your Ladyship? And then he claims to be a Spatio-analyst.\rdblquote\par
\tab Samia frowned. \ldblquote What of that?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote A year ago a Spatio-analyst was reported missing. The story was never given wide publicity. I knew, of course, because my ship was one of those that searched near space for signs of his ship. Whoever is backing these Florinian disorders has undoubtedly seized on that fact, and just knowing that the matter of the missing Spatio-analyst is known to them shows what a tight and unexpectedly efficient organization they have.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It might be that the Earthman and the missing Spatio-analyst have no connection.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No real connection, my Lady, undoubtedly. But to expect no connection at all is to expect too much of coincidence. It is an impostor we are dealing with. That is why he claims to have been psycho-probed.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote How can we prove he \i isn\rquote t\i0  a Spatio-analyst? He knows no details of the planet Earth beyond the bare fact that it is radioactive. He cannot pilot a ship. He knows nothing of Spatioanalysis. And he covers up by insisting he was psycho-probed. Do you see, my Lady?\rdblquote\par
\tab Samia could make no direct answer. \ldblquote But to what purpose?\rdblquote  she demanded.\par
\tab\ldblquote So that you might do exactly what you said you intended to do, my Lady.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Investigate the mystery?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No, my Lady. Take the man to your father.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I still see no point.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote There are several possibilities. At the best, he could be a spy upon your father, either for Florina or possibly for Trantor. I imagine old Abel of Trantor would certainly come forward to identify him as an Earthman, if for no other reason than to embarrass Sark by demanding the truth concerning this fictitious psycho-probing. At the worst, he will be your father\rquote s assassin.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Captain!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote My Lady?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote This is ridiculous!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Perhaps, my Lady. But if so, the Department of Security is also ridiculous. You will recall that just before dinner I was called away to receive a message from Sark.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote This is it.\rdblquote\par
\tab Samia received the thin translucent foil with its red lettering. It said: \ldblquote Two Florinians are reported to have taken secret, illegal passage on your ship. Secure them immediately. One of them may claim to be a Spatio-analyst and not a Florinian native. You are to take no action in this matter. You will be held strictly responsible for the safety of these people. They are to be held for delivery to Depsec. Extreme secrecy. Extreme urgency.\rdblquote\par
\tab Samia felt stunned. \ldblquote Depsec,\rdblquote  she said. \ldblquote The Department of Security.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Extreme secrecy,\rdblquote  said the Captain. \ldblquote I stretch a point to tell you this, but you have left me no choice, my Lady.\rdblquote\par
\tab She said, \ldblquote What will they do to him?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I cannot say for certain,\rdblquote  said the Captain. \ldblquote Certainly a suspected spy and assassin cannot expect gentle treatment. Probably his pretense will become partly a reality and he will learn what a psycho-probe is really like.\rdblquote\par
