\b THIRTEEN: The Yachtsman\par
\b0\f1\tab\par
\tab\par
\tab\f0 THE PORT\rquote S LIGHTS brightened evenly as the twilight deepened. At no time did the over-all illumination vary from that to be expected of a somewhat subdued late afternoon. At Port 9, as at the other yacht ports of Upper City, it was daylight throughout Florina\rquote s rotation. The brightness might grow unusually pronounced under the midday sun, but that was the only deviation.\par
\tab Markis Genro could tell that the day proper had passed only because, in passing into the port, he had left the colored night lights of the City behind him. Those were bright against the blackening sky but they made no pretense of substituting for day.\par
\tab Genro paused just inside the main entrance and seemed in no way impressed by the gigantic horseshoe with its three dozen hangars and five take-off pits. It was part of him, as it was part of any experienced yachtsman.\par
\tab He took a long cigarette, violet in color and tipped with the filmiest touch of silvery kyrt, and put it to his lips. He cupped his palms about the exposed tip and watched it glow to greenish life as he inhaled. It burned slowly and left no ash. An emerald smoke filtered out his nostrils.\par
\tab He murmured, \ldblquote Business as usual!\rdblquote\par
\tab A member of the yacht committee, in yachting costume, with only a discreet and tasteful lettering above one tunic button to indicate that he was a member of the committee, had moved up quickly to meet Genro, carefully avoiding any appearance of hurry.\par
\tab\ldblquote Ah, Genro! And why not business as usual?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Hello, Doty. I only thought that with all this fume and fuss going on it might occur to some bright boy to close the ports. Thank Sark it hasn\rquote t.\rdblquote\par
\tab The committeeman sobered. \ldblquote You know, it may come to that. Have you heard the latest?\rdblquote\par
\tab Genro grinned. \ldblquote How can you tell the latest from the next-to-the-latest?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, have you heard that it\rquote s definite now about the native? The killer?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You mean they\rquote ve caught him? I hadn\rquote t heard that.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No, they haven\rquote t caught him. But they know he\rquote s not in Lower City!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No? Where is he then?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Why, in Upper City. Here.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Go on.\rdblquote  Genro\rquote s eyes widened, then narrowed in disbelief. \par
\tab\ldblquote No, really,\rdblquote  said the committeeman, a little hurt, \ldblquote I have it for a fact. The patrollers are swooping up and down Kyrt Highway. They\rquote ve got City Park surrounded and they\rquote re using Central Arena as a co-ordination point. This is all authentic.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, maybe.\rdblquote  Genro\rquote s eyes roved carelessly over the hangared ships. \ldblquote I haven\rquote t been at g for two months, I think. Are there any new ships in the place?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No. Well, yes, there\rquote s Hjordesse\rquote s \i Flame Arrow\i0 .\rdblquote\par
\tab Genro shook his head. \ldblquote I\rquote ve seen that. It\rquote s all chromium and nothing else. I hate to think I\rquote ll have to end by designing my own.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Are you selling \i Comet V\i0 ?"\par
\tab\ldblquote Selling it or junking it. I\rquote m tired of these late models. They\rquote re too automatic. With their automatic relays and trajectory computers, they\rquote re killing the sport.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You know, I\rquote ve heard others say the same thing,\rdblquote  agreed the committeeman. \ldblquote Tell you what. If I hear of an old model in good condition on the market, I\rquote ll let you know.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Thanks. Mind if I wander about the place?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Of course not. Go ahead.\rdblquote  The committeeman grinned, waved, trotted away.\par
\tab Genro made his slow rounds, his cigarette, half gone, drooping from one side of his mouth. He stopped at each occupied hangar, appraising its contents shrewdly.\par
\tab At Hangar 26 he displayed a heightened interest. He looked over the low barrier and said, \ldblquote Squire?\rdblquote\par
\tab The call was one of polite inquiry, but after a pause of several moments he had to call again, a little more peremptorily, a little less politely.\par
\tab The Squire who emerged to view was not an impressive sight. For one thing, he was not in yachting costume. Secondly, he needed a shave, and his rather repellent-looking skullcap was yanked down in a most unfashionable manner. It seemed to cover half his face. Lastly, his attitude was one of peculiarly suspicious overcaution.\par
\tab Genro  said, \ldblquote I\rquote m Markis Genro. Is this your craft, sir?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, it is.\rdblquote  The words were slow and tense.\par
\tab Genro disregarded that. He tilted his head back and looked over the yacht\rquote s lines carefully. He removed what was left of his cigarette from between his lips and flicked it high in the air. It had not yet reached the high point of its arc when, with a little flash, it vanished.\par
\tab Genro said, \ldblquote I wonder if you\rquote d mind my coming in?\rdblquote  The other hesitated, then stepped aside. Genro entered.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote What kind of motor does the craft carry, sir?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Why do you ask?\rdblquote\par
\tab Genro was tall, skin and eyes were dark, hair crisp and cut short. He topped the other by half a head, and his smile showed white, evenly spaced teeth. He said, \ldblquote To be very frank, I\rquote m in the market for a new ship.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You mean you\rquote re interested in this one?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I don\rquote t know. Something like it, maybe, if the price is right. But anyway, I wonder if you\rquote d mind my looking at the controls and engines?\rdblquote\par
\tab The Squire stood there silently.\par
\tab Genro\rquote s voice grew a trifle colder. \ldblquote As you please, of course.\rdblquote  He turned away.\par
\tab The Squire said, \ldblquote I might sell.\rdblquote  He fumbled in his pockets. \ldblquote Here\rquote s the license!\rdblquote\par
\tab Genro looked at each side with a quick, experienced glance. He handed it back. \ldblquote You\rquote re Deamone?\rdblquote\par
\tab The Squire nodded. \ldblquote You can come in if you wish.\rdblquote\par
\tab Genro looked briefly at the large port-chronometer, the luminescent hands, sparking brightly even in the daylight illumination, indicating the beginning of the second hour after sunset.\par
\tab\ldblquote Thank you. Won\rquote t you lead the way?\rdblquote\par
\tab The Squire rummaged his pockets again and held out a booklet of key slivers. \ldblquote After you, sir.\rdblquote\par
\tab Genro took the booklet. He leafed through the slivers, looking at the small code marks for the \ldblquote ship stamp.\rdblquote  The other man made no attempt to help him.\par
\tab Finally he said, \ldblquote This one, I suppose?\rdblquote\par
\tab He walked up the short ramp to the air-lock balcony and considered the fine seam at the right of the lock carefully. \ldblquote I don\rquote t see--Oh, here it is,\rdblquote  and he stepped to the other side of the lock.\par
\tab Slowly, noiselessly, the lock yawned and Genro moved into the blackness. The red air-lock light went on automatically as the door closed behind them. The inner door opened and as they stepped into the ship proper white lights flickered on over all the length of the ship.\par
\par
\tab Myrlyn Terens had no choice. He no longer remembered the time, long since, when such a thing as \ldblquote choice\rdblquote  had existed. For three long, wretched hours, now, he had remained near Deamone\rquote s ship, waiting and helpless to do anything else. It had led to nothing till now. He did not see that it could lead to anything but capture.\par
\tab And then this fellow had come with an eye to the ship. To deal with him at all was madness. He could not possibly maintain his imposture at such close quarters. But then he could not possibly remain where he was, either.\par
\tab At least within the ship there might be food. Strange that that had not occurred to him before.\par
\tab There was.\par
\tab Terens said, \ldblquote It\rquote s close to dinnertime. Would you like to have something?\rdblquote\par
\tab The other had scarcely looked over his shoulder. \ldblquote Why, later, perhaps. Thank you.\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens did not urge him. He let him roam the ship and applied himself thankfully to the potted meat and cellulite-wrapped fruit. He drank thirstily. There was a shower across the corridor from the kitchen. He locked its door and bathed. It was a pleasure to be able to remove the tight skullcap, at least temporarily. He even found a shallow closet from which he could choose a change of clothing.\par
\tab He was far more master of himself when Genro returned.\par
\tab Genro said, \ldblquote Say, would you mind if I tried to fly this ship?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I have no objection. Can you handle this model?\rdblquote  asked Terens with an excellent imitation of nonchalance.\par
\tab\ldblquote I think so,\rdblquote  said the other with a little smile. \ldblquote I flatter myself I can handle any of the regular models. Anyway, I\rquote ve taken the liberty of calling the control tower and there\rquote s a take-off pit available. Here\rquote s my yachtsman\rquote s license if you\rquote d like to see it before I take over.\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens gave it as cursory a glance as Genro had given his. \ldblquote The controls are yours,\rdblquote  he said.\par
\par
\tab The ship rolled out of the hangar like an air-borne whale, moving slowly, its diamagnetized hull clearing the smooth-packed clay of the field by three inches.\par
\tab Terens watched Genro handling the controls with finger-tip precision. The ship was a live thing under his touch. The small replica of the field that was upon the visiplate shifted and changed with each tiny motion of every contact.\par
\tab The ship came to a halt, pinpointed at the lip of a take-off pit. The diamagnetic field strengthened progressively towards the ship\rquote s prow and it began tipping upward. Terens was mercifully unaware of this as the pilot room turned on its universal gimbals to meet the shifting gravity. Majestically, the ship\rquote s rear flanges fitted into the appropriate grooves of the pit. It stood upright, pointing to the sky.\par
\tab The duralite cover of the take-off pit slipped into its recess, revealing the neutralized lining, a hundred yards deep, that received the first energy thrusts of the hyperatomic motors.\par
\tab Genro kept up a cryptic exchange of information with the control tower. Finally, \ldblquote Ten seconds to take-off,\rdblquote  he said.\par
\tab A rising red thread in a quartz tube marked off the disappearing seconds. It made contact and the first surge of power tore backward.\par
\tab Terens grew heavier, felt himself pressing against the seat. Panic tore at him.\par
\tab He grunted, \ldblquote How does it handle?\rdblquote\par
\tab Genro seemed impervious to acceleration. His voice had almost its natural timbre as he said, \ldblquote Moderately well.\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens leaned back in his chair, trying to relax with the pressure, watching the stars in the visiplate turn hard and bright as the atmosphere vanished from between himself and them. The kyrt next to his skin felt cold and damp.\par
\par
\tab They were out in space now. Genro was putting the ship through its paces. Terens had no way of telling that first hand but he could see the stars march steadily across the visiplate as the yachtsman\rquote s long, slim fingers played with the controls as though they were the keys of a musical instrument. Finally a bulky orange segment of a globe filled the visiplate\rquote s clear surface.\par
\tab\ldblquote Not bad,\rdblquote  said Genro. \ldblquote You keep your craft in good condition, Deamone. It\rquote s small but it has its points.\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens said carefully, \ldblquote I suppose you\rquote d like to test its speed and its jumping capacity. You may, if you like. I have no objection.\rdblquote\par
\tab Genro nodded. \ldblquote Very well. Where do you suggest we take ourselves? What about--\rdblquote  He hesitated, then went on, \ldblquote Well, why not to Sark?\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens breathed a little more quickly. He had expected that. He was on the point of believing himself to be living in a world of magic. How things forced his moves, even without his connivance. It would not have been difficult to convince him that it was not \ldblquote things\rdblquote  but design that prompted the moves. His childhood had been steeped in the superstitions that the Squires fostered among the natives and such things are hard to outgrow. On Sark was Rik with his returning memories. The game was not over.\par
\tab He said wildly, \ldblquote Why not, Genro?\rdblquote\par
\tab Genro said, \ldblquote Sark it is then.\rdblquote\par
\tab With gathering speed, the globe of Florina slanted out beyond the visiplate\rquote s view and the stars returned.\par
\tab\ldblquote What\rquote s your best time on the Sark-Florina run?\rdblquote  asked Genro.\par
\tab\ldblquote Nothing record-breaking,\rdblquote  said Terens. \ldblquote About average.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Then you\rquote ve done it in better than six hours, I suppose?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote On occasion, yes.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Do you object to my trying to shave five?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Not at all,\rdblquote  said Terens.\par
\par
\tab It took hours to reach a point far enough from star-mass distortion of the space fabric to make a jump possible.\par
\tab Terens found wakefulness a torture. This was his third night with little or no sleep and the tensions of the days had exaggerated that lack.\par
\tab Genro looked at him askance. \ldblquote Why don\rquote t you turn in?\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens forced an expression of liveliness onto his sagging facial muscles. He said, \ldblquote It\rquote s nothing. Nothing.\rdblquote\par
\tab He yawned prodigiously and smiled in apology. The yachtsman turned back to his instruments and Terens\rquote  eyes glazed over once again.\par
\tab Seats in a space-yacht are comfortable by very necessity. They must cushion the person against accelerations. A man not particularly tired can easily and sweetly fall asleep upon them. Terens, who could, at the moment, have slept on broken glass, never knew when he passed the border line.\par
\tab He slept for hours; he slept as deeply and as dreamlessly as ever in his life.\par
\tab He did not stir; he showed no single sign of life other than his even breathing when the skullcap was removed from his head.\par
\par
\tab Terens woke blearily, slowly. For long minutes he had not the slightest notion of his whereabouts. He thought he was back in his Townman\rquote s cottage. The true state of affairs seeped back in stages. Eventually he could smile at Genro, who was still at the controls, and say, \ldblquote I guess I fell asleep.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I guess you did. There\rquote s Sark.\rdblquote  Genro nodded toward the large white crescent in the visiplate.\par
\tab\ldblquote When do we land?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote About an hour.\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens was awake enough now to sense a subtle change in the other\rquote s attitude. It was an icy shock to him that the steel-gray object in Genro\rquote s hand turned out to be the graceful barrel of a needle-gun.\par
\tab\ldblquote What in Space--\rdblquote  began Terens, rising to his feet.\par
\tab\ldblquote Sit down,\rdblquote  said Genro carefully. There was a skullcap in his other hand.\par
\tab Terens raised a hand to his head and his fingers found themselves clutching sandy hair.\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Genro, \ldblquote it\rquote s quite obvious. You\rquote re a native.\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens stared and said nothing.\par
\tab Genro said, \ldblquote I knew you were a native before I ever got on poor Deamone\rquote s ship.\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens\rquote  mouth was cotton-dry and his eyes burned. He watched the tiny, deadly muzzle of the gun and waited for a sudden, noiseless flash. He had carried it so far, so far, and had lost the gamble after all.\par
\tab Genro seemed in no hurry. He held the needle-gun steady and his words were even and slow.\par
\tab\ldblquote Your basic mistake, Townman, was the thought that you could really outwit an organized police force indefinitely. Even so, you would have done better if you hadn\rquote t made the unfortunate choice of Deamone as your victim.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I didn\rquote t choose him,\rdblquote  croaked Terens.\par
\tab\ldblquote Then call it luck. Alstare Deamone, some twelve hours ago, was standing in City Park, waiting for his wife. There was no reason, other than sentiment, for him to meet her there of all places. They had met in that very spot originally, and they met there again on every anniversary of that meeting. There\rquote s nothing particularly original about that sort of ceremony between young husbands and wives, but it seems important to them. Of course Deamone did not realize that the comparative isolation of the spot made him an appropriate victim for a murderer. Who would have thought that in Upper City?\par
\tab\ldblquote In the ordinary course of events the murder might not have been discovered for days. Deamone\rquote s wife, however, was on the scene within half an hour of the crime. The fact that her husband was not there astonished her. He was not the type, she explained, to leave in a fury because she herself was a trifle late. She was often late. He would more or less have expected that. It occurred to her that her husband might be waiting for her inside \lquote their\rquote  cave.\par
\tab\ldblquote Deamone had been waiting outside \lquote their\rquote  cave, naturally. It was the nearest one to the scene of the assault, consequently, and the one into which he was dragged. His wife entered that cave and found-well, you know what she found. She managed to relay the news to the Patrol Corps through our own Depsec offices, although she was almost incoherent with shock and hysteria.\par
\tab\ldblquote How does it feel, Townman, to kill a man in cold blood, leaving him to be found by his wife at the one spot most steeped with happy memories for them both?\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens was choking. He gasped out, through a red mist of anger and frustration, \ldblquote You Sarkites have killed millions of Florinians. Women. Children. You\rquote ve grown rich out of us. This yacht--\rdblquote  It was all he could manage.\par
\tab\ldblquote Deamone wasn\rquote t responsible for the state of affairs he found at birth,\rdblquote  said Genro. \ldblquote If you had been born a Sarkite, what would you have done? Resigned your estates, if any, and gone to work in the kyrt fields?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well then, shoot,\rdblquote  cried Terens, writhing. \ldblquote What are you waiting for?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote There\rquote s no hurry. There is plenty of time to finish my story. We weren\rquote t certain as to the identity of either the corpse or the murderer, but it was a very good guess that they were Deamone and yourself respectively. It seemed obvious to us from the fact that the ashes next to the body were of a patroller uniform that you were masquerading as a Sarkite. It seemed further probable that you would make for Deamone\rquote s yacht. Don\rquote t overestimate our stupidity, Townman.\par
\tab\ldblquote Matters were still rather complex. You were a desperate man. It was insufficient to track you down. You were armed and would undoubtedly commit suicide if trapped. Suicide was something we did not wish. They wanted you on Sark and they wanted you in working order.\par
\tab\ldblquote It was a particularly delicate affair for myself and it was quite necessary to convince Depsec that I could handle it alone, that I could get you to Sark without noise or difficulty. You\rquote ll have to admit that is just what I\rquote m doing.\par
\tab\ldblquote To tell you the truth, I wondered at first if you were really our man. You were dressed in ordinary business costume on the yacht-port grounds. It was in incredibly bad taste. No one, it seemed to me, would dream of impersonating a yachtsman without the proper costume. I thought you were being deliberately sent in as a decoy, that you were \i trying\i0  to be arrested while the man we wanted escaped in another direction.\par
\tab\ldblquote I hesitated and tested you in other ways. I fumbled with the ship\rquote s key in the wrong place. No ship ever invented opened at the right side of the air lock. It opens always and invariably at the left side. You never showed any surprise at my mistake. None at all. Then I asked you if your ship had ever made the Sark-Florina run in less than six hours. You said you had--occasionally. That is quite remarkable. The record time for the run is over nine hours.\par
\tab\ldblquote I decided you couldn\rquote t be a decoy. The ignorance was too supreme. You had to be naturally ignorant and probably the right man. It was only a question of your falling asleep (and it was obvious from your face that you needed sleep desperately), disarming you and covering you quietly with an adequate weapon. I removed your hat more out of curiosity than anything else. I wanted to see what a Sarkite costume looked like with a red-haired head sticking out of it.\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens kept his eyes on the whip. Perhaps Genro saw his jaw muscles bunch. Perhaps he simply guessed at what Terens was thinking.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote Of course I must not kill you, even if you jump me. I can\rquote t kill you even in self-defense. Don\rquote t think that gives you an advantage. Begin to move and I\rquote ll shoot your leg off.\rdblquote\par
\tab The fight went out of Terens. He put the heels of his palms to his forehead and sat rigid.\par
\tab Genro said softly, \ldblquote Do you know why I tell you all this?\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens did not answer.\par
\tab\ldblquote First,\rdblquote  said Genro, \ldblquote I rather enjoy seeing you suffer. I don\rquote t like murderers and I particularly don\rquote t like natives who kill Sarkites. I\rquote ve been ordered to deliver you alive but nothing in my orders says I have to make the trip pleasant for you. Secondly, it is necessary for you to be fully aware of the situation since, after we land on Sark, the next steps will be up to you.\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens looked up. \ldblquote What!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Depsec knows you\rquote re coming in. The Florinian regional office sent the word as soon as this craft cleared Florina\rquote s atmosphere. You can be sure of that. But I said it was quite necessary for me to convince Depsec that I could handle this alone and the fact that I have makes all the difference.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I don\rquote t understand you,\rdblquote  said Terens desperately.\par
\tab With composure, Genro answered, \ldblquote I said \lquote they\rquote  wanted you on Sark, \lquote they\rquote  wanted you in working order. By \lquote they\rquote  I don\rquote t mean Depsec, I mean Trantor!\rdblquote\par
