\b FOURTEEN: The Renegade\par
\b0\f1\tab\par
\tab\par
\tab\f0 SELIM JUNZ had never been the phlegmatic type. A year of frustration had done nothing to improve that. He could not sip wine carefully while his mental orientation sat upon suddenly trembling foundations. In short, he was not Ludigan Abel.\par
\tab And when Junz had done with his angry shouting that on no account was Sark to be allowed freedom to kidnap and imprison a member of the I.S.B. regardless of the condition of Trantor\rquote s espionage network, Abel merely said, \ldblquote I think you had better spend the night here, Doctor.\rdblquote\par
\tab Junz said freezingly, \ldblquote I have better things to do.\rdblquote\par
\tab Abel said, \ldblquote No doubt, man, no doubt. Just the same, if my men are being blasted to death, Sark must be bold indeed. There is a great possibility that some accident may happen to you before the night is over. Let us wait a night then and see what comes of a new day.\rdblquote\par
\tab Junz\rquote s protests against inaction came to nothing. Abel, without ever losing his cool, almost negligent air of indifference, was suddenly hard of hearing. Junz was escorted with firm courtesy to a chamber.\par
\tab In bed, he stared at the faintly luminous, frescoed ceiling (on which glowed a moderately skillful copy of Lenhaden\rquote s \ldblquote Battle of the Arcturian Moons\rdblquote ) and knew he would not sleep. Then he caught one whiff, a faint one, of the gas, somnin, and was asleep before he could catch another. Five minutes later, when a forced draft swept the room clean of the anesthetic, enough had been administered to assure a healthful eight hours.\par
\par
\tab He was awakened in the cold half-light of dawn. He blinked up at Abel.\par
\tab\ldblquote What time is it?\rdblquote  he asked.\par
\tab\ldblquote Six.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Great Space.\rdblquote  He looked about and thrust his bony legs out from under the sheet. \ldblquote You\rquote re up early.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I haven\rquote t slept.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I feel the lack, believe me. I don\rquote t respond to antisomnin as I did when I was younger.\rdblquote\par
\tab Junz murmured, \ldblquote If you will allow me a moment.\rdblquote\par
\tab This once his morning preparations for the day took scarcely more than that. He re-entered the room, drawing the belt about his tunic and adjusting the magneto-seam.\par
\tab\ldblquote Well?\rdblquote  he asked. \ldblquote Surely you don\rquote t wake through the night and rouse me at six unless you have something to tell me.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You\rquote re right. You\rquote re right.\rdblquote  Abel sat down on the bed vacated by Junz and threw his head back in a laugh. It was high-pitched and rather subdued. His teeth showed, their strong, faintly yellow plastic incongruous against his shrunken gums.\par
\tab\ldblquote I beg your pardon, Junz,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote I am not quite myself. This drugged wakefulness has me a little lightheaded. I almost think I will advise Trantor to replace me with a younger man.\rdblquote\par
\tab Junz said, with a flavor of sarcasm not entirely unmixed with sudden hope, \ldblquote You find they haven\rquote t got the Spatio-analyst after all?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No, they do. I\rquote m sorry but they do. I\rquote m afraid that my amusement is due entirely to the fact that our nets are intact.\rdblquote\par
\tab Junz would have liked to say, \ldblquote Damn your nets,\rdblquote  but refrained. \par
\tab Abel went on, \ldblquote There is no doubt they knew Khorov was one of our agents. They may know of others on Florina. Those are small fry. The Sarkites knew that and never felt it worth while to do more than hold them under observation.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote They killed one,\rdblquote  Junz pointed out.\par
\tab\ldblquote They did not,\rdblquote  retorted Abel. \ldblquote It was one of the Spatio-analyst\rquote s own companions in a patroller disguise who used the blaster.\rdblquote\par
\tab Junz stared. \ldblquote I don\rquote t understand.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It\rquote s a rather complicated story. Won\rquote t you join me at breakfast? I need food badly.\rdblquote\par
\par
\tab Over the coffee, Abel told the story of the last thirty-six hours. Junz was stunned. He put down his own coffee cup, half full, and returned to it no more. \ldblquote Even allowing them to have stowed away on that ship of all ships, the fact still remains they might not have been detected. If you send men to meet that ship as it lands--\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Bah. You know better than that. No modem ship could fail to detect the presence of excess body heat.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It might have been overlooked. Instruments may be infallible but men are not.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Wishful thinking. Look here. At the very time that the ship with the Spatio-analyst aboard is approaching Sark, there are reports of excellent reliability that the Squire of Fife is in conference with the other Great Squires. These intercontinental conferences are spaced as widely as the stars of the Galaxy. Coincidence?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote An intercontinental conference over a Spatio-analyst?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote An unimportant subject in itself, yes. But we have made it important. The I.S.B. has been searching for him for nearly a year with remarkable pertinacity.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Not the I.S.B.,\rdblquote  insisted Junz. \ldblquote Myself. I\rquote ve been working in almost an unofficial manner.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The Squires don\rquote t know that and wouldn\rquote t believe it if you told them. Then, too, Trantor has been interested.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote At my request.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Again they don\rquote t know that and wouldn\rquote t believe it.\rdblquote\par
\tab Junz stood up and his chair moved automatically away from the table. Hands firmly interlocked behind his back, he strode the carpet. Up and back. Up and back. At intervals he glanced harshly at Abel.\par
\tab Abel turned unemotionally to a second cup of coffee.\par
\tab Junz said, \ldblquote How do you know all this?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote All what?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Everything. How and when the Spatio-analyst stowed away. How and in what manner the Townman has been eluding capture. Is it your purpose to deceive me?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote My dear Dr. Junz.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You admitted you had your men watching for the Spatio-analyst independently of myself. You saw to it that I was safely out of the way last night, leaving nothing to chance.\rdblquote  Junz remembered, suddenly, that whiff of somnin.\par
\tab\ldblquote I spent a night, Doctor, in constant communication with certain of my agents. What I did and what I learned comes under the heading of, shall we say, classified material. You had to be out of the way, and yet safe. What I have told you just now I learned from my agents last night.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote To learn what you did you would need spies in the Sarkite government itself.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, naturally.\rdblquote\par
\tab Junz whirled on the ambassador. \ldblquote Come, now.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You find that surprising? To be sure, Sark is proverbial for the stability of its government and the loyalty of its people. The reason is simple enough since even the poorest Sarkite is an aristocrat in comparison with Florinians and can consider himself, however fallaciously, to be a member of a ruling class.\par
\tab\ldblquote Consider, though, that Sark is not the world of billionaires most of the Galaxy thinks it is. A year\rquote s residence must have well convinced you of that. Eighty per cent of its population has its living standard at a par with that of other worlds and not much higher than the standard of Florina itself. There will always be a certain number of Sarkites who, in their hunger, will be sufficiently annoyed with the small fraction of the population obviously drenched in luxury to lend themselves to my uses.\par
\tab\ldblquote It is the great weakness of the Sarkite government that for centuries they have associated rebellion only with Florina. They have forgotten to watch over themselves.\rdblquote\par
\tab Junz said, \ldblquote These small Sarkites, assuming they exist, can\rquote t do you much good.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Individually, no. Collectively, they form useful tools for our more important men. There are members even of the real ruling class who have taken the lessons of the last two centuries to heart. They are convinced that in the end Trantor will have established its rule over all the Galaxy, and, I believe, rightly convinced. They even suspect that the final dominion may take place within their lifetimes, and they prefer to establish themselves, in advance, on the winning side.\rdblquote\par
\tab Junz grimaced. \ldblquote You make interstellar politics sound a very dirty game.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It is, but disapproving of dirt doesn\rquote t remove it. Nor are all its facets unrelieved dirt. Consider the idealist. Consider the few men in Sark\rquote s government who serve Trantor neither for money nor for promises of power but only because they honestly believe that a unified Galactic government is best for humanity and that only Trantor can bring such a government about. I have one such man, my best one, in Sark\rquote s Department of Security, and at this moment he is bringing in the Townman.\rdblquote\par
\tab Junz said, \ldblquote You said he had been captured.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote By Depsec, yes. But my man is Depsec \i and my man\i0 .\rdblquote  For a moment Abel frowned and turned pettish. \ldblquote His usefulness will be sharply reduced after this. Once he lets the Townman get away, it will mean demotion at the best and imprisonment at the worst. Oh well!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What are you planning now?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I scarcely know. First, we must have our Townman. I am sure of him only to the point of arrival at the spaceport. What happens thereafter . . .\rdblquote  Abel shrugged, and his old, yellowish skin stretched parchmentlike over his cheekbones.\par
\tab Then he added, \ldblquote The Squires will be waiting for the Townman as well. They are under the impression they have him, and until one or the other of us has him in our fists, nothing more can happen.\rdblquote\par
\tab But that statement was wrong.\par
\par
\tab Strictly speaking, all foreign embassies throughout the Galaxy maintained extraterritorial rights over the immediate areas of their location. Generally this amounted to nothing more than a pious wish, except where the strength of the home planet enforced respect. In actual practice it meant that only Trantor could truly maintain the independence of its envoys.\par
\tab The grounds of the Trantorian Embassy covered nearly a square mile and within it armed men in Trantorian Costume and insignia maintained patrol. No Sarkite might enter but on invitation, and no armed Sarkite on any account. To be sure, the sum of Trantorian men and arms could withstand the determined attack of a single Sarkite armored regiment for not more than two or three hours, but behind the small band was the power of reprisal from the organized might of a million worlds.\par
\tab It remained inviolate.\par
\tab It could even maintain direct material communication with Trantor, without the need of passing through Sarkite ports of entry or debarkation. From the hold of a Trantorian mothership, hovering just outside the hundred-mile limit that marked off the boundary between \ldblquote planetary space\rdblquote  and \ldblquote free space,\rdblquote  small gyro-ships, vane-equipped for atmospheric travel with minimum power expenditure, might emerge and needle down (half coasting, half driven) to the small port maintained within the embassy grounds.\par
\tab The gyro-ship which now appeared over the embassy port, however, was neither scheduled nor Trantorian. The mosquito-might of the embassy was brought quickly and truculently into play. A needle-cannon lifted its puckered muzzle into the air. Force screens went up.\par
\tab Radioed messages whipped back and forth. Stubborn words rode the impulses upward, agitated ones slipped down.\par
\tab Lieutenant Camrum turned away from the instrument and said, \ldblquote I don\rquote t know. He claims he\rquote ll be shot out of the sky in two minutes if we don\rquote t let him down. He claims sanctuary.\rdblquote\par
\tab Captain Elyut had just entered. He said, \ldblquote Sure. Then Sark will claim we\rquote re interfering in politics and if Trantor decides to let things ride, you and I are broken as a gesture. \lquote Who is he?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Won\rquote t say,\rdblquote  said the lieutenant with more than a little exasperation. \ldblquote Says he must speak to the Ambassador. Suppose you tell me what to do, Captain.\rdblquote\par
\tab The short-wave receiver sputtered and a voice, half hysterical, said, \ldblquote Is anyone \i there?\i0  I\rquote m just coming down, that\rquote s all. Really! I can\rquote t wait another moment, I tell you.\rdblquote  It ended in a squeak.\par
\tab The captain said, \ldblquote Great Space, I know that voice. Let him down! My responsibility!\rdblquote\par
\tab The orders went out. The gyro-ship sank vertically, more quickly than it should have, the result of a hand at the controls that was both inexperienced and panicky. The needle-cannon maintained focus.\par
\tab The captain established a through line to Abel and the embassy was thrown into full emergency. The flight of Sarkite ships that hovered overhead not ten minutes after the first vessel had landed maintained a threatening vigil for two hours, then departed.\par
\par
\tab They sat at dinner, Abel, Junz and the newcomer. With admirable aplomb, considering the circumstances, Abel had acted the unconcerned host. For hours he had refrained from asking why a Great Squire needed sanctuary.\par
\tab Junz was far less patient. He hissed at Abel, \ldblquote Space! What are you going to do with him?\rdblquote\par
\tab And Abel smiled back. \ldblquote Nothing. At least until I find out whether I have my Townman or not. I like to know what my hand is before tossing chips onto the table. And since he\rquote s come to me, waiting will rattle him more than it will us.\rdblquote\par
\tab He was right. Twice the Squire launched into rapid monolog and twice Abel said, \ldblquote My dear Squire! Surely serious conversation is unpleasant on an empty stomach.\rdblquote  He smiled gently and ordered dinner.\par
\tab Over the wine, the Squire tried again. He said, \ldblquote You\rquote ll want to know why I have left Steen Continent.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I cannot conceive of any reason,\rdblquote  admitted Abel, \ldblquote for the Squire of Steen ever to have fled from Sarkite vessels.\rdblquote\par
\tab Steen watched them carefully. His slight figure and thin, pale face were tense with calculation. His long hair was bound into carefully arranged tufts held by tiny clips that rubbed against one another with a rustling sound whenever he moved his head, as though to call attention to his disregard for the current Sarkite clipped-hair fashion. A faint fragrance came from his skin and clothing.\par
\tab Abel, who did not miss the slight tightening of Junz\rquote s lips and the quick way in which the Spatio-analyst patted his own short, woolly hair, thought how amusing Junz\rquote s reaction might have been if Steen had appeared more typically, with rouged cheeks and coppered fingernails.\par
\tab Steen said, \ldblquote There was an intercontinental conference today.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Really?\rdblquote  said Abel.\par
\tab Abel listened to the tale of the conference without a quiver of countenance.\par
\tab\ldblquote And we have twenty-four hours,\rdblquote  Steen said indignantly. \ldblquote It\rquote s sixteen hours now. Really!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And you\rquote re X,\rdblquote  cried Junz, who had been growing increasingly restless during the recitation. \ldblquote You\rquote re X. You\rquote ve come here because he\rquote s caught you. Well now, that\rquote s fine. Abel, here\rquote s our proof as to the identity of the Spatio-analyst. We can use him to force a surrender of the man.\rdblquote\par
\tab Steen\rquote s thin voice had difficulty making itself heard over Junz\rquote s staunch baritone.\par
\tab\ldblquote Now really. I say, now really. You\rquote re mad. Stop it! Let me speak, I tell you. . . . Your Excellency, I can\rquote t remember this man\rquote s name.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Dr. Selim Junz, Squire.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well then, Dr. Selim Junz, I have never in my life seen this idiot or Spatio-analyst or whatever in the world he may be. Really! I never heard such nonsense. I am certainly not X. Really! I\rquote ll thank you not even to use the silly letter. Imagine believing Fife\rquote s ridiculous melodrama! Really!\rdblquote\par
\tab Junz clung to his notion. \ldblquote Why did you run then?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Good Sark, isn\rquote t it clear? Oh, I could choke. Really! Look here, don\rquote t you see what Fife was doing?\rdblquote\par
\tab Abel interrupted quietly. \ldblquote If you\rquote ll explain, Squire, there will be no interruptions.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, thank \i you\i0  at least.\rdblquote  He continued, with an air of wounded dignity. \ldblquote The others don\rquote t think much of me because I don\rquote t see the point of bothering with documents and statistics and all those boring details. But, really, what is the Civil Service for, I\rquote d like to know? If a Great Squire can\rquote t \i be\i0  a Great Squire?\par
\tab\ldblquote Still that doesn\rquote t mean I\rquote m a ninny, you know, just because I like my comfort. Really! Maybe the others are blind, but I can see that Fife doesn\rquote t give a darn for the Spatio-analyst. I don\rquote t even think he exists. Fife just got the idea a year ago and he\rquote s been manipulating it ever since.\par
\tab\ldblquote He\rquote s been playing us for fools and idiots. Really! And so the others are. Disgusting fools! He\rquote s \i arranged\i0  all this perfectly awful nonsense about idiots and Spatio-analysis. I wouldn\rquote t be surprised if the native who\rquote s supposed to be killing patrollers by the dozen isn\rquote t just one of Fife\rquote s spies in a red wig. Or if he\rquote s a real native, I suppose Fife has hired him.\par
\tab\ldblquote I wouldn\rquote t put it past Fife. Really! He would use natives against his own kind. That\rquote s how low he is.\par
\tab\ldblquote Anyway, it\rquote s obvious that he\rquote s using it just as an excuse to ruin the rest of us and to make himself dictator of Sark. Isn\rquote t it obvious to you?\par
\tab\ldblquote There isn\rquote t any X at all, but tomorrow, unless he\rquote s stopped, he\rquote ll spread the sub-etherics full of conspiracies and declarations of emergencies and he\rquote ll have himself declared Leader. We haven\rquote t had a Leader on Sark in five hundred years but that won\rquote t stop Fife. He\rquote d just let the constitution go hang. Really!\par
\tab\ldblquote Only I mean to stop him. That\rquote s why I had to leave. If I were still in Steen, I\rquote d be under house arrest.\par
\tab\ldblquote As soon as the conference was over I had my own personal port checked, and, you know, his men had taken over. It was in clear disregard of continental autonomy. It was the act of a cad. Really! But nasty as he is, he isn\rquote t so bright. He thought some of us might try to leave the planet so he had the spaceports watched, but\rdblquote --here he smiled in vulpine fashion and emitted the ghost of a giggle--\rdblquote it didn\rquote t occur to him to watch the gyro-ports.\par
\tab\ldblquote Probably he thought there wasn\rquote t a place on the planet that would be safe for us. But I thought of the Trantorian Embassy. It\rquote s more than the others did. They make me tired. Especially Bort. Do you know Bort? He\rquote s terribly uncouth. Actually \i dirty\i0 . Talks at me as though there were something wrong with being clean and smelling pleasant.\rdblquote\par
\tab He put his finger tips to his nose and inhaled gently.\par
\tab Abel put a light hand on Junz\rquote s wrist as the latter moved restlessly in his seat. Abel said, \ldblquote You have left a family behind. Have you thought that Fife can still hold a weapon over you?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I couldn\rquote t very well pile all my pretty ones in my gyroplane.\rdblquote  He reddened a trifle. \ldblquote Fife wouldn\rquote t dare touch them. Besides, I\rquote ll be back in Steen tomorrow.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote How?\rdblquote  asked Abel.\par
\tab Steen looked at him in astonishment. His thin lips parted. \ldblquote I\rquote m offering alliance, Your Excellency. You can\rquote t pretend Trantor isn\rquote t \i interested\i0  in Sark. Surely you\rquote ll tell Fife that any attempt to change Sark\rquote s constitution would necessitate Trantor\rquote s intervention.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I scarcely see how that can be done, even if I felt my government would back me,\rdblquote  said Abel.\par
\tab\ldblquote How can it \i not\i0  be done?\rdblquote  asked Steen indignantly. \ldblquote If he controls the entire kyrt trade he\rquote ll raise the price, ask concessions for rapid delivery and all sorts of things.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Don\rquote t the five of you control the price as is?\rdblquote\par
\tab Steen threw himself back in the seat. \ldblquote Well, really! I don\rquote t know all the details. Next you\rquote ll be asking me for figures. Goodness, you\rquote re as bad as Bort.\rdblquote  Then he recovered and giggled. \ldblquote I\rquote m just teasing, of course. What I mean is that, with Fife out of the way, Trantor \i might\i0  make an arrangement with the rest of us. In return for your help, it would only be right that Trantor get preferential treatment, or even maybe a small interest in the trade.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And how would we keep intervention from developing into a Galaxy-wide war?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, but really, don\rquote t you see? It\rquote s plain as day. You wouldn\rquote t be \i aggressors\i0 . You would just be preventing civil war to keep the kyrt trade from disruption. I\rquote d announce that I\rquote d appealed to you for help. It would be worlds removed from aggression. The whole Galaxy would be on your side. Of course, if Trantor benefits from it afterward, why, that\rquote s nobody\rquote s business at all. Really!\rdblquote\par
\tab Abel put his gnarled fingers together and regarded them. \ldblquote I can\rquote t believe you really mean to join forces with Trantor.\rdblquote\par
\tab An intense look of hatred passed momentarily over Steen\rquote s weakly smiling face. He said, \ldblquote Rather Trantor than Fife.\rdblquote\par
\tab Abel said, \ldblquote I don\rquote t like threatening force. Can\rquote t we wait and let matters develop a bit--\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No, no,\rdblquote  cried Steen. \ldblquote Not a day. Really! If you\rquote re not firm now, right now, it will be too late. Once the deadline is past, he\rquote ll have gone too far to retreat without losing face. If you\rquote ll help me now, the people of Steen will back me, the other Great Squires will join me. If you wait even a day, Fife\rquote s propaganda mill will begin to grind. I\rquote ll be smeared as a renegade. Really! I! \i I!\i0  A renegade! He\rquote ll use all the anti-Trantor prejudice he can whip up and you know, meaning no offense, that\rquote s quite a bit.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Suppose we ask him to allow us to interview the Spatio-analyst?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What good will that do? He\rquote ll play both ends. He\rquote ll tell us the Florinian idiot is a Spatio-analyst, but he\rquote ll tell you the Spatio-analyst is a Florinian idiot. You don\rquote t know the man. He\rquote s \i awful!\i0\rdblquote\par
\tab Abel considered that. He hummed to himself, his forefinger keeping gentle time. Then he said, \ldblquote We have the Townman, you know.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What Townman?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The one who killed the patrollers and the Sarkite.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh! Well, really! Do you suppose Fife will care about that if it\rquote s a question of taking all Sark?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I think so. You see, it isn\rquote t that we have the Townman. It\rquote s the circumstances of his capture. I think, Squire, that Fife will listen to me and listen very humbly, too.\rdblquote\par
\tab For the first time in his acquaintance with Abel, Junz sensed a lessening of coolness in the old man\rquote s voice, a substitution for it of satisfaction, almost of triumph.\par
\tab\par
\tab\par
\b FIFTEEN: The Captive\par
\b0\f1\tab\par
\tab\par
\tab\f0 IT WAS not very usual for the Lady Samia of Fife to feel frustrated. It was unprecedented, even inconceivable, that she had felt frustrated for hours now.\par
\tab The commander of the spaceport was Captain Racety all over again. He was polite, almost obsequious, looked unhappy, expressed his regrets, denied the least willingness to contradict her, and stood like iron against her plainly stated wishes.\par
\tab She was finally forced from stating her desires to demanding her rights as though she were a common Sarkite. She said, \ldblquote I suppose that as a citizen I have the right to meet any incoming vessel if I wish.\rdblquote\par
\tab She was poisonous about it.\par
\tab The commander cleared his throat and the expression of pain on his lined face grew, if anything, clearer and more definite. Finally he said, \ldblquote As a matter of fact, my Lady, we have no wish at all to exclude you. It is only that we have received specific orders from the Squire, your father, to forbid your meeting the ship.\rdblquote\par
\tab Samia said frozenly, \ldblquote Are you ordering me to leave the port, then?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No, my Lady.\rdblquote  The commander was glad to compromise. \ldblquote We were not ordered to exclude you from the port. If you wish to remain here you may do so. But, with all due respect, we will have to stop you from approaching closer to the pits.\rdblquote\par
\tab He was gone and Samia sat in the futile luxury of her private ground-car, a hundred feet inside the outermost entrance of the port. They had been waiting and watching for her. They would probably keep on watching her. If she as much as rolled a wheel onward, she thought indignantly, they would probably cut her power-drive.\par
\tab She gritted her teeth. It was unfair of her father to do this. It was all of a piece. They always treated her as though she understood nothing. Yet she had thought he understood.\par
\tab He had risen from his seat to greet her, a thing he never did for anyone else now that Mother was dead. He had clasped her, squeezed her tightly, abandoned all his work for her. He had even sent his secretary out of the room because he knew she was repelled by the native\rquote s still, white countenance.\par
\tab It was almost like the old days before Grandfather died when Father had not yet become Great Squire.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote Mia, child, I\rquote ve counted the hours. I never knew it was such a long way from Florina. When I heard that those natives had hidden on your ship, the one I had sent just to insure your safety, I was nearly wild.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Daddy! There was nothing to worry about.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Wasn\rquote t there? I almost sent out the entire fleet to take you off and bring you in with full military security.\rdblquote\par
\tab They laughed together at the thought. Minutes passed before Samia could bring the conversation back to the subject that filled her.\par
\tab She said casually, \ldblquote What are you going to do with the stowaways, Dad?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Why do you want to know, Mia?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You don\rquote t think they\rquote ve plans to assassinate you, or anything like that?\rdblquote\par
\tab Fife smiled. \ldblquote You shouldn\rquote t think morbid thoughts.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You don\rquote t think so, do you?\rdblquote  she insisted.\par
\tab\ldblquote Of course not.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Good! Because I\rquote ve talked to them, Dad, and I just don\rquote t believe they\rquote re anything more than poor harmless people. I don\rquote t care what Captain Racety says.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote They\rquote ve broken a considerable number of laws for \lquote poor harmless people,\rquote  Mia.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You can\rquote t treat them as common criminals, Dad.\rdblquote  Her voice rose in alarm.\par
\tab\ldblquote How else?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The man isn\rquote t a native. He\rquote s from a planet called Earth and he\rquote s been psycho-probed and he\rquote s not responsible.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well then, dear, Depsec will realize that. Suppose you leave it to them.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No, it\rquote s too important to just leave to them. They won\rquote t understand. Nobody understands. Except me!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Only you in the whole world, Mia?\rdblquote  he asked indulgently, and put out a finger to stroke a lock of hair that had fallen over her forehead.\par
\tab Samia said with energy, \ldblquote Only I! Only I! Everyone else is going to think he\rquote s crazy, but I\rquote m \i sure\i0  he isn\rquote t. He says there is some great danger to Florina and to all the Galaxy. He\rquote s a Spatio-analyst and you know they specialize in cosmogony. He would \i know!\i0 "\par
\tab\ldblquote How do you know he\rquote s a Spatio-analyst, Mia?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote He says so.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And what are the details of the danger?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote He doesn\rquote t know. He\rquote s been psycho-probed. Don\rquote t you see that that\rquote s the best evidence of all? He knew too much. Someone was interested in keeping it dark.\rdblquote  Her voice instinctively fell and grew huskily confidential. She restrained an impulse to look over her shoulder. She said, \ldblquote If his theories were false, don\rquote t you see, there wouldn\rquote t have been any need to psycho-probe him.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Why didn\rquote t they kill him, if that\rquote s the case?\rdblquote  asked Fife and instantly regretted the question. There was no use in teasing the girl.\par
\tab Samia thought awhile, fruitlessly, then said, \ldblquote If you\rquote ll order Depsec to let me speak to him, I\rquote ll find out. He trusts me. I know he does. I\rquote ll get more out of him than Depsec can. Please tell Depsec to let me see him, Dad. It\rquote s \i very\i0  important.\rdblquote\par
\tab Fife squeezed her clenched fists gently and smiled at her. \ldblquote Not yet, Mia. Not yet. In a few hours we\rquote ll have the third person in our hands. After that, perhaps.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The third person? The native who did all the killings?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Exactly. The ship carrying him will land in about an hour.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And you won\rquote t do anything with the native girl and the Spatio-analyst till then?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Not a thing.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Good! I\rquote ll meet the ship.\rdblquote  She rose.\par
\tab\ldblquote Where are you going, Mia?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote To the port, Father. I have a great deal to ask of this other native.\rdblquote  She laughed. \ldblquote I\rquote ll show you that your daughter can be quite a detective.\rdblquote\par
\tab But Fife did not respond to her laughter. He said, \ldblquote I\rquote d rather you didn\rquote t.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Why not?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It\rquote s essential that there be nothing out of the way about this man\rquote s arrival. You\rquote d be too conspicuous at the port.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What of it?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I can\rquote t explain statecraft to you, Mia.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Statecraft, pooh.\rdblquote  She leaned toward him, pecked a quick kiss at the center of his forehead and was gone.\par
\tab Now she sat helplessly car-bound in the port while far overhead there was a growing speck in the sky, dark against the brightness of the late afternoon.\par
\tab She pressed the button that opened the utility compartment and took out her polo-glasses. Ordinarily they were used to follow the gyrating antics of the one-man speedsters which took part in stratospheric polo. They could be put to more serious use too. She put them to her eyes and the descending dot became a ship in miniature, the ruddy glow of its stern drive plainly visible.\par
\tab She would at least see the men as they left, learn as much as she could by the one sense of sight, arrange an interview somehow, \i somehow\i0  thereafter.\par
\tab Sark filled the visiplate. A continent and half an ocean, obscured in part by the dead cotton-white of clouds, lay below.\par
\tab Genro said, his words a trifle uneven as the only indication that the better part of his mind was perforce on the controls before him, \ldblquote The spaceport will not be heavily guarded. That was at my suggestion too. I said that any unusual treatment of the arrival of the ship might warn Trantor that something was up. I said that success depended upon Trantor being at no time aware of the true state of affairs until it was too late. Well, never mind that.\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens shrugged his shoulders glumly. \ldblquote What\rquote s the difference?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Plenty, to you. I will use the landing pit nearest the East Gate. You will get out the safety exit in the rear as soon as I land. Walk quickly but not too quickly toward that gate. I have some papers that may get you through without trouble and may not. I\rquote ll leave it to you to take necessary action if there is trouble. From past history, I judge I can trust you that far. Outside the gate there will be a car waiting to take you to the embassy. That\rquote s all.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What about you?\rdblquote\par
\tab Slowly Sark was changing from a huge featureless sphere of blinding browns and greens and blues and cloud-white into something more alive, into a surface broken by rivers and wrinkled by mountains.\par
\tab Genro\rquote s smile was cool and humorless. \ldblquote Your worries may end with yourself. When they find you gone, I may be shot as a traitor. If they find me completely helpless and physically unable to stop you, they may merely demote me as a fool. The latter, I suppose, is preferable, so I will ask you, before you leave, to use a neuronic whip on me.\rdblquote\par
\tab The Townman said, \ldblquote Do you know what a neuronic whip is like?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Quite.\rdblquote  There were small drops of perspiration at his temples. \par
\tab\ldblquote How do you know I won\rquote t kill you afterward? I\rquote m a Squire-killer, you know.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I know. But killing me won\rquote t help you. It will just waste your time. I\rquote ve taken worse chances.\rdblquote\par
\tab The surface of Sark as viewed in the visiplate was expanding, its edges rushed out past the border of visibility, its center grew and the new edges rushed out in turn. Something like the rainbow of a Sarkite city could be made out.\par
\tab\ldblquote I hope,\rdblquote  said Genro, \ldblquote you have no ideas of striking out on your own. Sark is no place for that. It\rquote s either Trantor or the Squires. Remember.\rdblquote\par
\tab The view was definitely that of a city now and a green-brown patch on its outskirts expanded and became a spaceport below them. It floated up toward them at a slowing pace.\par
\tab Genro said, \ldblquote If Trantor doesn\rquote t have you in the next hour the Squires will have you before the day is out. I don\rquote t guarantee what Trantor will do to you, but I can guarantee what Sark will do to you.\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens had been in the Civil Service. He knew what Sark would do with a Squire-killer.\par
\tab The port held steady in the visiplate, but Genro no longer regarded it. He was switching to instruments, riding the pulse-beam downward. The ship turned slowly in air, a mile high, and settled, tail down.\par
\tab A hundred yards above the pit, the engines thundered high. Over the hydraulic springs, Terens could feel their shuddering. He grew giddy in his seat.\par
\tab Genro said, \ldblquote Take the whip. Quickly now. Every second is important. The emergency lock will close behind you. It will take them five minutes to wonder why I don\rquote t open the main lock, another five minutes to break in, another five minutes to find you. You have fifteen minutes to get out of the port and into the car.\rdblquote\par
\tab The shuddering ceased and in the thick silence Terens knew they had made contact with Sark.\par
\tab The shifting diamagnetic fields took over. The yacht tipped majestically and slowly moved down upon its side.\par
\tab Genro said, \ldblquote Now!\rdblquote  His uniform was wet with perspiration.\par
\tab Terens, with swimming head, and eyes that all but refused to focus, raised his neuronic whip. .\par
\par
\tab Terens felt the nip of a Sarkite autumn. He had spent years in its harsh seasons until he had almost forgotten the soft eternal June of Florina. Now his days in Civil Service rushed back upon him as though he had never left this world of Squires.\par
\tab Except that now he was a fugitive and branded upon him was the ultimate crime, the murder of a Squire.\par
\tab He was walking in time to the pounding of his heart. Behind him was the ship and in it was Genro, frozen in the agony of the whip. The lock had closed softly behind him, and he was walking down a broad, paved path. There were workmen and mechanics in plenty about him. Each had his own job and his own troubles. They didn\rquote t stop to stare a man in the face. They had no reason to.\par
\tab Had anyone actually seen him emerge from the ship?\par
\tab He told himself no one had, or by now there would have been the clamor of pursuit.\par
\tab He touched his hat briefly. It was still down over his ears, and the little medallion it now carried was smooth to the touch. Genro had said that it would act as identification. The men from Trantor would be watching for just that medallion, glinting in the sun.\par
\tab He could remove it, wander away on his own, find his way to another ship--somehow. He would get away from Sark-- somehow. He would escape--somehow.\par
\tab Too many somehows! In his heart he knew he had come to the final end, and as Genro had said, it was either Trantor or Sark. He hated and feared Trantor, but he knew that in any choice it could not and must not be Sark.\par
\par
\tab\ldblquote You! You there!\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens froze. He looked up in cold panic. The gate was a hundred feet away. If he ran. . . But they wouldn\rquote t allow a running man to get out. It was a thing he dared not do. He must not run.\par
\tab The young woman was looking out the open window of a car such as Terens had never seen, not even during fifteen years on Sark. It gleamed with metal and sparkled with translucent gemmite.\par
\tab She said, \ldblquote Come here.\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens\rquote  legs carried him slowly to the car. Genro had said Trantor\rquote s car would be waiting outside the port. Or had he? And would they send a woman on such an errand? A girl, in fact. A girl with a dark, beautiful face.\par
\tab She said, \ldblquote You arrived on the ship that just landed, didn\rquote t you?\rdblquote\par
\tab He was silent.\par
\tab She became impatient. \ldblquote Come, I saw you leave the ship!\rdblquote  She tapped her polo-glasses. He had seen such glasses before.\par
\tab Terens mumbled, \ldblquote Yes. Yes.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Get in then.\rdblquote\par
\tab She held the door open for him. The car was even more luxurious inside. The seat was soft and it all smelled new and fragrant and the girl was beautiful. \par
\tab She said, \ldblquote Are you a member of the crew?\rdblquote\par
\tab She was testing him, Terens imagined. He said, \ldblquote You know who I am.\rdblquote  He raised his fingers momentarily to the medallion.\par
\tab Without any sound of motive power the car backed and turned.\par
\tab At the gate Terens shrank back into the soft, cool, kyrt-covered upholstery, but there was no need for caution. The girl spoke peremptorily and they passed through.\par
\tab She said, \ldblquote This man is with me. I am Samia of Fife.\rdblquote\par
\tab It took seconds for the tired Terens to hear and understand that. When he lurched tensely forward in his seat the car was traveling along the express lanes at a hundred per.\par
\par
\tab A laborer within the port looked up from where he stood and muttered briefly into his lapel. He entered the building then and returned to his work. His superintendent frowned and made a mental note to talk to Tip about this habit of lingering outside to smoke cigarettes for half an hour at a time.\par
\tab Outside the port one of two men in a ground-car said with annoyance, \ldblquote Got into a car with a girl? What car? What girl?\rdblquote  For all his Sarkite costume, his accent belonged definitely to the Arcturian worlds of the Trantorian Empire.\par
\tab His companion was a Sarkite, well versed in the visicast news releases. When the car in question rolled through the gate and picked up speed as it began to veer off and upward to the express level, he half rose in his seat and cried, \ldblquote It\rquote s the Lady Samia\rquote s car. There isn\rquote t another like it. Good Galaxy, what do we do?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Follow,\rdblquote  said the other briefly.\par
\tab\ldblquote But the Lady Samia--\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote She\rquote s nothing to me. She shouldn\rquote t be anything to you either. Or what are you doing here?\rdblquote\par
\tab Their own car was making the turn, climbing upward onto the broad, nearly empty stretches on which only the speediest of ground travel was permitted.\par
\tab The Sarkite groaned, \ldblquote We can\rquote t catch that car. As soon as she spots us she\rquote ll kick out resistance. That car can make two-fifty.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote She\rquote s staying at a hundred so far,\rdblquote  said the Arcturian.\par
\tab After a while he said, \ldblquote She\rquote s not going to Depsec. That\rquote s for sure.\rdblquote\par
\tab And after another while he said, \ldblquote She\rquote s not going to the Palace of Fife.\rdblquote\par
\tab Still another interval and he said, \ldblquote I\rquote ll be spun in space if I know \i where\i0  she\rquote s going. She\rquote ll be leaving the city again.\rdblquote\par
\tab The Sarkite said, \ldblquote How do we know it\rquote s the Squire-killer that\rquote s in there? Suppose it\rquote s a game to get us away from the post. She\rquote s not trying to shake us and she wouldn\rquote t use a car like that if she didn\rquote t \i want\i0  to be followed. You can\rquote t miss it at two miles.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I know, but Fife wouldn\rquote t send his girl to get us out of the way. A squad of patrollers would have done the job better.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Maybe it isn\rquote t really the Lady in it.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote We\rquote re going to find out, man. She\rquote s slowing. Flash past and stop around a curve!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I want to speak to you,\rdblquote  said the girl.\par
\tab Terens decided it was not the ordinary kind of trap he had first considered it. She \i was\i0  the Lady of Fife. She must be. It did not seem to occur to her that anyone could or ought to interfere with her.\par
\tab She had never looked back to see if she were followed. Three times as they turned he had noted the same car to the rear, keeping its distance, neither closing the gap nor falling behind.\par
\tab It was not just a car. That was certain. It might be Trantor, which would be well. It might be Sark, in which case the Lady would be a decent sort of hostage.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote I\rquote m ready to speak.\rdblquote\par
\tab She said, \ldblquote You were on the ship that brought the native from Florina? The one wanted for all those killings?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I said I was.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Very well. Now I\rquote ve brought you out here so that there\rquote ll be no interference. Was the native questioned during the trip to Sark?\rdblquote\par
\tab Such na\'efvet\'e9, Terens thought, could not be assumed. She really did not know who he was. He said guardedly, \ldblquote Yes.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Were you present at the questioning?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Good. I thought so. Why did you leave the ship, by the way?\rdblquote\par
\tab That, thought Terens, was the question she should have asked first of all.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote I was to bring a special report to--\rdblquote  He hesitated. She seized on the hesitation eagerly. \ldblquote To my father? Don\rquote t worry about that. I\rquote ll protect you completely. I\rquote ll say you came with me at my orders.\rdblquote\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote Very well, my Lady.\rdblquote\par
\tab The words \ldblquote my Lady\rdblquote  struck deeply into his own consciousness. She was a Lady, the greatest in the land, and he was a Florinian. A man who could kill patrollers could learn easily how to kill Squires, and a Squire-killer might, by the same token, look a Lady in the face.\par
\tab He looked at her, his eyes hard and searching. He lifted his head and stared down at her.\par
\tab She was very beautiful.\par
\tab And because she was the greatest Lady in the land, she was unconscious of his regard. She said, \ldblquote I want you to tell me everything that you heard at the questioning. I want to know all that was told to you by the native. It\rquote s very important.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote May I ask why you are interested in the native, my Lady?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You may not,\rdblquote  she said flatly.\par
\tab\ldblquote As you wish, my Lady.\rdblquote\par
\tab He didn\rquote t know what he was going to say. With half his consciousness he was waiting for the pursuing car to catch up. With the other half he was growing more aware of the face and body of the beautiful girl sitting near him.\par
\tab Florinians in the Civil Service and those acting as Townmen were, theoretically, celibates. In actual practice, most evaded that restriction when they could. Terens had done what he dared and what was expedient in that direction. At best, his experiences had never been satisfactory.\par
\tab So it was all the more important that he had never been so near a beautiful girl in a car of such luxuriance under conditions of such isolation.\par
\tab She was waiting for him to speak, dark eyes (such dark eyes) aflame with interest, full red lips parted in anticipation, a figure more beautiful for being set off in beautiful kyrt. She was completely unaware that anyone, \i anyone\i0 , could possibly dare harbor dangerous thought with regard to the Lady of Fife.\par
\tab The half of his consciousness that waited for the pursuers faded out.\par
\tab He suddenly knew that the killing of a Squire was not the ultimate crime after all.\par
\tab He wasn\rquote t quite aware that he moved. He knew only that her small body was in his arms, that it stiffened, that for an instant she cried out, and then he smothered the cry with his lips\'85\par
\tab There were hands on his shoulder and the drift of cool air on his back through the opened door of the car. His fingers groped for his weapon, too late. It was ripped from his hand.\par
\tab Samia gasped wordlessly.\par
\tab The Sarkite said with horror, \ldblquote Did you see what he did?\rdblquote\par
\tab The Arcturian said, \ldblquote Never mind!\rdblquote\par
\tab He put a small black object into his pocket and smoothed the seam shut. \ldblquote Get him,\rdblquote  he said.\par
\tab The Sarkite dragged Terens out of the car with the energy of fury. \ldblquote And she let him,\rdblquote  he muttered. \ldblquote She let him.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Who \i are\i0  you?\rdblquote  cried Samia with sudden energy. \ldblquote Did my father send you?\rdblquote\par
\tab The Arcturian said, \ldblquote No questions, please.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You\rquote re a foreigner,\rdblquote  said Samia angrily.\par
\tab The Sarkite said, \ldblquote By Sark, I ought to bust his head in.\rdblquote  He cocked his fist.\par
\tab\ldblquote Stop it!\rdblquote  said the Arcturian. He seized the Sarkite\rquote s wrist and forced it back.\par
\tab The Sarkite growled sullenly, \ldblquote There are limits. I can take the Squire-killing. I\rquote d like to kill a few myself, but standing by and watching a native do what he did is just about too much for me.\rdblquote\par
\tab Samia said in an unnaturally high-pitched voice, \ldblquote Native?\rdblquote  \par
\tab The Sarkite leaned forward, snatched viciously at Terens\rquote  cap. The Townman paled but did not move. He kept his gaze steadily upon the girl and his sandy hair moved slightly in the breeze.\par
\tab Samia moved helplessly back along the car seat as far as she could and then, with a quick movement, she covered her face with both hands, her skin turning white under the pressure of her fingers.\par
\tab The Sarkite said, \ldblquote What are we going to do with her?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Nothing.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote She saw us; She\rquote ll have the whole planet after us before we\rquote ve gone a mile.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Are you going to kill the Lady of Fife?\rdblquote  asked the Arcturian sarcastically.\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, no. But we can wreck her car. By the time she gets to a radio-phone, we\rquote ll be all right.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Not necessary.\rdblquote  The Arcturian leaned into the car. \ldblquote My Lady, I have only a moment. Can you hear me?\rdblquote\par
\tab She did not move.\par
\tab The Arcturian said, \ldblquote You had better hear me. I am sorry I interrupted you at a tender moment but luckily I have put that moment to use. I acted quickly and was able to record the scene by tri-camera. This is no bluff. I will transmit the negative to a safe place minutes after I leave you and thereafter any interference on your part will force me to be rather nasty. I\rquote m sure you understand me.\rdblquote\par
\tab He turned away. \ldblquote She won\rquote t say anything about this. Not a thing. Come along with me, Townman.\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens followed. He could not look back at the white, pinched face in the car.\par
\tab Whatever might now follow, he had accomplished a miracle. For one moment he had kissed the proudest Lady on Sark, had felt the fleeting touch of her soft, fragrant lips.\par
