\tab\f0 DIPLOMACY has a language and a set of attitudes all its own. Relationships between the representatives of sovereign states, if conducted strictly according to protocol, are stylized and stultifying. The phrase \ldblquote unpleasant consequences\rdblquote  becomes synonymous with war and \ldblquote suitable adjustment\rdblquote  with surrender.\par
\tab When on his own, Abel preferred to abandon diplomatic double-talk. With a tight personal beam connecting himself and Fife, he might merely have been an elderly man talking amiably over a glass of wine.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote You have been hard to reach, Fife.\rdblquote\par
\tab Fife smiled. He seemed at ease and undisturbed. \ldblquote A busy day, Abel.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes. I\rquote ve heard a bit about it.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Steen?\rdblquote  Fife was casual.\par
\tab\ldblquote Partly. Steen\rquote s been with us about seven hours.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I know. My own fault, too. Are you considering turning him over to us?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote m afraid not.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote He\rquote s a criminal.\rdblquote\par
\tab Abel chuckled and turned the goblet in his hand, watching the lazy bubbles. \ldblquote I think we can make out a case for his being a political refugee. Interstellar law will protect him on Trantorian territory.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Will your government back you?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I think it will, Fife. I haven\rquote t been in the foreign service for thirty-seven years without knowing what Trantor will back and what it won\rquote t.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I can have Sark ask for your recall.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What good would that do? I'm a peaceable man with whom you are well acquainted. My successor might be anybody.\rdblquote\par
\tab There was a pause. Fife\rquote s leonine countenance puckered. \ldblquote I think you have a suggestion.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I do. You have a man of ours.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What man of yours?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote A Spatio-analyst. A native of the planet Earth, which, by the way, is part of the Trantorian domain.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Steen told you this?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Among other things.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Has he seen this Earthman?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote He hasn\rquote t said he has.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, he hasn\rquote t. Under the circumstances, I doubt that you can have faith in his word.\rdblquote\par
\tab Abel put down his glass. He clasped his hands loosely in his lap and said, \ldblquote Just the same, I\rquote m sure the Earthman exists. I tell you, Fife, we should get together on this. I have Steen and you have the Earthman. In a sense we\rquote re even. Before you go on with your current plans, before your ultimatum expires and your \i coup d\rquote etat\i0  takes place, why not a conference on the kyrt situation generally?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I don\rquote t see the necessity. What is happening on Sark now is an internal matter entirely. I'm quite willing to guarantee personally that there will be no interference with the kyrt trade regardless of political events here. I think that should end Trantor\rquote s legitimate interests.\rdblquote\par
\tab Abel sipped at his wine, seemed to consider. He said, \ldblquote It seems we have a second political refugee. A curious case. One of your Florinian subjects, by the way. A Townman. Myrlyn Terens, he calls himself.\rdblquote\par
\tab Fife\rquote s eyes blazed suddenly. \ldblquote We half suspected that. By Sark, Abel, there\rquote s a limit to the open interference of Trantor on this planet. The man you have kidnaped is a murderer. You can\rquote t make a political refugee out of him.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, now, do you want the man?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You have a deal in mind? Is that it?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The conference I spoke of.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote For one Florinian murderer. Of course not.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But the manner in which the Townman managed to escape to us is rather curious. You may be interested. . .\rdblquote\par
\par
\tab Junz paced the floor, shaking his head. The night was already well advanced. He would like to be able to sleep but he knew he would require somnin once again.\par
\tab Abel said, \ldblquote I might have had to threaten force, as Steen suggested. That would have been bad. The risks would have been awful, the results uncertain. Yet until the Townman was brought to us I saw no alternative, except of course, a policy of do-nothing.\rdblquote\par
\tab Junz shook his head violently. \ldblquote No. Something had to be done. Yet it amounted to blackmail.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Technically, I suppose so. What would you have had me do?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Exactly what you did. I\rquote m not a hypocrite, Abel. Or I try not to be. I won\rquote t condemn your methods when I intend to make full use of the results. Still, what about the girl?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote She won\rquote t be hurt as long as Fife keeps his bargain.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote m sorry for her. I\rquote ve grown to dislike the Sarkite aristocrats for what they\rquote ve done to Florina, but I can\rquote t help feeling sorry for her.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote As an individual, yes. But the true responsibility lies with Sark itself. Look here, old man, did you ever kiss a girl in a ground-car?\rdblquote\par
\tab The tip of a smile quivered at the corners of Junz\rquote s mouth. \ldblquote Yes.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote So have I, though I have to call upon longer memories than you do, I imagine. My eldest granddaughter is probably engaged in the practice at this moment, I shouldn\rquote t wonder. What is a stolen kiss in a ground-car, anyway, except the expression of the most natural emotion in the Galaxy?\par
\tab\ldblquote Look here, man. We have a girl, admittedly of high social standing, who, through mistake, finds herself in the same car with, let us say, a criminal. He seizes the opportunity to kiss her. It\rquote s on impulse and without her consent. How ought she to feel? How ought her father to feel? Chagrined? Perhaps. Annoyed? Certainly. Angry? Offended? Insulted? All that, yes. But disgraced? No! Disgraced enough to be willing to endanger important affairs of state to avoid exposure? Nonsense.\par
\tab\ldblquote But that\rquote s exactly the situation and it could happen only on Sark. The Lady Samia is guilty of nothing but willfulness and a certain na\'efvet\'e9. She has, I am sure, been kissed before. If she kissed again, if she kissed innumerable times, anyone but a Florinian, nothing would be said. But she \i did\i0  kiss a Florinian.\par
\tab\ldblquote It doesn\rquote t matter that she did not know he was a Florinian. It doesn\rquote t matter that he forced the kiss upon her. To make public the photograph we have of the Lady Samia in the arms of the Florinian would make life unbearable for her and for her father. I saw Fife\rquote s face when he stared at the reproduction. There was no way of telling for certain that the Townman was a Florinian. He was in Sarkite costume with a cap that covered his hair well. He was light-skinned, but that was inconclusive. Still, Fife knew that the rumor would be gladly believed by many who were interested in scandal and sensation and that the picture would be considered incontrovertible proof. And he knew that his political enemies would make the greatest possible capital out of it. You may call it blackmail, Junz, and maybe it is, but it\rquote s a blackmail that would not work on any other planet in the Galaxy. Their own sick social system gave us this weapon and I have no compunction about using it.\rdblquote\par
\tab Junz sighed. \ldblquote What\rquote s the final arrangement?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote We\rquote ll meet at noon tomorrow.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote His ultimatum has been postponed then?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Indefinitely. I will be at his office in person.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Is that a necessary risk?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It\rquote s not much of one. There will be witnesses. And I am anxious to be in the material presence of this Spatio-analyst you have been searching for so long.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote ll attend?\rdblquote  asked Junz anxiously.\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh yes. The Townman as well. We\rquote ll need him to identify the Spatio-analyst. And Steen, of course. All of you will be present by trimensic personification.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Thank you.\rdblquote\par
\tab The Trantorian Ambassador smothered a yawn and blinked at Junz through watering eyes. \ldblquote Now, if you don\rquote t mind, I\rquote ve been awake for two days and a night and I\rquote m afraid my old body can take no more antisomnin. I must sleep.\rdblquote\par
\par
\tab With trimensic personification perfected, important conferences were rarely held face to face. Fife felt strongly an element of actual indecency in the material presence of the old Ambassador. His olive complexion could not be said to have darkened, but its lines were set in silent anger.\par
\tab It had to be silent. He could say nothing. He could only stare sullenly at the men who faced him.\par
\tab Abel! An old dotard in shabby clothes with a million worlds behind him.\par
\tab Junz! A dark-skinned, woolly-haired interferer whose perseverance had precipitated the crisis.\tab Steen! The traitor! Afraid to meet his eyes!\par
\tab The Townman! To look at him was most difficult of all. He was the native who had dishonored his daughter with his touch yet who could remain safe and untouchable behind the walls of the Trantorian Embassy. He would have been glad to grind his teeth and pound his desk if he had been alone. As it was, not a muscle of his face must move though it tore beneath the strain.\par
\tab If Samia had not . . . He dropped that. His own negligence had cultivated her willfulness and he could not blame her for it now. She had not tried to excuse herself or soften her own guilt. She had told him all the truth of her private attempts to play the interstellar spy and how horribly it had ended. She had relied completely, in her shame and bitterness, on his understanding, and she would have that much. She would have that much, if it meant the ruin of the structure he had been building.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote This conference has been forced upon me. I see no point in saying anything. I\rquote m here to listen.\rdblquote\par
\tab Abel said, \ldblquote I believe Steen would like to have his say first.\rdblquote\par
\tab Fife\rquote s eyes filled with contempt that stung Steen.\par
\tab Steen yelled his answer. \ldblquote You made me turn to Trantor, Fife. You violated the principle of autonomy. You couldn\rquote t expect me to stand for that. Really.\rdblquote\par
\tab Fife said nothing and Abel said, not without a little contempt of his own, \ldblquote Get to your point, Steen. You said you had something to say. Say it.\rdblquote\par
\tab Steen\rquote s sallow cheekbones reddened without benefit of rouge. \ldblquote I will, and right now. Of course I don\rquote t claim to be the detective that the Squire of Fife represents himself to be, but I can think. Really! And I\rquote ve \i been\i0  thinking. Fife had a story to tell yesterday, all about a mysterious traitor he called X. I could see it was just a lot of talk so that he could declare an emergency. I wasn\rquote t fooled a minute.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote There\rquote s no X?\rdblquote  asked Fife quietly. \ldblquote Then why did you run? A man who runs needs no other accusation.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Is that so? Really?\rdblquote  cried Steen. \ldblquote Well, I would run out of a burning building even if I had not set the fire myself.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Go on, Steen,\rdblquote  said Abel.\par
\tab Steen licked his lips and turned to a minute consideration of his fingernails. He smoothed them gently as he spoke. \ldblquote But then I thought, why make up that particular story with all its complications and things? It\rquote s not his way. Really! It\rquote s not Fife\rquote s way. I know him. We all know him. He has no imagination at all, Your Excellency. A brute of a man! Almost as bad as Bort.\rdblquote\par
\tab Fife scowled. \ldblquote Is he saying something, Abel, or is he babbling?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Go on, Steen,\rdblquote  said Abel.\par
\tab\ldblquote I will, if you\rquote ll let me talk. My goodness! Whose side are you on? I said to myself (this was after dinner), I said, Why would a man like Fife make up a story like that? There was only one answer. He couldn\rquote t make it up. Not with \i his\i0  mind. So it was true. It must be true. And, of course, patrollers \i had\i0  been killed, though Fife is quite capable of arranging to have that happen.\rdblquote\par
\tab Fife shrugged his shoulders.\par
\tab Steen drove on. \ldblquote Only who is X? It isn\rquote t I. Really! I know it isn\rquote t I! And I\rquote ll admit it could only have been a Great Squire. But what Great Squire knew most about it, anyway? What Great Squire has been trying to use the story of the Spatio-analyst for a year now to frighten the others into some sort of what he calls \lquote united effort\rquote  and what I call surrender to a Fife dictatorship?\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote ll tell you who X is.\rdblquote  Steen stood up, the top of his head brushing the edge of the receptor-cube and flattening as the uppermost inch sliced off into nothingness. He pointed a trembling finger. \ldblquote\i He\rquote s\i0  X. The Squire of Fife. He found this Spatio-analyst. He put him out of the way, when he saw the rest of us weren\rquote t impressed with his silly remarks at our first conference, and then he brought him out again after he had already arranged a military coup.\rdblquote\par
\tab Fife turned wearily to Abel. \ldblquote Is he through? If so, remove him. He is an unbearable offense to any decent man.\rdblquote\par
\tab Abel said, \ldblquote Have you any comment to make on what he says?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Of course not. It isn\rquote t worth comment. The man is desperate. He\rquote ll say anything.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You can\rquote t just brush it off, Fife,\rdblquote  called Steen. He looked about at the rest. His eyes narrowed and the skin at his nostrils was white with tension. He remained standing. \ldblquote Listen. He said his investigators found records in a doctor\rquote s office. He said the doctor had died by accident after diagnosing the Spatio-analyst as the victim of psycho-probing. He said it was murder by X to keep the identity of the Spatio-analyst secret. That\rquote s what he said. Ask him. Ask him if that isn\rquote t what he said.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And if I did?\rdblquote  asked Fife.\par
\tab\ldblquote Then ask him how he could get the records from the office of a doctor who was dead and buried for months unless he had them all along. Really!\rdblquote\par
\tab Fife said, \ldblquote This is foolish. We can waste time indefinitely this way. Another doctor took over the dead man\rquote s practice and his records as well. Do any of you think medical records are destroyed along with a physician?\rdblquote\par
\tab Abel said, \ldblquote No, of course not.\rdblquote\par
\tab Steen stuttered, then sat down.\par
\tab Fife said, \ldblquote What\rquote s next? Have any of you more to say? More accusations? More anything?\rdblquote  His voice was low. Bitterness showed through.\par
\tab Abel said, \ldblquote Why, that was Steen\rquote s say, and we\rquote ll let it pass. Now Junz and I, we\rquote re here on another kind of business. We would like to see the Spatio-analyst.\rdblquote\par
\tab Fife\rquote s hands had been resting upon the desk top. They lifted now and came down to clutch the edge of the desk. His black eyebrows drew together.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote We have in custody a man of subnormal mentality who claims to be a Spatio-analyst. I\rquote ll have him brought in!\rdblquote\par
\par
\tab Valona March had never, never in her life dreamed such impossibilities could exist. For over a day now, ever since she had landed on this planet of Sark, there had been a touch of wonder about everything. Even the prison cells in which she and Rik had been separately placed seemed to have an unreal quality of magnificence about them. Water came out of a hole in a pipe when you pressed a button. Heat came out of the wall, although the air outside had been colder than she had thought air could possibly get. And everyone who spoke to her wore such beautiful clothes.\par
\tab She had been in rooms in which were all sorts of things she had never seen before. This one now was larger than any yet but it was almost bare. It had more people in it, though. There was a stern-looking man behind a desk, and a much older, very wrinkled man in a chair, and three others.\par
\tab One was the Townman!\par
\tab She jumped up and ran to him. \ldblquote Townman! Townman!\rdblquote\par
\tab But he wasn\rquote t there!\par
\tab He had gotten up and waved at her. \ldblquote Stay back, Lona. Stay back!\rdblquote\par
\tab And she passed right through him. She had reached out to seize his sleeve, he moved it away. She lunged, half stumbling, and passed right through him. For a moment the breath went out of her body. The Townman had turned, was facing her again, but she could only stare down at her legs.\par
\tab Both of them were thrusting through the heavy arm of the chair in which the Townman had been sitting. She could see it plainly, in all its color and solidity. It encircled her legs but she did not feel it. She put out a trembling hand and her fingers sank an inch deep into upholstery they could not feel either. Her fingers remained visible.\par
\tab She shrieked and fell, her last sensation being that of the Townman\rquote s arms reaching automatically for her and herself f ailing through their circle as though they were pieces of flesh-tinted air.\par
\tab She was in a chair again, Rik holding one hand tightly and the old, wrinkled man leaning over her.\par
\tab He was saying, \ldblquote Don\rquote t be frightened, my dear. It\rquote s just a picture. A photograph, you know.\rdblquote\par
\tab Valona looked about. The Townman was still sitting there. He wasn\rquote t looking at her.\par
\tab She pointed a finger. \ldblquote Isn\rquote t he there?\rdblquote\par
\tab Rik said suddenly, \ldblquote It\rquote s a trimensic personification, Lona. He\rquote s somewhere else, but we can see him from here.\rdblquote\par
\tab Valona shook her head. If Rik said so, it was all right. But she lowered her eyes. She dared not look at people who were there and not there at the same time.\par
\tab Abel said to Rik, \ldblquote So you know what trimensic personification is, young man?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, sir.\rdblquote  It had been a tremendous day for Rik, too, but where Valona was increasingly dazzled, he had found things increasingly familiar and comprehensible.\par
\tab\ldblquote Where did you learn that?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I don\rquote t know. I knew it before--before I forgot.\rdblquote\par
\tab Fife had not moved from his seat behind the desk during the wild plunge of Valona March toward the Townman.\par
\tab He said acidly, \ldblquote I am sorry to have to disturb this meeting by bringing in a hysterical native woman. The so-called Spatio-analyst required her presence.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It\rquote s all right,\rdblquote  said Abel. \ldblquote But I notice that your Florinian of subnormal mentality seems to be acquainted with trimensic personification.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote He has been well drilled, I imagine,\rdblquote  said Fife.\par
\tab Abel said, \ldblquote Has he been questioned since arriving on Sark?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote He certainly has.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote With what result?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No new information.\rdblquote\par
\tab Abel turned to Rik. \ldblquote What\rquote s your name?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Rik is the only name I remember,\rdblquote  said Rik calmly.\par
\tab\ldblquote Do you know anyone here?\rdblquote\par
\tab Rik looked from face to face without fear. He said, \ldblquote Only the Towriman. And Lona, of course.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote This,\rdblquote  said Abel, gesturing toward Fife, \ldblquote is the greatest Squire that ever lived. He owns the whole world. What do you think of him?\rdblquote\par
\tab Rik said boldly, \ldblquote I'm an Earthman. He doesn\rquote t own \i me\i0 .\rdblquote\par
\tab Abel said in an aside to Fife, \ldblquote I don\rquote t think an adult native Florinian could be trained into that sort of defiance.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Even with a psycho-probe?\rdblquote  returned Fife scornfully.\par
\tab\ldblquote Do you know this gentleman?\rdblquote  asked Abel, returning to Rik.\par
\tab\ldblquote No, sir.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote This is Dr. Selim Junz. He\rquote s an important official at the Interstellar Spatio-analytic Bureau.\rdblquote\par
\tab Rik looked at him intently. \ldblquote Then he\rquote d be one of my chiefs. But,\rdblquote  with disappointment, \ldblquote I don\rquote t know him. Or maybe I just don\rquote t remember.\rdblquote\par
\tab Junz shook his head gloomily. \ldblquote I\rquote ve never seen him, Abel.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote That\rquote s something for the record,\rdblquote  muttered Fife.\par
\tab\ldblquote Now listen, Rik,\rdblquote  said Abel. \ldblquote I'm going to tell you a story. I want you to listen with all your mind and think. Think and think! Do you understand me?\rdblquote\par
\tab Rik nodded.\par
\tab Abel talked slowly. His voice was the only sound in the room for long minutes. As he went on, Rik\rquote s eyelids closed and screwed themselves tight shut. His lips drew back, his fists moved up to his chest, and his head bent forward. He had the look of a man in agony.\par
\tab Abel talked on, passing back and forth across the reconstruction of events as they had originally been presented by the Squire of Fife. He talked of the original message of disaster, of its interception, of the meeting between Rik and X, of the psycho-probing, of how Rik had been found and brought up on Florina, of the doctor who diagnosed him and then died, of his returning memory.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote That\rquote s the whole story, Rik. I\rquote ve told you all of it. Does anything sound familiar to you?\rdblquote\par
\tab Slowly, painfully, Rik said, \ldblquote I remember the last parts. You know, the last few days. I remember something further back, too. Maybe it was the doctor, when I first started talking. It\rquote s very dim. . . . But that\rquote s all.\rdblquote\par
\tab Abel said, \ldblquote But you \i do\i0  remember further back. You remember danger to Florina.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes. Yes. That was the first thing I remembered.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Then can\rquote t you remember after that? You landed on Sark and met a man.\rdblquote\par
\tab Rik moaned, \ldblquote I can\rquote t. I can\rquote t remember.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Try! Try!\rdblquote\par
\tab Rik looked up. His white face was wet with perspiration. \ldblquote I remember a word.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What word, Rik?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It doesn\rquote t make sense.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Tell us anyway.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It goes along with a table. Long, long ago. Very dim. I was sitting. I think, maybe, someone else was sitting. Then he was standing, looking down at me. And there\rquote s a word.\rdblquote\par
\tab Abel was patient. \ldblquote What word?\rdblquote\par
\tab Rik clenched his fists and whispered, \ldblquote Fife!\rdblquote\par
\tab Every man but Fife rose to his feet. Steen shrieked, \ldblquote I told you,\rdblquote  and burst into a high-pitched bubbling cackle.\par
