\b SEVENTEEN: The Accuser\par
\b0\f1\tab\par
\tab\par
\tab\f0 Fife said with tightly controlled passion, \ldblquote Let us end this farce.\rdblquote  \par
\tab He had waited before speaking, his eyes hard and his face expressionless, until in sheer anticlimax the rest were forced to take their seats again. Rik had bent his head, eyes screwed painfully shut, probing his own aching mind. Valona pulled him toward herself, trying hard to cradle his head on her shoulder, stroking his cheek softly.\par
\tab Abel said shakily, \ldblquote Why do you say this is a farce?\rdblquote\par
\tab Fife said, \ldblquote Isn\rquote t it? I agreed to this meeting in the first place only because of a particular threat you held over me. I would have refused even so if I had known the conference was intended to be a trial of myself with renegades and murderers acting as both prosecutors and jury.\rdblquote\par
\tab Abel frowned and said with chilling formality, \ldblquote This is not a trial, Squire. Dr. Junz is here in order to recover the person of a member of the I.S.B., as is his right and duty. I am here to protect the interests of Trantor in a troubled time. There is no doubt in my mind that this man, Rik, is the missing Spatio-analyst. We can end this part of the conference immediately if you will agree to turn over the man to Dr. Junz for further examination, including a check of physical characteristics. We would naturally require your further help in finding the guilty psycho-prober and in setting up safeguards against a future repetition of such acts against what is, after all, an interstellar agency which has consistently held itself above regional politics.\rdblquote\par
\tab Fife said, \ldblquote Quite a speech! But the obvious remains obvious and your plans are quite transparent. What would happen if I gave up this man? I rather think that the I.S.B. will manage to find out exactly what it wants to find out. It claims to be an interstellar agency with no regional ties, but it\rquote s a fact, isn\rquote t it, that Trantor contributes two thirds of its annual budget? I doubt that any reasonable observer would consider it really neutral in the Galaxy of today. Its findings with regard to this man will surely suit Trantor\rquote s imperial interests.\par
\tab\ldblquote And what will these findings be? That\rquote s obvious too. The man\rquote s memory will slowly come back. The I.S.B. will issue daily bulletins. Bit by bit he will remember more and more of the necessary details. First my name. Then my appearance. Then my exact words. I will be solemnly declared guilty. Reparations will be required and Trantor will be forced to occupy Sark temporarily, an occupation which will somehow become permanent.\par
\tab\ldblquote There are limits beyond which any blackmail breaks down. Yours, Mr. Ambassador, ends here. If you want this man, have Trantor send a fleet after him.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote There is no question of force,\rdblquote  said Abel. \ldblquote Yet I notice that you have carefully avoided denying the implication in what the Spatio-analyst has last said.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote There isn\rquote t any implication that I need dignify by a denial. He remembers a word, or says he does. What of it?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Doesn\rquote t it mean anything that he does?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Nothing at all. The name Fife is a great one on Sark. Even if we assume the so-called Spatio-analyst is sincere, he had a year\rquote s opportunity to hear the name on Florina. He came to Sark on a ship that carried my daughter, a still better opportunity to have heard the name of Fife. What is more natural than that the name became involved with his trace memories? Of course, he may not be sincere. This man\rquote s bit-by-bit disclosures may be well rehearsed.\rdblquote\par
\tab Abel thought of nothing to say. He looked at the others. Junz was frowning darkly, the fingers of his right hand slowly kneading his chin. Steen was simpering foolishly and muttering to himself. The Florinian Townman stared blankly at his knees.\par
\tab It was Rik who spoke, forcing himself from Valona\rquote s grasp and standing up.\par
\tab\ldblquote Listen,\rdblquote  he said. His pale face was twisted. His eyes mirrored pain.\par
\tab Fife said, \ldblquote Another disclosure, I suppose.\rdblquote\par
\tab Rik said, \ldblquote Listen! We were sitting at a table. The tea was drugged. We had been quarreling. I don\rquote t remember why. Then I couldn\rquote t move. I could only sit there. I couldn\rquote t talk. I could only think, Great Space, rye been drugged. I wanted to shout and scream and run, but I couldn\rquote t. Then the other one, Fife, came. He had been shouting at me. Only now he wasn\rquote t shouting. He didn\rquote t have to. He came around the table. He stood there, towering over me. I couldn\rquote t say anything. I couldn\rquote t do anything. I could only try to turn my eyeballs up toward him.\rdblquote\par
\tab Rik remained standing, silent.\par
\tab Selim Junz said, \ldblquote This other man was Fife?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I remember his name was Fife.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, was he that man?\rdblquote\par
\tab Rik did not turn to look. He said, \ldblquote I can\rquote t remember what he looked like.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Are you sure?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote ve been trying.\rdblquote  He burst out, \ldblquote You don\rquote t know how hard it is. It hurts! It\rquote s like a red-hot needle. Deep! In here!\rdblquote  He put his hands to his head.\par
\tab Junz said softly, \ldblquote I know it\rquote s hard. But you must try. Don\rquote t you see, you must keep on trying. Look at that man! Turn and look at him!\rdblquote\par
\tab Rik twisted toward the Squire of Fife. For a moment he stared, then turned away.\par
\tab Junz said, \ldblquote Can you remember now?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No! No!\rdblquote\par
\tab Fife smiled grimly. \ldblquote Has your man forgotten his lines, or will the story seem more believable if he remembers my face the next time around?\rdblquote\par
\tab Junz said hotly, \ldblquote I have never seen this man before, and I have never spoken to him. There has been no arrangement to frame you and I am tired of your accusations in that direction. I am after the truth only.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Then may I ask him a few questions?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Go ahead.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Thank you, I\rquote m sure, for your kindness. Now you--Rik, or whatever your real name is--\rdblquote\par
\tab He was a Squire, addressing a Florinian.\par
\tab Rik looked up. \ldblquote Yes, sir.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You remember a man approaching you from the other side of the table as you sat there, drugged and helpless.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, sir.\rdblquote\par
\tab\lquote The last thing you remember is this man staring down at you.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, sir.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You stared up at him, or tried to.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, sir.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Sit down.\rdblquote\par
\tab Rik did so.\par
\tab For a moment Fife did nothing. His lipless mouth might have grown tighter, the jaw muscles under the blue-black sheen of the stubble on his cheeks and chin bunched a bit. Then he slid down from his chair.\par
\tab Slid \i down!\i0  It was as though he had gotten down on his knees there behind the desk.\par
\tab But he moved from behind it and was seen plainly to be standing.\par
\tab Junz\rquote s head swam. The man, so statuesque and formidable in his seat, had been converted without warning into a pitiful midget.\par
\tab Fife\rquote s deformed legs moved under him with an effort, carrying the ungainly mass of torso and head forward. His face flushed but his eyes kept their look of arrogance intact. Steen broke into a wild giggle and choked it off when those eyes turned on him. The rest sat in fascinated silence.\par
\tab Rik, wide-eyed, watched him approach.\par
\tab Fife said, \ldblquote Was I the man who approached you around the table?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I can\rquote t remember his face, sir.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I don\rquote t ask you to remember his face. Can you have forgotten this?\rdblquote  His two arms went wide, framing his body. \ldblquote Can you have forgotten my appearance, my walk?\rdblquote\par
\tab Rik said miserably, \ldblquote It seems I shouldn\rquote t, sir, but I don\rquote t know.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But you were sitting, he was standing, and you were looking up at him.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, sir.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote He was looking down at you, \lquote towering\rquote  over you, in fact.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, sir.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You remember that at least? You\rquote re certain of that?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, sir.\rdblquote\par
\tab The two were now face to face.\par
\tab\ldblquote Am I looking down at you?\rdblquote\par
\tab Rik said, \ldblquote No, sir.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Are you looking up at me?\rdblquote\par
\tab Rik, sitting, and Fife, standing, stared levelly at one another, eye to eye.\par
\tab\ldblquote No, sir.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Could I have been the man?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No, sir.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Are you certain?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, sir.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You still say the name you remember is Fife?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I remember that name,\rdblquote  insisted Rik stubbornly.\par
\tab\ldblquote Whoever it was, then, used my name as a disguise?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote He--he must have.\rdblquote\par
\tab Fife turned and with slow dignity struggled back to his desk and climbed into his seat.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote I have never allowed any man to see me standing before this in all my adult life. Is there any reason why this conference should continue?\rdblquote\par
\tab Abel was at once embarrassed and annoyed. So far the conference had backfired badly. At every step Fife had managed to put himself in the right, the others in the wrong. Fife had successfully presented himself as a martyr. He had been forced into conference by Trantorian blackmail, and made the subject of false accusations that had broken down at once.\par
\tab Fife would see to it that his version of the conference flooded the Galaxy and he would not have to depart very far from the truth to make it excellent anti-Trantorian propaganda.\par
\tab Abel would have liked to cut his losses. The psycho-probed Spatio-analyst would be of no use to Trantor now. Any \ldblquote memory\rdblquote  he might have thereafter would be laughed down, made ridiculous, however true it might be. He would be accepted as an instrument of Trantorian imperialism, and a broken instrument at that.\par
\tab But he hesitated, and it was Junz who spoke.\par
\tab Junz said, \ldblquote It seems to me there\rquote s a very good reason for not ending the conference just yet. We have not yet determined exactly who is responsible for the psycho-probing. You have accused the Squire of Steen, and Steen has accused you. Granting that both of you are mistaken and that both are innocent, it still remains true that you each believe one of the Great Squires is guilty. Which one, then?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Does it matter?\rdblquote  asked Fife. \ldblquote As far as you\rquote re concerned, I\rquote m sure it doesn\rquote t. That matter would have been solved by now except for the interference of Trantor and the I.S.B. Eventually I will find the traitor. Remember that the psycho-prober, whoever he is, had the original intention of forcing a monopoly of the kyrt trade into his own hands, so I am not likely to let him escape. Once the psycho-prober is identified and dealt with, your man here will be returned unharmed to you. That is the only offer I can make and it is a very reasonable one.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What will you do with the psycho-prober?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote That is a purely internal matter that does not concern you.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But it does,\rdblquote  Junz said energetically. \ldblquote This is not just a question of the Spatio-analyst. There\rquote s something of greater importance involved and I\rquote m surprised that it hasn\rquote t been mentioned yet. This man Rik wasn\rquote t psycho-probed just because he was a Spatio-analyst.\rdblquote\par
\tab Abel was not sure what Junz\rquote s intentions were, but he threw his weight into the scales. He said blandly, \ldblquote Dr. Junz is referring, of course, to the Spatio-analyst\rquote s original message of danger.\rdblquote\par
\tab Fife shrugged. \ldblquote As far as I know, no one has yet attached any importance to that, including Dr. Junz over the past year. However, your man is here, Doctor. Ask him what it\rquote s all about.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Naturally, he won\rquote t remember,\rdblquote  Junz retorted angrily. \ldblquote The psycho-probe is most effective upon the more intellectual chains of reasoning stored in the mind. The man may never recover the quantitative aspects of his lifework.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Then it\rquote s gone,\rdblquote  said Fife. \ldblquote What can be done about that?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Something very definite. That\rquote s the point. There\rquote s someone else who knows, and that\rquote s the psycho-prober. He may not have been a Spatio-analyst himself; he may not know the precise details. However, he spoke to the man in a state of untouched mind. He will have learned enough to put us far on the right track. Without having learned enough he would not have dared to destroy the source of his information. Still, for the record, \i do\i0  you remember, Rik?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Only that there was danger and that it involved the currents of space,\rdblquote  muttered Rik.\par
\tab Fife said, \ldblquote Even if you find out, what will you have? How reliable are any of the startling theories that sick Spatio-analysts are forever coming up with? Many of them think they know the secrets of the universe when they\rquote re so sick they can barely read their instruments.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It may be that you are right. Are you afraid to let me find out?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I am against starting any morbid rumors that might, whether true or false, affect the kyrt trade. Don\rquote t you agree with me, Abel?\rdblquote\par
\tab Abel squirmed inwardly. Fife was maneuvering himself into the position where any break in kyrt deliveries resulting from his own \i coup\i0  could be blamed on Trantorian maneuvers. But Abel was a good gambler. He raised the stakes calmly and unemotionally.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote I don\rquote t. I suggest you listen to Dr. Junz.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Thanks,\rdblquote  said Junz. \ldblquote Now you have said, Squire Fife, that whoever the psycho-prober was, he must have killed the doctor who examined this man Rik. That implies that the psycho-prober had kept some sort of watch over Rik during his stay on Florina.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote There must be traces of that kind of watching.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You mean you think these natives would know who was watching them.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Why not?\rdblquote\par
\tab Fife said, \ldblquote You are not a Sarkite and so you make mistakes. I assure you that natives keep their places. They don\rquote t approach Squires and if Squires approach them they know enough to keep their eyes on their toes. They would know nothing of being watched.\rdblquote\par
\tab Junz quivered visibly with indignation. The Squires had their despotism so ingrained that they saw nothing wrong or shameful in speaking of it openly.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote Ordinary natives perhaps. But we have a man here who is not an ordinary native. I think he has shown us rather thoroughly that he is not a properly respectful Florinian. So far he has contributed nothing to the discussion and it is time to ask him a few questions.\rdblquote\par
\tab Fife said, \ldblquote That native\rquote s evidence is worthless. In fact, I take the opportunity once more to demand that Trantor surrender him to proper trial by the courts of Sark.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Let me speak to him first.\rdblquote\par
\tab Abel put in mildly, \ldblquote I think it will do no harm to ask him a few questions, Fife. If he proves unco-operative or unreliable, we may consider your request for extradition.\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens, who, till now, had stolidly concentrated on the fingers of his clasped hands, looked up briefly.\par
\tab Junz turned to Terens. He said, \ldblquote Rik has been in your town since he was first found on Florina, hasn\rquote t he?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And you were in town all that time? I mean you weren\rquote t on any extended business trips, were you?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Townmen don\rquote t make business trips. Their business is in their town.\rdblquote\par
\tab "All right. Now relax and don\rquote t get touchy. It would be part of your business to know about any Squire that might come to town, I imagine.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Sure. When they come.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Did they come?\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens shrugged. \ldblquote Once or twice. Pure routine, I assure you. Squires don\rquote t dirty their hands with kyrt. Unprocessed kyrt, that is.\par
\tab\ldblquote Be respectful!\rdblquote  roared Fife.\par
\tab Terens looked at him and said, \ldblquote Can you make me?\rdblquote\par
\tab Abel interrupted smoothly, \ldblquote Let\rquote s keep this between the man and Dr. Junz, Fife. You and I are spectators.\rdblquote\par
\tab Junz felt a glow of pleasure at the Townman\rquote s insolence, but he said, \ldblquote Answer my questions without side comments please, Townman. Now who exactly were the Squires who visited your town this past year?\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens said fiercely, \ldblquote How can I know? I can\rquote t answer that question. Squires are Squires and natives are natives. I may be a Townman but I\rquote m still a native to them. I don\rquote t greet them at the town gates and ask their names.\par
\tab\ldblquote I get a message, that\rquote s all. It\rquote s addressed \lquote Townman.\rquote  It says there\rquote ll be a Squire\rquote s Inspection on such-and-such a day and I\rquote m to make the necessary arrangements. I must then see to it that the mill-workers have on their best clothes, that the mill is cleaned up and working properly, that the kyrt supply is ample, that everyone looks contented and pleased, that the houses have been cleaned and the streets policed, that some dancers are on hand in case the Squires would care to view some amusing native dance, that maybe a few pretty g--\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Never mind that, Townman,\rdblquote  said Junz.\par
\tab\ldblquote\i You\i0  never mind that. I do.\rdblquote\par
\tab After his experiences with the Florinians of the Civil Service, Junz found the Townman as refreshing as a drink of cold water. He made up his mind that what influence the I.S.B. could bring to bear would be used to prevent any surrender of the Townman to the Squires.\par
\tab Terens went on, in calmer tones, \ldblquote Anyway, that\rquote s my part. When they come, I line up with the rest. I don\rquote t know who they are. I don\rquote t speak to them.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Was there any such inspection the week before the City Doctor was killed? I suppose you know what week that happened.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I think I heard about it in the newscasts. I don\rquote t think there was any Squire\rquote s Inspection at that time. I can\rquote t swear to it.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Whom does your land belong to?\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens pulled the corners of his mouth back. \ldblquote To the Squire of Fife.\rdblquote\par
\tab Steen spoke up, breaking into the give-and-take with rather surprising suddenness. \ldblquote Oh, look here. Really! You\rquote re playing into Fife\rquote s hands with this kind of questioning, Dr. Junz. Don\rquote t you see you won\rquote t get anywhere? Really! Do you suppose if Fife were interested in keeping tabs on that creature there that he would go to all the trouble of making trips to Florina to look at him? What are patrollers for? Really!\rdblquote\par
\tab Junz looked flustered. \ldblquote In a case like this, with a world\rquote s economy and maybe its physical safety resting on the contents of one man\rquote s mind, it\rquote s natural that the psycho-prober would not care to leave the guardianship to patrollers.\rdblquote\par
\tab Fife intervened. \ldblquote Even after he had wiped out that mind, to all intents?\rdblquote\par
\tab Abel pushed out his lower lip and frowned. He saw his latest gamble sliding into Fife\rquote s hands with all the rest.\par
\tab Junz tried again, hesitantly. \ldblquote Was there any particular patroller or group of patrollers that was always underfoot?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote d never know. They\rquote re just uniforms to me.\rdblquote\par
\tab Junz turned to Valona with the effect of a sudden pounce. A moment before she had gone a sickly white and her eyes had become wide and stary. Junz had not missed that.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote What about you, girl?\rdblquote\par
\tab But she only shook her head, wordlessly.\par
\tab Abel thought heavily, There\rquote s nothing more to do. It\rquote s all over.\par
\tab But Valona was on her feet, trembling. She said in a husky whisper, \ldblquote I want to say something.\rdblquote\par
\tab Junz said, \ldblquote Go ahead, girl. What is it?\rdblquote\par
\tab Valona talked breathlessly and with fright obvious in every line of her countenance and every nervous twitch of her fingers. She said, \ldblquote I\rquote m just a country girl. Please don\rquote t be angry with me. It\rquote s just that it seems that things can only be one way. Was my Rik so very important? I mean, the way you said?\rdblquote\par
\tab Junz said gently, \ldblquote I think he was very, very important. I think he still is.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Then it must be like you said. Whoever it was who had put him on Florina wouldn\rquote t have dared take his eye away for even a minute hardly. Would he? I mean, suppose Rik was beaten by the mill superintendent or was stoned by the children or got sick and died. He wouldn\rquote t be left helpless in the fields, would he, where he might die before anyone found him? They wouldn\rquote t suppose that it would just be \i luck\i0  that would keep him safe.\rdblquote  She was speaking with an intense fluency now.\par
\tab\ldblquote Go on,\rdblquote  said Junz, watching her.\par
\tab\ldblquote Because there was one person who did watch Rik from the start. He found him in the fields, fixed it so I would take care of him, kept him out of trouble and knew about him every day. He even knew all about the doctor, because I told him. It was he! It was he!\rdblquote\par
\tab With her voice at screaming intensity, her finger pointed rigidly at Myrlyn Terens, Townman.\par
\tab And this time even Fife\rquote s superhuman calm broke and his arms stiffened on his desk, lifting his massive body a full inch off his seat, as his head swiveled quickly toward the Townman.\par
