\tab\par
\tab\f0 IT WAS as though vocal paralysis had gripped them all. Even Rik, with disbelief in his eyes, could only stare woodenly, first at Valona, then at Terens.\par
\tab Then came Steen\rquote s high-pitched laugh and the silence was broken.\par
\tab Steen said, \ldblquote I believe it. Really! I said so all along. I said the native was in Fife\rquote s pay. That shows you the kind of man Fife is. He\rquote d pay a native to--\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote That\rquote s an infernal lie.\rdblquote\par
\tab It wasn\rquote t Fife who spoke, but the Townman. He was on his feet, eyes glistening with passion.\par
\tab Abel, who of them all seemed the least moved, said, \ldblquote What is?\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens stared at him a moment, not comprehending, then said chokingly, \ldblquote What the Squire said. I am in the pay of no Sarkite.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And what the girl said? Is that a lie too?\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens wet his dry lips with the tip of his tongue. \ldblquote No, that\rquote s true. I am the psycho-prober.\rdblquote  He hurried on. \ldblquote Don\rquote t look at me like that, Lona. I didn\rquote t mean to hurt him. I didn\rquote t intend any of what happened.\rdblquote  He sat down again.\par
\tab Fife said, \ldblquote This is a sort of device. I don\rquote t know exactly what you\rquote re planning, Abel, but it\rquote s impossible on the face of it that this criminal could have included this particular crime in his repertoire. It\rquote s definite that only a Great Squire could have had the necessary knowledge and facilities. Or are you anxious to take your man Steen off the hook by arranging for a false confession?\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens, hands tightly clasped, leaned forward in his seat. \ldblquote I don\rquote t take Trantorian money, either.\rdblquote\par
\tab Fife ignored him.\par
\tab Junz was the last to come to himself. For minutes, he could not adjust to the fact that the Townman was not really in the same room with him, that he was somewhere else on the embassy grounds, that he could see him only in image form, no more real actually than was Fife, who was twenty miles away. He wanted to go to the Townman, grip him by the shoulder, speak to him alone, but he couldn\rquote t. He said, \ldblquote There\rquote s no point in arguing before we hear the man. Let\rquote s have the details. If he \i is\i0  the psycho-prober, we need the details badly. If he isn\rquote t, the details he\rquote ll try to give us will prove it.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote If you want to know what happened,\rdblquote  cried Terens, \ldblquote I\rquote ll tell you. Holding it back won\rquote t do me any good any longer. It\rquote s Sark or Trantor after all, so to Space with it. This will at least give me a chance to get one or two things into the open.\rdblquote\par
\tab He pointed at Fife in scorn. \ldblquote There\rquote s a Great Squire. Only a Great Squire, says this Great Squire, can have the knowledge or the facilities to do what the psycho-prober did. He believes it, too. But what does he know? What do any of the Sarkites know?\par
\tab\ldblquote They don\rquote t run the government. Florinians do! The Florinian Civil Service does. They get the papers, they make the papers, they file the papers. And it\rquote s the papers that run Sark. Sure, most of us are too beaten even to whimper, but do you know what we could do if we wanted to, even under the noses of our damned Squires? Well, you see what I\rquote ve done.\par
\tab\ldblquote I was temporarily traffic manager at the spaceport a year ago. Part of my training. It\rquote s in the records. You\rquote ll have to dig a little to find it because the listed traffic manager is a Sarkite. He had the title but I did the actual work. My name would be found in the special section headed Native Personnel. No Sarkite would have dirtied his eyes looking there.\par
\tab\ldblquote When the local I.S.B. sent the Spatio-analyst\rquote s message to the port with a suggestion that we meet the ship with an ambulance, \i I\i0  got the message. I passed on what was safe. This matter of the destruction of Florina was not passed on.\par
\tab\ldblquote I arranged to meet the Spatio-analyst at a small suburban port. I could do that easily. All the wires and strings that ran Sark were at my finger tips. I was in the Civil Service, remember. A Great Squire who wanted to do what I did, couldn\rquote t, unless he ordered some Florinian to do it for him. I could do it without anyone\rquote s help. So much for knowledge and facility.\par
\tab\ldblquote I met the Spatio-analyst, kept him away from both Sark and the I.S.B. I squeezed as much information out of him as I could and set about using that information for Florina and against Sark.\rdblquote\par
\tab Words were forced out of Fife. \ldblquote You sent those first letters?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I sent those first letters, Great Squire,\rdblquote  said Terens calmly. \ldblquote I thought I could force control of enough of the kyrt lands into my own hands to make a deal with Trantor on my terms and drive you off the planet.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You were mad.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Maybe. Anyway, it didn\rquote t work. I had told the Spatio-analyst I was the Squire of Fife. I had to, because he knew that Fife was the biggest man on the planet, and as long as he thought I was Fife, he was willing to talk openly. It made me laugh to realize that he thought Fife was anxious to do whatever was best for Florina.\par
\tab\ldblquote Unfortunately, he was more impatient than I was. He insisted that every day lost was a calamity, while I knew that my dealings with Sark needed time more than anything else. I found it difficult to control him and eventually had to use a psychic probe. I could get one. I had seen it used in hospitals. I knew something about it. Unfortunately, not enough.\par
\tab\ldblquote I set the probe to wipe out the anxiety from the surface layers of his mind. That\rquote s a simple operation. I still don\rquote t know what happened. I think the anxiety must have run deeper, very deep, and the probe automatically followed it, digging out most of the conscious mind along with it. I was left with a mindless thing on my hands     m sorry, Rik.\rdblquote\par
\tab Rik, who had been listening intently, said sadly, \ldblquote You shouldn\rquote t have interfered with me, Townman, but I know how you must have felt.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Terens, \ldblquote you\rquote ve lived on the planet. You know about patrollers and Squires and the difference between Lower City and Upper City.\rdblquote\par
\tab He took up the current of his story again. \ldblquote So there I was with the Spatio-analyst completely helpless. I couldn\rquote t let him be found by anyone who might trace his identity. I couldn\rquote t kill him. I felt sure his memory would return and I would still need his knowledge, to say nothing of the fact that killing him would forfeit the good will of Trantor and the I.S.B., which I would eventually need. Besides, in those days, I was incapable of killing.\par
\tab\ldblquote I arranged to be transferred to Florina as Townman and I took the Spatio-analyst with me on forged papers. I arranged to have him found, I picked Valona to take care of him. There was no danger thereafter except for that one time with the doctor. Then I had to enter the power plants of Upper City. That was not impossible. The engineers were Sarkites but the janitors were Florinian. On Sark I learned enough about power mechanics to know how to short a power line. It took me three days to find the proper time for it. After that, I could murder easily. I never knew, though, that the doctor kept duplicate records in both halves of his office. I wish I had.\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens could see Fife\rquote s chronometer from where he sat. \ldblquote Then, one hundred hours ago--it seems like a hundred years-- Rik began remembering again. Now you have the whole story.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Junz, \ldblquote we have not. What are the details of the Spatio-analyst\rquote s story of planetary destruction?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Do you think I understood the details of what he had to say? It was some sort of--pardon me, Rik--madness.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It wasn\rquote t,\rdblquote  blazed Rik. \ldblquote It couldn\rquote t have been.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The Spatio-analyst had a ship,\rdblquote  said Junz. \ldblquote Where is it?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote On the scrap heap long ago,\rdblquote  said Terens. \ldblquote An order scrapping it was sent out. My superior signed it. A Sarldte never reads papers, of course. It was scrapped without question.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And Rik\rquote s papers? You said he showed you papers!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Surrender that man to us,\rdblquote  said Fife suddenly, \ldblquote and we\rquote ll find out what he knows.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Junz. \ldblquote His first crime was against the I.S.B. He kidnaped and damaged the mind of a Spatio-analyst. He belongs to us.\rdblquote\par
\tab Abel said, \ldblquote Junz is correct.\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens said, \ldblquote Now look here. I don\rquote t say a word without safeguards. I know where Rik\rquote s papers are. They\rquote re where no Sarkite or Trantorian will ever find them. If you want them you\rquote ll have to agree that I\rquote m a political refugee. Whatever I did was out of patriotism, out of a regard for the needs of my planet. A Sarkite or a Trantorian may claim to be patriotic; why not a Florinian as well?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The Ambassador,\rdblquote  said Junz, \ldblquote has said you will be given over to the I.S.B. I assure you that you will not be turned over to Sark. For your treatment of the Spatio-analyst, you will be tried. I cannot guarantee the result, but if you co-operate with us now, it will count in your favor.\rdblquote\par
\tab Terens looked searchingly at Junz. Then he said, \ldblquote I\rquote ll take my chance with you, Doctor. . . . According to the Spatio-analyst, Florina\rquote s sun is in the pre-nova stage.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What!\rdblquote  The exclamation or its equivalent came from all but Valona.\par
\tab\ldblquote It\rquote s about to explode and go boom,\rdblquote  said Terens sardonically. \ldblquote And when that happens all of Florina will go poof, like a mouthful of tobacco smoke.\rdblquote\par
\tab Abel said, \ldblquote I\rquote m no Spatio-analyst, but I have heard that there is no way of predicting when a star will explode.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote That\rquote s true. Until now, anyway. Did Rik explain what made him think so?\rdblquote  asked Junz.\par
\tab\ldblquote I suppose his papers will show that. All I can remember is about the carbon current.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote He kept saying, \lquote The carbon current of space. The carbon current of space.\rquote  That, and the words \lquote catalytic effect.\rquote  There it is.\par
\tab Steen giggled. Fife frowned. Junz stared.\par
\tab Then Junz muttered, \ldblquote Pardon me. I\rquote ll be right back.\rdblquote  He stepped out of the limits of the receptor cube and vanished.\par
\tab He was back in fifteen minutes.\par
\tab Junz looked about in bewilderment when he returned. Only Abel and Fife were present.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote Where--\rdblquote\par
\tab Abel broke in instantly. \ldblquote We have been waiting for you, Dr. Junz. The Spatio-analyst and the girl are on their way to the Embassy. The conference is ended.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Ended! Great Galaxy, we have only begun. I\rquote ve got to explain the possibilities of nova formation.\rdblquote\par
\tab Abel shifted uneasily in his seat. \ldblquote It is not necessary to do that, Doctor.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It is very necessary. It is essential. Give me five minutes.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Let him speak,\rdblquote  said Fife. He was smiling.\par
\tab Junz said, \lquote Take it from the beginning. In the earliest recorded scientific writings of Galactic civilization it was already known that stars obtained their energy from nuclear transformations in their interiors. It was also known that, given what we know about conditions in stellar interiors, two types, and only two types, of nuclear transformations can possibly yield the necessary energy. Both involve the conversion of hydrogen to helium. The first transformation is direct: two hydrogens and two neutrons combine to form one helium nucleus. The second is indirect, with several steps. It ends up with hydrogen becoming helium, but in the intermediate steps, carbon nuclei take part. These carbon nuclei are not used up but are re-formed as the reactions proceed, so that a trifling amount of carbon can be used over and over again, serving to convert a great deal of hydrogen to helium. The carbon acts as a catalyst, in other words. All this has been known back to the days of prehistory, back to the time when the human race was restricted to a single planet, if there ever was such a time.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote If we all know it,\rdblquote  said Fife, \ldblquote I would suggest that you are contributing nothing but a waste of time.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But this is \i all\i0  we know. Whether stars use one or the other, or both, nuclear processes has never been determined. There have always been schools of thought in favor of each of the alternatives. Usually the weight of opinion has been in favor of the direct hydrogen-helium conversion as being the simpler of the two.\par
\tab\ldblquote Now Rik\rquote s theory must be this. The hydrogen-helium direct conversion is the \i normal\i0  source of stellar energy, but under certain conditions the carbon catalysis adds its weight, hastening the process, speeding it up, heating up the star.\par
\tab\ldblquote There are currents in space. You all know that well. Some of these are carbon currents. Stars passing through the currents pick up innumerable atoms. The total mass of atoms attracted, however, is incredibly microscopic in comparison to the star\rquote s weight and does not affect it in any way. \i Except for carbon!\i0  A star that passes through a current containing unusual concentrations of carbon becomes unstable. I don\rquote t know how many years or centuries or millions of years it takes for the carbon atoms to diffuse into the star\rquote s interior, but it probably takes a long time. That means that a carbon current must be wide and a star must intersect it at a small angle. In any case, once the quantity of carbon percolating into the star\rquote s interior passes a certain critical amount, the star\rquote s radiation is suddenly boosted tremendously. The outer layers give way under an unimaginable explosion and you have a nova.\par
\tab\ldblquote Do you see?\rdblquote\par
\tab Junz waited.\par
\tab Fife said, \ldblquote Have you figured all this out in two minutes as a result of some vague phrase the Townman remembered the Spatio-analyst to have said a year ago?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes. Yes. There\rquote s nothing surprising in that. Spatio-analysis is ready for that theory. If Rik had not come up with it, someone else would have shortly. In fact, similar theories have been advanced before, but they were never taken seriously. They were put forward before the techniques of Spatio-analysis were developed and no one was ever able to account for the sudden acquisition of excess carbon by the star in question.\par
\tab\ldblquote But now we know there \i are\i0  carbon currents. We can plot their courses, find out what stars intersected those courses in the past ten thousand years, check that against our records for nova formation and radiation variations. That\rquote s what Rik must have done. Those must have been the calculations and observations he tried to show the Townman. But that\rquote s all beside the immediate point.\par
\tab\ldblquote What must be arranged for now is the immediate beginning of an evacuation of Florina.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I thought it would come to that,\rdblquote  said Fife composedly.\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote m sorry, Junz,\rdblquote  said Abel, \ldblquote but that\rquote s quite impossible.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Why impossible?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote\i When\i0  will Florina\rquote s sun explode?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I don\rquote t know. From Rik\rquote s anxiety a year ago, I\rquote d say we had little time.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But you can\rquote t set a date?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Of course not.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote When will you be able to set a date?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote There\rquote s no way of telling. Even if we get Rik\rquote s calculations, it would all have to be rechecked.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Can you guarantee that the Spatio-analyst\rquote s theory will prove to be correct?\rdblquote\par
\tab Junz frowned. \ldblquote I am personally certain of it, but no scientist can guarantee any theory in advance.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Then it turns out that you want Florina evacuated on mere speculation.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I think the chance of killing the population of a planet is not one that can be taken.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote If Florina were an ordinary planet I would agree with you. But Florina bears the Galactic supply of kyrt. It can\rquote t be done.\rdblquote\par
\tab Junz said angrily, \ldblquote Is that the agreement you came to with Fife while I was gone?\rdblquote\par
\tab Fife intervened. He said, \ldblquote Let me explain, Dr. Junz. The government of Sark would never consent to evacuate Florina, even if the I.S.B. claimed it had proof of this nova theory of yours. Trantor cannot force us because while the Galaxy might support a war against Sark for the purpose of maintaining the kyrt trade, it will never support one for the purpose of ending it.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Exactly,\rdblquote  said Abel. \ldblquote I am afraid our own people would not support us in such a war.\rdblquote\par
\tab Junz found revulsion growing strong within him. A planet full of people meant nothing against the dictates of economic necessity!\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote Listen to me. This is not a matter of one planet, but of a whole Galaxy. There are now twenty full novae originating within the Galaxy every year. In addition, some two thousand stars among the Galaxy\rquote s hundred billion shift their radiation characteristics sufficiently to render uninhabitable any habitable planet they may have. Human beings occupy one million stellar systems in the Galaxy. That means that on an average of once every fifty years some inhabited planet somewhere becomes too\bullet  hot for life. Such cases are a matter of historical record. Every five thousand years some inhabited planet has a fifty-fifty chance of being puffed to gas by a nova.\par
\tab\ldblquote If Trantor does nothing about Florina, if it allows it to vaporize with its people on it, that will serve notice to all the people of the Galaxy that when their own turn comes they may expect no help, if such help is in the way of the economic convenience of a few powerful men. Can you risk that, Abel?\par
\tab\ldblquote On the other hand, help Florina and you will have shown that Trantor puts its responsibility to the people of the Galaxy above the maintenance of mere property rights. Trantor will win good will that it could never win by force.\rdblquote\par
\tab Abel bowed his head. Then he shook it wearily. \ldblquote No, Junz. What you say appeals to me, but it is not practical. I can\rquote t count on emotions as against the assured political effect of any attempt to end the kyrt trade. In fact, I think it might be wise to avoid investigating the theory. The thought that it might be true would do too much harm.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But what if it \i is\i0  true?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote We must work on the assumption that it is not. I take it that when you were gone a few moments ago it was to contact the I.S.B.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No matter. Trantor, I think, will have enough influence to stop their investigations.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote m afraid not. Not these investigations. Gentlemen, we will soon have the secret of cheap kyrt. There will be no kyrt monopoly within a year, whether or not there is a nova.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What do you mean?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The conference is reaching the essential point now, Fife. Kyrt grows only on Florina of all inhabited planets. Its seeds produce ordinary cellulose elsewhere. Florina is probably the only inhabited planet, on a chance basis, that is currently pre-nova, and it has probably been pre-nova since it first entered the carbon current, perhaps thousands of years ago, if the angle of intersection was small. It seems quite probable, then, that kyrt and the prenova stage go together.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Nonsense,\rdblquote  said Fife.\par
\tab\ldblquote Is it? There must be a reason why kyrt is kyrt on Florina and cotton elsewhere. Scientists have tried many ways of artificially producing kyrt elsewhere, but they tried blindly, so they\rquote ve always failed. Now they will know it is due to factors induced in a pre-nova stellar system.\rdblquote\par
\tab Fife said scornfully, \ldblquote They\rquote ve tried duplicating the radiation qualities of Fife\rquote s sun.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote With appropriate arc lights, yes, that duplicated the visible and ultraviolet spectrum only. What about radiation in the infrared and beyond? What about magnetic fields? What about electron emission? What about cosmic-ray effects? I\rquote m not a physical biochemist so there may be factors I know nothing about. But people who are physical biochemists will be looking now, a whole Galaxy of them. Within the year, I assure you, the solution will be found.\par
\tab\ldblquote Economics is on the side of humanity now. The Galaxy wants cheap kyrt, and if they find it or even if they imagine they will shortly find it, they will want Florina evacuated, not only out of humanity, but out of a desire to turn the tables, at long last, on the kyrt-gouging Sarkites.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Bluff!\rdblquote  growled Fife.\par
\tab\ldblquote Do you think so, Abel?\rdblquote  demanded Junz. \ldblquote If you help the Squires, Trantor will be looked on not as the saviors of the kyrt trade but of the kyrt monopoly. Can you chance that?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Can Trantor chance a war?\rdblquote  demanded Fife.\par
\tab\ldblquote War? Nonsense! Squire, in one year your holdings on Florina will be worthless, nova or not. Sell out. Sell out all Florina. Trantor can pay for it.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Buy a planet?\rdblquote  said Abel in dismay.\par
\tab\ldblquote Why not? Trantor has the funds, and its gain in good will among the people of the universe will pay it back a thousandfold. If telling them that you are saving hundreds of millions of lives is not enough, tell them that you will bring them cheap kyrt. That will do it.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote ll think about it,\rdblquote  said Abel.\par
\tab Abel looked at the Squire. Fife\rquote s eyes fell.\par
\tab After a long pause he too said, \ldblquote I\rquote ll think about it.\rdblquote\par
\tab Junz laughed harshly. \ldblquote Don\rquote t think too long. The kyrt story will break quickly enough. Nothing can stop it. After that, neither one of you will have freedom of action. You can each strike a better bargain now.\rdblquote\par
\par
\tab The Townman seemed beaten. \ldblquote It\rquote s really true?\rdblquote  he kept repeating. \ldblquote Really true? No more Florina?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It\rquote s true,\rdblquote  said Junz.\par
\tab Terens spread his arms, let them fall against his side. \ldblquote If you want the papers I got from Rik, they\rquote re filed among vital statistic files in my home town. I picked the dead files, records a century back and more. No one would ever look there for any reason.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Look,\rdblquote  said Junz, \ldblquote I\rquote m sure we can make an agreement with the I.S.B. We\rquote ll need a man on Florina, one who knows the Florinian people, who can tell us how to explain the facts to them, how best to organize the evacuation, how to pick the most suitable planets of refuge. Will you help us?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And beat the game that way, you mean? Get away with murder? Why not?\rdblquote  There were sudden tears in the Townman\rquote s eyes. \ldblquote But I lose anyway. I will have no world, no home. We all lose. The Florinians lose their world, the Sarkites lose their wealth, the Trantorians their chance to get that wealth. There are no winners at all.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Unless,\rdblquote  said Junz gently, \ldblquote you realize that in the new Galaxy--a Galaxy safe from the threat of stellar instability, a Galaxy with kyrt available to all, and a Galaxy in which political unification will be so much closer--there will be winners after all. One quadrillion winners The people of the Galaxy, \i they\i0  are the victors.\rdblquote\par
