\tab\f0\ldblquote Rik! Rik!\rdblquote  Selim Junz hurried across the port grounds toward the ship, hands outstretched. \ldblquote And Lona! I\rquote d never have recognized either of you. How are you? How are you?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote As well as we could wish. Our letter reached you, I see,\rdblquote  said Rik.\par
\tab\ldblquote Of course. Tell me, what do you think of it all?\rdblquote  They were walking back together, toward Junz\rquote s offices.\par
\tab Valona said sadly, \ldblquote We visited our old town this morning. The fields are so empty.\rdblquote  Her clothing was now that of a woman of the Empire, rather than that of a peasant of Florina.\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, it must be dreary for a person who has lived here. It grows dreary even for me, but I will stay as long as I can. The radiation recordings of Florina\rquote s sun are of tremendous theoretical interest.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote So much evacuation in less than a year! It speaks for excellent organization.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote We\rquote re doing our best, Rik. Oh, I think I should be calling you by your real name.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Please don\rquote t. I\rquote ll never be used to it. I\rquote m Rik. That\rquote s still the only name I remember.\rdblquote\par
\tab Junz said, \ldblquote Have you decided whether you\rquote re going to return to Spatio-analysis?\rdblquote\par
\tab Rik shook his head. \ldblquote I\rquote ve decided, but the decision is, no. I\rquote ll never remember enough. That part\rquote s gone forever. It doesn\rquote t bother me, though. I\rquote ll be returning to Earth. . . . By the way, I rather hoped I\rquote d see the Townman.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I think not. He decided to go off today. I think he\rquote d rather not see you. He feels guilty, I think. You have no grudge against him?\rdblquote\par
\tab Rik said, \ldblquote No. He meant well, and he changed my life in many ways for the better. For one thing, I met Lana.\rdblquote  His arm went about her shoulder.\par
\tab Valona looked at him and smiled.\par
\tab\ldblquote Besides,\rdblquote  Rik went on, \ldblquote he cured me of something. I\rquote ve found out why I was a Spatio-analyst. I know why nearly a third of all Spatio-analysts are recruited from the one planet, Earth. Anyone living on a radioactive world is bound to grow up in fear and insecurity. A misstep can mean death and our planet\rquote s own surface is the greatest enemy we have.\par
\tab\ldblquote That makes for a sort of anxiety bred into us, Dr. Junz, a fear of planets. We\rquote re only happy in space; that\rquote s the only place we can feel safe.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And you don\rquote t feel that way any longer, Rik?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I certainly don\rquote t. I don\rquote t even remember feeling that way. That\rquote s it, you see. The Townman had set his psychic probe to remove feelings of anxiety and he hadn\rquote t bothered to set the intensity controls. He thought he had a recent, superficial trouble to deal with. Instead there was this deep, ingrained anxiety he knew nothing of. He got rid of all of it. In a sense, it was worth getting rid of it even though so much else went with it. I don\rquote t have to stay in space now. I can go back to Earth. I can work there and Earth needs men. It always will.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You know,\rdblquote  Junz said, \ldblquote why can\rquote t we do for Earth what we\rquote re doing for Florina? There\rquote s no need to bring up Earthmen in such fear and insecurity. The Galaxy is big.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Rik vehemently. \ldblquote It\rquote s a different case. Earth has its past, Dr. Junz. Many people may not believe it, but we of Earth know that Earth was the original planet of the human race.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, perhaps. I can\rquote t say, one way or the other.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It \i was\i0 . It\rquote s a planet that can\rquote t be abandoned; it \i mustn\rquote t\i0  be abandoned. Someday we\rquote ll change it, change its surface back to what it once must have been. Till then--we\rquote re staying.\rdblquote\par
\tab Valona said softly, \ldblquote And I\rquote m an Earthwoman now.\rdblquote\par
\tab Rik was looking out at the horizon. Upper City was as garish as ever, but the people were gone.\par
\tab He said, \ldblquote How many are left on Florina?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote About twenty million,\rdblquote  said Junz. \ldblquote We work slower as we go along. We have to keep our withdrawals balanced. The people that are left must always maintain themselves as an economic unit in the months that are left. Of course, resettlement is in its earliest stages. Most of the evacuees are still in temporary camps on neighboring worlds. There is unavoidable hardship.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote When will the last person leave?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Never, really.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I don\rquote t understand.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The Townman has applied unofficially for permission to remain. It\rquote s been granted, also unofficially. It won\rquote t be a matter of public record.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Remain?\rdblquote  Rik was shocked. \ldblquote But for the sake of all the Galaxy, why?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I didn\rquote t know,\rdblquote  said Junz, \ldblquote but I think you explained it when you talked of Earth. He feels as you do. He says he can\rquote t bear the thought of leaving Florina to die alone.\rdblquote\par
